{"title_page": "2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on social media", "text_new": "{{short description|Impact of COVID-19}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{2019-20 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' has affected the usage of [[social media]] by the world's general population, celebrities, world leaders, and professionals. [[Social networking service|Social networking services]] have been used to spread information, and to find humor and distraction from the pandemic via [[Internet meme]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Facebook struggles with high traffic as world sits at home and takes to social media because of Covid-19 |url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/other/facebook-struggles-with-high-traffic-as-world-sits-at-home-and-takes-to-social-media-because-of-covid-19/ar-BB11Gra4 |website=www.msn.com |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001022/https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/other/facebook-struggles-with-high-traffic-as-world-sits-at-home-and-takes-to-social-media-because-of-covid-19/ar-BB11Gra4 |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Okwodu |first1=Janelle |title=\"We Need Joy to Survive\": Naomi Shimada on How to Mindfully Use Social Media in the Age of Social Distancing |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/naomi-shimada-mixed-feelings-social-media-interview |website=Vogue |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001022/https://www.vogue.com/article/naomi-shimada-mixed-feelings-social-media-interview |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSocial media has seen a sharp increase in use during the pandemic, largely due to [[social distancing]] measures encouraged by many governments. Since many people are asked to remain home, they have turned to social media to maintain their [[Interpersonal relationship|relationship]]s and to access entertainment to pass the time.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vicnews.com/news/covid-19-social-media-use-goes-up-as-country-stays-indoors/|title=COVID-19: Social media use goes up as country stays indoors|date=2020-03-31|website=Victoria News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Moreover, social distancing has forced lifestyle changes for many people, which can put a strain on [[mental health]].<ref name=\":02\" /> Therefore, many online [[counselling]] services that use social media have surfaced and begun to rise in popularity, connecting [[mental health worker]]s with those who need them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.owensoundsuntimes.com/news/local-news/wes-for-youth-online-sees-surge-in-counselling-service-use|title=WES for Youth Online sees surge in counselling service use|first=Rob |last=Gowan |date=2020-04-09|website=Owen Sound Sun Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== Increase in usage ==\n\n=== Messaging and video call services ===\nMultiple social media websites reported a sharp increase in usage after social distancing measures were put into place. Since many people cannot connect with their friends and family in person for the time being, social media has become the main form of communication to maintain these valuable connections. For example, [[Facebook]]'s analytics department reported over 50 per cent increase in overall [[Messaging apps|messaging]] during the last month of March 2020.<ref name=\":02\" /> WhatsApp has also reported a 40 per cent increase in usage.<ref name=\":02\" /> Moreover, the video conferencing platform [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] has seen an enormous user increase since the start of the pandemic<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/zooms-new-users-increasing-costs-focus-is-keeping-the-platform-free.html|title=Zoom's massive surge in new users is increasing costs, but the focus is on keeping video calls reliable|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=2020-04-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nFacebook, Twitter, and YouTube have all increased reliance on [[spam filter]]s because staff members who [[Moderation system|moderate content]] were unable to work.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Coronavirus Disrupts Social Media's First Line of Defense|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-social-media-automated-content-moderation/|url-status=live|journal=Wired|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322000250/https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-social-media-automated-content-moderation/|archive-date=2020-03-22|access-date=2020-03-25|via=www.wired.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Online counselling services ===\nParticularly in countries where the virus was hit hardest, such as China, [[Online counseling|online mental health]] services received a surge in demand. This is because COVID-19 has forced many difficult and unplanned lifestyle changes, which are never easy to adjust to. In China, medical staff has used social media programs like [[WeChat]], [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]], and [[TikTok]] to roll out online mental health education programmes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liu|first=Shuai|last2=Yang|first2=Lulu|last3=Zhang|first3=Chenxi|last4=Xiang|first4=Yu-Tao|last5=Liu|first5=Zhongchun|last6=Hu|first6=Shaohua|last7=Zhang|first7=Bin|date=April 2020|title=Online mental health services in China during the COVID-19 outbreak|journal=The Lancet Psychiatry|language=en|volume=7|issue=4|pages=e17\u2013e18|doi=10.1016/S2215-0366(20)30077-8|pmc=7129099|pmid=32085841}}</ref> In [[Canada]], the provincial government of [[Alberta]] has launched a $53 million COVID-19 mental health response plan, which includes increasing accessibility to phone and online supports with existing helplines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chatnewstoday.ca/2020/04/15/alberta-launches-53m-covid-19-mental-health-response-plan/|title=Alberta launches $53M COVID-19 mental health response plan|last=Brown|first=Chris|website=CHAT News Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In the province of [[Ontario]], the government has provided emergency funding of up to $12 million to expand online and virtual mental health supports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/04/ontario-increasing-mental-health-support-during-covid-19.html|title=Ontario Increasing Mental Health Support During COVID-19|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==== Effect of COVID-19 on mental health ====\nThere is extensive [[psychology]] research proving that connectivity with others develops a sense of belonging and psychosocial wellbeing, which enhances mental health and reduces risk for [[Anxiety disorder|anxiety]] and [[Depression disorder|depression]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Allen|first=Kelly A.|last2=Ryan|first2=Tracii|last3=Gray|first3=DeLeon L.|last4=McInerney|first4=Dennis M.|last5=Waters|first5=Lea|date=July 2014|title=Social Media Use and Social Connectedness in Adolescents: The Positives and the Potential Pitfalls|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0816512214000029/type/journal_article |journal=The Australian Educational and Developmental Psychologist |language=en|volume=31|issue=1|pages=18\u201331|doi=10.1017/edp.2014.2|issn=0816-5122}}</ref>\n\n== Use as entertainment ==\nMany [[Internet meme]]s have been created about the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a31693127/coronavirus-covid-19-memes-tweets-jokes/|title=These Coronavirus Memes Will Make Life Feel A Little Bit Better|last=Nicholson|first=Tom|date=March 19, 2020|website=Esquire|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327034412/https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a31693127/coronavirus-covid-19-memes-tweets-jokes/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6688866/19-covid-19-memes-to-get-you-through-the-weekend/|title=19 COVID-19 memes to get you through the weekend|last=Joyce|first=James|date=March 20, 2020|website=The Canberra Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321224846/https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6688866/19-covid-19-memes-to-get-you-through-the-weekend/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/trending-in-india/coronavirus-modi-announces-janata-curfew-twitter-reacts-with-memes-and-jokes-6323555/|title=Memes, jokes on social media after PM Modi announces 'Janata Curfew' to slow Covid-19 spread|date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321164759/https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/trending-in-india/coronavirus-modi-announces-janata-curfew-twitter-reacts-with-memes-and-jokes-6323555/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> A Facebook group has even been created as a space for young people (predominantly [[Generation Z]]) to share memes they create and find about the pandemic. The group is called \"Zoom Memes for Self Quaranteens,\" playing on pun of the increase in [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] usage and self-quarantining as teenagers, and has over 500,000 members as of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/zoommemes/|title=Zoom Memes for Self Quaranteens|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> The group serves as entertainment for the hundreds of thousands of young people that have been forced to switch to online school, helping them pass the extra time and help cope with the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytargum.com/article/2020/03/humor-in-the-face-of-global-pandemic|title=Humor in the face of coronavirus|website=The Daily Targum}}</ref>\n\nDuring the pandemic many challenges spread across social media, potentially to link individuals to one another and to bring entertainment of the individuals attempts. One such challenge was the #''See10Do10'' which involves the individual doing 10 push-ups and recreating it, others included baby photos, dance challenges, and voting in candy and chocolate [[March madness|March Madness]] bracket voting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/harnessing-social-media-for-the-covid-19-pandemic/|title=Harnessing Social Media for the COVID-19 Pandemic|last=Iwai|first=Yoshiko|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Spreading information==\nSocial media has been used by news outlets, organisations, and the general public to spread both valid information and misinformation about the pandemic.<ref name=\"BMJ1\">{{Cite journal|last=Llewellyn|first=Sue|date=March 25, 2020|title=Covid-19: how to be careful with trust and expertise on social media|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1160|journal=BMJ|volume=368|pages=m1160|doi=10.1136/bmj.m1160|pmid=32213480|via=www.bmj.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zarocostas|first=John|date=2020-02-29|title=How to fight an infodemic|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30461-X/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=395|issue=10225|pages=676|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30461-X|issn=0140-6736|pmid=32113495|pmc=7133615}}</ref> The CDC, WHO, medical journals, and health care organisations have been updating and spreading information across numerous platforms with partnerships with Facebook, [[Google Scholar]] and Twitter. Others such as an attending emergency medicine physician in the New York hospital system have been using their social media accounts to report first hand accounts of working to combat COVID-19.<ref name=\":2\" /> It was reported on 8 April, that COVID-19 conversations around disease states have increased 1,000% around healthcare professionals and 2,500% among consumers based on a social listening study from 1 January to 19 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/marketing/social-listening-survey-finds-hcp-activity-way-up-around-covid-19-and-pharma-looking-for|title=Docs are talking about COVID-19 on social media\u2014and pharma is looking for lessons|last=Syner Bulik|first=Beth|date=April 8, 2020|website=FiercePharma|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nDoctors are also joining groups on social media to spread information about treating the disease<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ama-assn.org/delivering-care/public-health/doctor-uses-reach-social-media-ease-covid-19-pandemic-fears|title=Doctor uses reach of social media to ease COVID-19 pandemic fears|last=Berg|first=Sara|date=February 28, 2020|website=American Medical Association|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> with one group on Facebook, the PMG COVID19 Subgroup on Facebook reporting some 30,000 members worldwide by the end of March. Another group, Physician Moms Group, which was started five years prior to the pandemic had so many people wanting to join the 70,000 strong group that Facebook click-to-join code broke and 10,000 additional doctors waited for it to be fixed. The groups have allowed medical professionals to collaborate with one another, gather information and help direct supplies to hospitals that need them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-24/covid-19-mysteries-yield-to-doctors-new-weapon-crowd-sourcing|title=Doctors Turn to Social Media to Develop Covid-19 Treatments in Real Time|last=Smith|first=Michael|last2=Fay Cortez|first2=Michelle|date=March 24, 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\nMedical professionals have also used social media in an effort to educate the general population about the impact of working in PPE for upwards of twelve hour shifts, utilising a trend that showcased their faces after their shifts and their masks are removed. Many of the individuals who participated had bruises, indents, redness and even bandaids covering blisters formed by the masks sitting tight on their faces for hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5807918/health-care-workers-selfies-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=Healthcare Workers Share Selfies of Exhausted Faces After Hard Days Treating COVID-19 Patients|last=Law|first=Tara|date=March 22, 2020|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Celebrity usage ==\nDuring the pandemic many celebrities took to social media to interact with their fan bases and attempt to alleviate the situation through posts, acts of kindness or trends. Some have had posts swiftly condemned by the public, such as [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] who deleted a tone-deaf [[Instagram]] post about her designer fashion and [[Jared Leto]] who caused anger with his [[Twitter]] post about coming out of a 12-day silent meditation isolation in the desert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/04/01/social-media-shaming-about-coronavirus/|title=Social media shaming is spiking during the coronavirus pandemic, for better or worse|last=Brown|first=Jennifer|date=April 1, 2020|website=The Colorado Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Other celebrities such as [[Ellen DeGeneres]] and [[Gal Gadot]] received kick back for their social media posts, of complaining in about being stuck in her California mansion and gathering all of her celebrity friends to sing [[John Lennon]]'s \"[[Imagine (John Lennon song)|Imagine]]\" respectively.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/04/celebrity-coronavirus-social-media|title=There Is No Good Celebrity Content Right Now|last=Lawson|first=Richard|date=April 1, 2020|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nOther celebrities or their family members used social media to announce their positive diagnosis of the disease such as [[Tom Hanks]] and [[Rita Wilson]], [[Idris Elba]], and [[Daniel Dae Kim]].<ref name=\":0\" /> An Instagram post made by [[K-pop|K-Pop]] Star [[Kim Jae-joong|Kim Jaejoong]] claiming that he had contracted the disease and was in the hospital receiving treatment, was later deleted and framed as an [[April Fools' Day|April Fools' Day]] Prank to raise awareness of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2020/04/01/kim-jaejoong-covid19-april-fools-day-prank-kpop-star/|title=K-Pop Star Kim Jaejoong Says April Fools' Day Prank About COVID-19 Hospitalization Was To Raise Awareness|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|date=April 1, 2020|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nSocial media was used by celebrities to raise awareness for [[Charitable activities related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|charitable action during the pandemic]]. [[Ansel Elgort]] posted an almost full front nude of himself on his Instagram page used the caption to post \"OnlyFans LINK IN BIO\" which directed fans to a [[GoFundMe]] created by actor [[Jeffrey Wright]] to feed frontline workers during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/22/entertainment/ansel-elgort-nude-coronavirus/index.html|title=Ansel Elgort's nude Instagram photo helped raise thousands for coronavirus relief|first=Lisa Respers |last=France|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship==\nIn Turkey, more than 400 people were arrested for posting \"provocative\" messages about the pandemic on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-turkey-idUSKBN21C1SG|title=Turkey rounds up hundreds for social media posts about coronavirus|newspaper=Reuters|date=25 March 2020|via=www.reuters.com|access-date=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325150956/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-turkey-idUSKBN21C1SG|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Chinese social media networks, such as [[WeChat]] have reportedly censored any term related to the pandemic since 31 December 2019, notably with [[Li Wenliang|Dr. Li Wenliang]] being censured by the [[Wuhan]] police for posting about the pandemic in a private group chat.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rogerhuang/2020/03/29/internet-censorship-during-covid-19-is-threat-to-cryptocurrencies-and-liberty/|title=Internet Censorship During COVID-19 Is Threat To Cryptocurrencies And Liberty|last=Huang|first=Roger|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Doctors in China had been told by local authorities to delete posts on social media that appealed for the donation of medical supplies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2020/0207/Chinese-hero-doctor-dies-unleashing-public-fury-at-Beijing|title=Chinese 'hero' doctor dies, unleashing public fury at Beijing|last=McDonald|first=Joe|date=7 February 2020|website=Christian Science Monitor|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[NetBlocks]], a civil society group working for digital rights, cyber security and Internet governance reported strange Internet outages in Wuhan during the pandemic, and the [[Persian language|Farsi]] version of Wikipedia was blocked for 24 hours in Iran. The [[Virtual private network|VPN]] company Surfshark reported about a 50% drop-off of its network in Iran after the pandemic was declared on 13 March by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Documentation and coverage by news outlets==\n''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' has called the coronavirus pandemic \"the first true social-media 'infodemic'\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/615184/the-coronavirus-is-the-first-true-social-media-infodemic/|title=The coronavirus is the first true social-media \"infodemic\"|first=Karen|last=Hao|website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/615368/facebook-twitter-social-media-infodemic-misinformation/|title=Here's how social media can combat the coronavirus 'infodemic'|first=Joan|last=Donovan|website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref> [[National Geographic]] has reported on an increased level of \"fake animal news\" on social media during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/|title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life|date=March 20, 2020|website=Animals}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghen C\u00f4 Vy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |last1=Ouyang |first1=Helen |title=At the Front Lines of Coronavirus, Turning to Social Media |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/well/live/coronavirus-doctors-facebook-twitter-social-media-covid.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 18, 2020|ref=none}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Adam |title=Facebook and Instagram to Limit Coronavirus Misinformation |journal=Entrepreneur |date=31 January 2020 |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/345770 |ref=none}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Carman |first1=Ashley |title=Instagram cracks down on coronavirus AR effects |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21179055/instagram-augmented-reality-effect-coronavirus-covid-19 |work=The Verge |date=March 13, 2020|ref=none}}\n* [https://www.cbsnews.com/video/social-medias-role-in-spreading-coronavirus-misinformation/ Coronavirus misinformation on social media], [[CBS News]]\n* [https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/how-to-spot-fake-coronavirus-news-on-social-media How to spot fake coronavirus news on social media], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on social media}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Social media]]\n[[Category:2019 in internet culture]]\n[[Category:2020 in internet culture]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Impact of COVID-19}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{2019-20 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' has affected the usage of [[social media]] by the world's general population, celebrities, world leaders, and professionals. [[Social networking service|Social networking services]] have been used to spread information, and to find humor and distraction from the pandemic via [[Internet meme]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Facebook struggles with high traffic as world sits at home and takes to social media because of Covid-19 |url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/other/facebook-struggles-with-high-traffic-as-world-sits-at-home-and-takes-to-social-media-because-of-covid-19/ar-BB11Gra4 |website=www.msn.com |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001022/https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/other/facebook-struggles-with-high-traffic-as-world-sits-at-home-and-takes-to-social-media-because-of-covid-19/ar-BB11Gra4 |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Okwodu |first1=Janelle |title=\"We Need Joy to Survive\": Naomi Shimada on How to Mindfully Use Social Media in the Age of Social Distancing |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/naomi-shimada-mixed-feelings-social-media-interview |website=Vogue |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001022/https://www.vogue.com/article/naomi-shimada-mixed-feelings-social-media-interview |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSocial media has seen a sharp increase in use during the pandemic, largely due to [[social distancing]] measures encouraged by many governments. Since many people are asked to remain home, they have turned to social media to maintain their [[relationship]]s and to access entertainment to pass the time.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vicnews.com/news/covid-19-social-media-use-goes-up-as-country-stays-indoors/|title=COVID-19: Social media use goes up as country stays indoors|date=2020-03-31|website=Victoria News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Moreover, social distancing has forced lifestyle changes for many people, which can put a strain on [[mental health]].<ref name=\":02\" /> Therefore, many online [[counselling]] services that use social media have surfaced and begun to rise in popularity, connecting [[mental health worker]]s with those who need them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.owensoundsuntimes.com/news/local-news/wes-for-youth-online-sees-surge-in-counselling-service-use|title=WES for Youth Online sees surge in counselling service use|first=Rob |last=Gowan |date=2020-04-09|website=Owen Sound Sun Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== Increase in usage ==\n\n=== Messaging and video call services ===\nMultiple social media websites reported a sharp increase in usage after social distancing measures were put into place. Since many people cannot connect with their friends and family in person for the time being, social media has become the main form of communication to maintain these valuable connections. For example, [[Facebook]]'s analytics department reported over 50 per cent increase in overall [[Messaging apps|messaging]] during the last month of March 2020.<ref name=\":02\" /> WhatsApp has also reported a 40 per cent increase in usage.<ref name=\":02\" /> Moreover, the video conferencing platform [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] has seen an enormous user increase since the start of the pandemic<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/zooms-new-users-increasing-costs-focus-is-keeping-the-platform-free.html|title=Zoom's massive surge in new users is increasing costs, but the focus is on keeping video calls reliable|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=2020-04-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nFacebook, Twitter, and YouTube have all increased reliance on [[spam filter]]s because staff members who [[Moderation system|moderate content]] were unable to work.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Coronavirus Disrupts Social Media's First Line of Defense|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-social-media-automated-content-moderation/|url-status=live|journal=Wired|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322000250/https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-social-media-automated-content-moderation/|archive-date=2020-03-22|access-date=2020-03-25|via=www.wired.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Online counselling services ===\nParticularly in countries where the virus was hit hardest, such as China, [[Online counseling|online mental health]] services received a surge in demand. This is because COVID-19 has forced many difficult and unplanned lifestyle changes, which are never easy to adjust to. In China, medical staff has used social media programs like [[WeChat]], [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]], and [[TikTok]] to roll out online mental health education programmes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liu|first=Shuai|last2=Yang|first2=Lulu|last3=Zhang|first3=Chenxi|last4=Xiang|first4=Yu-Tao|last5=Liu|first5=Zhongchun|last6=Hu|first6=Shaohua|last7=Zhang|first7=Bin|date=April 2020|title=Online mental health services in China during the COVID-19 outbreak|journal=The Lancet Psychiatry|language=en|volume=7|issue=4|pages=e17\u2013e18|doi=10.1016/S2215-0366(20)30077-8|pmc=7129099|pmid=32085841}}</ref> In [[Canada]], the provincial government of [[Alberta]] has launched a $53 million COVID-19 mental health response plan, which includes increasing accessibility to phone and online supports with existing helplines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chatnewstoday.ca/2020/04/15/alberta-launches-53m-covid-19-mental-health-response-plan/|title=Alberta launches $53M COVID-19 mental health response plan|last=Brown|first=Chris|website=CHAT News Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In the province of [[Ontario]], the government has provided emergency funding of up to $12 million to expand online and virtual mental health supports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/04/ontario-increasing-mental-health-support-during-covid-19.html|title=Ontario Increasing Mental Health Support During COVID-19|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==== Effect of COVID-19 on mental health ====\nThere is extensive [[psychology]] research proving that connectivity with others develops a sense of belonging and psychosocial wellbeing, which enhances mental health and reduces risk for [[Anxiety disorder|anxiety]] and [[Depression disorder|depression]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Allen|first=Kelly A.|last2=Ryan|first2=Tracii|last3=Gray|first3=DeLeon L.|last4=McInerney|first4=Dennis M.|last5=Waters|first5=Lea|date=July 2014|title=Social Media Use and Social Connectedness in Adolescents: The Positives and the Potential Pitfalls|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0816512214000029/type/journal_article |journal=The Australian Educational and Developmental Psychologist |language=en|volume=31|issue=1|pages=18\u201331|doi=10.1017/edp.2014.2|issn=0816-5122}}</ref>\n\n== Use as entertainment ==\nMany [[Internet meme]]s have been created about the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a31693127/coronavirus-covid-19-memes-tweets-jokes/|title=These Coronavirus Memes Will Make Life Feel A Little Bit Better|last=Nicholson|first=Tom|date=March 19, 2020|website=Esquire|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327034412/https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a31693127/coronavirus-covid-19-memes-tweets-jokes/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6688866/19-covid-19-memes-to-get-you-through-the-weekend/|title=19 COVID-19 memes to get you through the weekend|last=Joyce|first=James|date=March 20, 2020|website=The Canberra Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321224846/https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6688866/19-covid-19-memes-to-get-you-through-the-weekend/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/trending-in-india/coronavirus-modi-announces-janata-curfew-twitter-reacts-with-memes-and-jokes-6323555/|title=Memes, jokes on social media after PM Modi announces 'Janata Curfew' to slow Covid-19 spread|date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321164759/https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/trending-in-india/coronavirus-modi-announces-janata-curfew-twitter-reacts-with-memes-and-jokes-6323555/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> A Facebook group has even been created as a space for young people (predominantly [[Generation Z]]) to share memes they create and find about the pandemic. The group is called \"Zoom Memes for Self Quaranteens,\" playing on pun of the increase in [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] usage and self-quarantining as teenagers, and has over 500,000 members as of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/zoommemes/|title=Zoom Memes for Self Quaranteens|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> The group serves as entertainment for the hundreds of thousands of young people that have been forced to switch to online school, helping them pass the extra time and help cope with the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytargum.com/article/2020/03/humor-in-the-face-of-global-pandemic|title=Humor in the face of coronavirus|website=The Daily Targum}}</ref>\n\nDuring the pandemic many challenges spread across social media, potentially to link individuals to one another and to bring entertainment of the individuals attempts. One such challenge was the #''See10Do10'' which involves the individual doing 10 push-ups and recreating it, others included baby photos, dance challenges, and voting in candy and chocolate [[March madness|March Madness]] bracket voting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/harnessing-social-media-for-the-covid-19-pandemic/|title=Harnessing Social Media for the COVID-19 Pandemic|last=Iwai|first=Yoshiko|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Spreading information==\nSocial media has been used by news outlets, organisations, and the general public to spread both valid information and misinformation about the pandemic.<ref name=\"BMJ1\">{{Cite journal|last=Llewellyn|first=Sue|date=March 25, 2020|title=Covid-19: how to be careful with trust and expertise on social media|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1160|journal=BMJ|volume=368|pages=m1160|doi=10.1136/bmj.m1160|pmid=32213480|via=www.bmj.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zarocostas|first=John|date=2020-02-29|title=How to fight an infodemic|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30461-X/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=395|issue=10225|pages=676|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30461-X|issn=0140-6736|pmid=32113495|pmc=7133615}}</ref> The CDC, WHO, medical journals, and health care organisations have been updating and spreading information across numerous platforms with partnerships with Facebook, [[Google Scholar]] and Twitter. Others such as an attending emergency medicine physician in the New York hospital system have been using their social media accounts to report first hand accounts of working to combat COVID-19.<ref name=\":2\" /> It was reported on 8 April, that COVID-19 conversations around disease states have increased 1,000% around healthcare professionals and 2,500% among consumers based on a social listening study from 1 January to 19 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/marketing/social-listening-survey-finds-hcp-activity-way-up-around-covid-19-and-pharma-looking-for|title=Docs are talking about COVID-19 on social media\u2014and pharma is looking for lessons|last=Syner Bulik|first=Beth|date=April 8, 2020|website=FiercePharma|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nDoctors are also joining groups on social media to spread information about treating the disease<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ama-assn.org/delivering-care/public-health/doctor-uses-reach-social-media-ease-covid-19-pandemic-fears|title=Doctor uses reach of social media to ease COVID-19 pandemic fears|last=Berg|first=Sara|date=February 28, 2020|website=American Medical Association|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> with one group on Facebook, the PMG COVID19 Subgroup on Facebook reporting some 30,000 members worldwide by the end of March. Another group, Physician Moms Group, which was started five years prior to the pandemic had so many people wanting to join the 70,000 strong group that Facebook click-to-join code broke and 10,000 additional doctors waited for it to be fixed. The groups have allowed medical professionals to collaborate with one another, gather information and help direct supplies to hospitals that need them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-24/covid-19-mysteries-yield-to-doctors-new-weapon-crowd-sourcing|title=Doctors Turn to Social Media to Develop Covid-19 Treatments in Real Time|last=Smith|first=Michael|last2=Fay Cortez|first2=Michelle|date=March 24, 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\nMedical professionals have also used social media in an effort to educate the general population about the impact of working in PPE for upwards of twelve hour shifts, utilising a trend that showcased their faces after their shifts and their masks are removed. Many of the individuals who participated had bruises, indents, redness and even bandaids covering blisters formed by the masks sitting tight on their faces for hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5807918/health-care-workers-selfies-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=Healthcare Workers Share Selfies of Exhausted Faces After Hard Days Treating COVID-19 Patients|last=Law|first=Tara|date=March 22, 2020|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Celebrity usage ==\nDuring the pandemic many celebrities took to social media to interact with their fan bases and attempt to alleviate the situation through posts, acts of kindness or trends. Some have had posts swiftly condemned by the public, such as [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] who deleted a tone-deaf [[Instagram]] post about her designer fashion and [[Jared Leto]] who caused anger with his [[Twitter]] post about coming out of a 12-day silent meditation isolation in the desert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/04/01/social-media-shaming-about-coronavirus/|title=Social media shaming is spiking during the coronavirus pandemic, for better or worse|last=Brown|first=Jennifer|date=April 1, 2020|website=The Colorado Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Other celebrities such as [[Ellen DeGeneres]] and [[Gal Gadot]] received kick back for their social media posts, of complaining in about being stuck in her California mansion and gathering all of her celebrity friends to sing [[John Lennon]]'s \"[[Imagine (John Lennon song)|Imagine]]\" respectively.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/04/celebrity-coronavirus-social-media|title=There Is No Good Celebrity Content Right Now|last=Lawson|first=Richard|date=April 1, 2020|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nOther celebrities or their family members used social media to announce their positive diagnosis of the disease such as [[Tom Hanks]] and [[Rita Wilson]], [[Idris Elba]], and [[Daniel Dae Kim]].<ref name=\":0\" /> An Instagram post made by [[K-pop|K-Pop]] Star [[Kim Jae-joong|Kim Jaejoong]] claiming that he had contracted the disease and was in the hospital receiving treatment, was later deleted and framed as an [[April Fools' Day|April Fools' Day]] Prank to raise awareness of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2020/04/01/kim-jaejoong-covid19-april-fools-day-prank-kpop-star/|title=K-Pop Star Kim Jaejoong Says April Fools' Day Prank About COVID-19 Hospitalization Was To Raise Awareness|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|date=April 1, 2020|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nSocial media was used by celebrities to raise awareness for [[Charitable activities related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|charitable action during the pandemic]]. [[Ansel Elgort]] posted an almost full front nude of himself on his Instagram page used the caption to post \"OnlyFans LINK IN BIO\" which directed fans to a [[GoFundMe]] created by actor [[Jeffrey Wright]] to feed frontline workers during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/22/entertainment/ansel-elgort-nude-coronavirus/index.html|title=Ansel Elgort's nude Instagram photo helped raise thousands for coronavirus relief|first=Lisa Respers |last=France|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship==\nIn Turkey, more than 400 people were arrested for posting \"provocative\" messages about the pandemic on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-turkey-idUSKBN21C1SG|title=Turkey rounds up hundreds for social media posts about coronavirus|newspaper=Reuters|date=25 March 2020|via=www.reuters.com|access-date=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325150956/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-turkey-idUSKBN21C1SG|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Chinese social media networks, such as [[WeChat]] have reportedly censored any term related to the pandemic since 31 December 2019, notably with [[Li Wenliang|Dr. Li Wenliang]] being censured by the [[Wuhan]] police for posting about the pandemic in a private group chat.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rogerhuang/2020/03/29/internet-censorship-during-covid-19-is-threat-to-cryptocurrencies-and-liberty/|title=Internet Censorship During COVID-19 Is Threat To Cryptocurrencies And Liberty|last=Huang|first=Roger|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Doctors in China had been told by local authorities to delete posts on social media that appealed for the donation of medical supplies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2020/0207/Chinese-hero-doctor-dies-unleashing-public-fury-at-Beijing|title=Chinese 'hero' doctor dies, unleashing public fury at Beijing|last=McDonald|first=Joe|date=7 February 2020|website=Christian Science Monitor|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[NetBlocks]], a civil society group working for digital rights, cyber security and Internet governance reported strange Internet outages in Wuhan during the pandemic, and the [[Persian language|Farsi]] version of Wikipedia was blocked for 24 hours in Iran. The [[Virtual private network|VPN]] company Surfshark reported about a 50% drop-off of its network in Iran after the pandemic was declared on 13 March by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Documentation and coverage by news outlets==\n''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' has called the coronavirus pandemic \"the first true social-media 'infodemic'\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/615184/the-coronavirus-is-the-first-true-social-media-infodemic/|title=The coronavirus is the first true social-media \"infodemic\"|first=Karen|last=Hao|website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/615368/facebook-twitter-social-media-infodemic-misinformation/|title=Here's how social media can combat the coronavirus 'infodemic'|first=Joan|last=Donovan|website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref> [[National Geographic]] has reported on an increased level of \"fake animal news\" on social media during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/|title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life|date=March 20, 2020|website=Animals}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghen C\u00f4 Vy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |last1=Ouyang |first1=Helen |title=At the Front Lines of Coronavirus, Turning to Social Media |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/well/live/coronavirus-doctors-facebook-twitter-social-media-covid.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 18, 2020|ref=none}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Adam |title=Facebook and Instagram to Limit Coronavirus Misinformation |journal=Entrepreneur |date=31 January 2020 |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/345770 |ref=none}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Carman |first1=Ashley |title=Instagram cracks down on coronavirus AR effects |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21179055/instagram-augmented-reality-effect-coronavirus-covid-19 |work=The Verge |date=March 13, 2020|ref=none}}\n* [https://www.cbsnews.com/video/social-medias-role-in-spreading-coronavirus-misinformation/ Coronavirus misinformation on social media], [[CBS News]]\n* [https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/how-to-spot-fake-coronavirus-news-on-social-media How to spot fake coronavirus news on social media], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on social media}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Social media]]\n[[Category:2019 in internet culture]]\n[[Category:2020 in internet culture]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:relationship\u2192Interpersonal relationship", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_social_media"}
{"title_page": "Fernand Ouellet", "text_new": "'''Fernand Ouellet''', [[Order of Canada|OC]], [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] (born 6 November 1926 in [[Lac-Bouchette, Quebec]]), a [[French-Canadian]] author and educator, was educated at [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]] and gained a [[PhD]] in 1965.\n\nOuellet taught at Universit\u00e9 Laval, [[Carleton University]], and the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1961\u20131985, prior to joining the History Department at [[York University]] in 1986.\n\nThroughout his career, he used techniques imported from [[economics]] and [[psychology]] to challenge the foundations of [[Quebec nationalism]]. His contributions to the historiographical debates over the British Conquest and the [[1837 Rebellion]] have been especially controversial. In particular, he drew attention to the role played by women in [[Quebec]] society. More recently, he has accused fellow historians of trying to \"normalize\" Quebec's past, so as to provide a stronger justification of sovereignty.<ref>Ronald Rudin, ''Making History in Twentieth Century Quebec'' (1997)</ref>  In response, French-speaking historians have been hostile to his suggestion that French-Canadians are the agents of their own difficulties. These historians, instead of dwelling on economic shortcomings, have stressed the deep roots of modernity, a position that Ouellet strongly rejected. In a nutshell, Ouellet insisted that Qu\u00e9bec's history offers \"more support for the thesis of backwardness than for that of modernization.\"<ref>1991 statement quoted in Ronald Rudin, \"Ouellet, Fernand.\" in {{cite book|author=Kelly Boyd, ed.|title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing, vol. 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0121vD9STIMC&pg=PA897|year=1999|page=897}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOuellet has received numerous prizes, awards, and honours, including the [[J. B. Tyrrell Historical Medal]] of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] in 1969, the [[Governor General's Award]] for non-fiction in 1977, the [[John A. Macdonald|Sir John A. Macdonald Prize]] of the [[Canadian Historical Association]] in 1977, and others. He is a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]], serving as honorary secretary from 1977 to 1980.\n\nOuellet served as President of the [[Canadian Historical Association]] in 1970, and was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in 1979. He was also the editor of ''Histoire Sociale'' (''Social History'') from 1971 to 1988. Ouellet is the author of several works on the history of nineteenth-century French Canada including ''Histoire \u00e9conomique et sociale du Qu\u00e9bec, 1760\u20131850,'' published 1966, ''Le Bas-Canada, 1791\u20131840,'' and ''Louis Joseph Papineau, un \u00eatre divis\u00e9,'' published 1960.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Rudin, Ronald. \"Ouellet, Fernand.\" in {{cite book|author=Kelly Boyd, ed.|title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing, vol. 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0121vD9STIMC&pg=PA896|year=1999|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=896\u201397}}\n*[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0006016 Fernand Ouellet entry in The Canadian Encyclopedia]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouellet, Fernand}}\n[[Category:Canadian historians]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:York University faculty]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval faculty]]\n\n{{Canada-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Fernand Ouellet''', [[Order of Canada|OC]], [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] (born 6 November 1926 in [[Lac-Bouchette, Quebec]]), a [[French-Canadian]] author and educator, was educated at [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]] and gained a [[PhD]] in 1965.\n\nOuellet taught at Universit\u00e9 Laval, [[Carleton University]], and the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1961\u20131985, prior to joining the History Department at [[York University]] in 1986.\n\nThroughout his career, he used techniques imported from [[economics]] and [[psychology]] to challenge the foundations of [[Quebec nationalism]]. His contributions to the historiographical debates over the British Conquest and the [[1837 Rebellion]] have been especially controversial. In particular, he drew attention to the role played by women in [[Quebec]] society. More recently, he has accused fellow historians of trying to \"normalize\" Quebec's past, so as to provide a stronger justification of sovereignty.<ref>Ronald Rudin, ''Making History in Twentieth Century Quebec'' (1997)</ref>  In response, French-speaking historians have been hostile to his suggestion that French-Canadians are the agents of their own difficulties. These historians, instead of dwelling on economic shortcomings, have stressed the deep roots of modernity, a position that Ouellet strongly rejected. In a nutshell, Ouellet insisted that Qu\u00e9bec's history offers \"more support for the thesis of backwardness than for that of modernization.\"<ref>1991 statement quoted in Ronald Rudin, \"Ouellet, Fernand.\" in {{cite book|author=Kelly Boyd, ed.|title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing, vol. 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0121vD9STIMC&pg=PA897|year=1999|page=8997}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOuellet has received numerous prizes, awards, and honours, including the [[J. B. Tyrrell Historical Medal]] of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] in 1969, the [[Governor General's Award]] for non-fiction in 1977, the [[John A. Macdonald|Sir John A. Macdonald Prize]] of the [[Canadian Historical Association]] in 1977, and others. He is a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]], serving as honorary secretary from 1977 to 1980.\n\nOuellet served as President of the [[Canadian Historical Association]] in 1970, and was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in 1979. He was also the editor of ''Histoire Sociale'' (''Social History'') from 1971 to 1988. Ouellet is the author of several works on the history of nineteenth-century French Canada including ''Histoire \u00e9conomique et sociale du Qu\u00e9bec, 1760\u20131850,'' published 1966, ''Le Bas-Canada, 1791\u20131840,'' and ''Louis Joseph Papineau, un \u00eatre divis\u00e9,'' published 1960.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Rudin, Ronald. \"Ouellet, Fernand.\" in {{cite book|author=Kelly Boyd, ed.|title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing, vol. 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0121vD9STIMC&pg=PA896|year=1999|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=896\u201397}}\n*[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0006016 Fernand Ouellet entry in The Canadian Encyclopedia]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouellet, Fernand}}\n[[Category:Canadian historians]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:York University faculty]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval faculty]]\n\n{{Canada-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mr Serjeant Buzfuz", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo in page number in citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fernand_Ouellet"}
{"title_page": "World Food Programme", "text_new": "{{short description|Food-assistance branch of the United Nations}}\n{{redirect|WFP}}\n{{Infobox United Nations\n| image         = Emblem of the United Nations.svg\n| image_size    = 120px\n| name         = World Food Programme\n| map        = World Food Programme Logo Simple.svg\n| map_size   = 200\n| map_caption      = The World Food Programme logo\n| type         = [[Intergovernmental organization]], [[Regulatory body]], [[Advisory board]]\n| abbreviation     = WFP\n| leader_title  = Head\n| leader_name         = [[David Beasley]]\n| status       = Active\n| formation  = {{start date and age|1961|12|19|df=yes}}\n| headquarters = [[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n| website      = [http://www1.wfp.org www.wfp.org]\n| parent_organization       = [[United Nations General Assembly]]\n| subsidiaries = \n| footnotes    = {{portal-inline|Politics|size=tiny}}\n}}\nThe '''World Food Programme'''{{efn|[[French language|French]]: '''''Programme alimentaire mondial'''''; [[Italian language|Italian]]: '''''Programma alimentare mondiale'''''; [[Spanish language|Spanish]]: '''''Programa Mundial de Alimentos'''''; [[Arabic]]: '''\u0628\u0631\u0646\u0627\u0645\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0623\u063a\u0630\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a''', ''barnamaj al'aghdhiat alealami''; [[Russian language|Russian]]: '''''\u0412\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430''''', ''Vsemirnaya prodovol'stvennaya programma''; Chinese: '''\u8054\u5408\u56fd\u4e16\u754c\u7cae\u98df\u8ba1\u5212\u7f72''', ''Li\u00e1nh\u00e9gu\u00f3 sh\u00ecji\u00e8 li\u00e1ngsh\u00ed j\u00echu\u00e0 sh\u01d4''}} ('''WFP''') is the [[aid|food-assistance]] branch of the [[United Nations]] and the world's largest [[humanitarian]] organization addressing [[hunger]] and promoting [[food security]].<ref>{{cite web |last= WFP |title= Mission Statement |url= http://www.wfp.org/about/mission-statement |publisher= WFP |accessdate= 2 November 2013}}</ref> According to the WFP, it provides food assistance to an average of 91.4 million people in 83 countries each year.<ref>[http://www1.wfp.org/overview Overview]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2018-11-19</ref> From its headquarters in [[Rome]] and from more than 80 country offices around the world, the WFP works to help people who cannot produce or obtain enough food for themselves and their families. It is a member of the [[United Nations Development Group]] and part of its executive committee.<ref>\n[http://www.undg.org/index.cfm?P=23 Executive Committee] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511150052/http://www.undg.org/index.cfm?P=23 |date=2011-05-11 }}. Undg.org. Retrieved on 2012-01-15\n</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:World Food Programme.jpg|thumb|WFP Headquarters in [[Rome]]]]\n\nWFP was established in 1961<ref>{{cite web |publisher=World Food Program |title=About |url=http://www.wfp.org/about |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> after the 1960 [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO) Conference, when [[George McGovern]], director of the US [[Food for Peace]] Programmes, proposed establishing a multilateral food aid programme. The WFP was formally established in 1963 by the FAO and the [[United Nations General Assembly]] on a three-year experimental basis. In 1965, the programme was extended to a continuing basis.\n\n===Goals and strategies===\n[[File:Armored vehicle from the UN World Food Program.JPG|thumb|A WFP armoured vehicle.]]\nThe WFP strives to eradicate [[hunger]] and [[malnutrition]], with the ultimate goal in mind of eliminating the need for food aid itself.\n\nThe objectives that the WFP hopes to achieve are to:<ref>{{cite web |last=WFP |title=Our Work |url=http://www.wfp.org/our-work |publisher=WFP |accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n# \"Save lives and protect livelihoods in emergencies\"\n# \"Support food security and nutrition and (re)build livelihoods in fragile settings and following emergencies\"\n# \"Reduce risk and enable people, communities and countries to meet their own food and nutrition needs\"\n# \"Reduce under-nutrition and break the inter-generational cycle of hunger\"\n# \"Zero Hunger in 2030\"\n\nWFP food aid is also directed to fight [[micronutrient]] deficiencies, reduce [[child mortality]], improve maternal health, and combat disease, including [[HIV]] and [[AIDS]].  Food-for-work programmes help promote environmental and economic stability and agricultural production.\n\n===Funding===\nThe WFP operations are funded by voluntary donations from governments of the world, corporations and private donors. The organization's administrative costs are only six and half percent\u2014one of the lowest and best among [[aid agency|aid agencies]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} \nFrom 2008-2012, private voluntary donors donated around $500 million.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\nIn 2016, WFP received from donors in total US$5,933,529,247. The USA was the major donor of WFP with 2 billion US$, followed by the European Commission (894 million US$) and Germany (884 million US$).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfp.org/funding/year/2016|title=Contributions to WFP in 2016 - WFP - United Nations World Food Programme - Fighting Hunger Worldwide|website=wfp.org}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe WFP is governed by an executive board which consists of representatives from 36 member states. [[David Beasley]], from [[South Carolina]], [[United States of America|United States]], is the current executive director, appointed jointly by the [[UN Secretary General]] and the director-general of the FAO for a five-year term. He heads the secretariat of the WFP. The [[European Union]] is a permanent observer in the WFP and, as a major donor, participates in the work of its executive board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eeas.europa.eu/delegations/rome/eu_united_nations/work_with_3_un_agencies_rome/index_en.htm|title=European Union|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> \n[[File:GovernorBeasley.JPG|thumb|[[David Beasley]], executive director of the World Food Programme|150px]]\n\nIts vision is a \"world in which every man, woman and child has access at all times to the food needed for an active and healthy life.\"\n\nThe WFP has a staff of about 18,555 people,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfp.org/world-humanitarian-summit/using-technology-leave-no-one-behind|title=Using Technology to Leave No One Behind - WFP - United Nations World Food Programme - Fighting Hunger Worldwide|website=wfp.org}}</ref> the majority of whom work in remote areas.\n\n===Logistics Cluster===\nThe [[Logistics Cluster]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logcluster.org/|publisher=Logistics Cluster|title=Logistics Cluster|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> is an [[Inter-Agency Standing Committee]] (IASC) humanitarian coordination mechanism whose primary role is supporting emergency responses. One of eleven sectoral coordination bodies, it was set by [[United Nations|UN]] [[United Nations General Assembly|General Assembly]] resolution 46/182 in December 1991 and extended in the Humanitarian Reform of 2005, with new elements adopted to improve capacity, predictability, accountability, leadership and partnership.\n\nThe Logistics Cluster provides coordination and information management services to support operational decision-making and improve the predictability, timeliness and efficiency of humanitarian emergency responses. Where necessary, the Logistics Cluster also facilitates access to common [[logistics]] services. Due to its expertise in the field of [[Humanitarian Logistics|humanitarian logistics]], the World Food Programme (WFP) was chosen by the IASC as the lead agency for the Logistics Cluster. WFP hosts the Global Logistics Cluster support team in its headquarters in Rome. WFP also acts as a \u2018provider of last resort\u2019 offering common logistics services, when critical gaps hamper the humanitarian response.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://logcluster.org|title=Logistics Cluster|website=logcluster.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n[[File:Un c-130 food delivery rumbek sudan.jpg|thumb|United Nations [[C-130 Hercules]] transports deliver food for the [[Rumbek]] region of southern [[Sudan]] (2004).]]\n\nIn 2013, the WFP reached 80.9 million people in 75 countries and provided 3.1 million tonnes of food,<ref>[http://publications.wfp.org/en/apr/2013/ The World Food Programme's Achievements in 2013]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref> including nutritionally enriched ready-to-use [[therapeutic food]]s.<ref>[https://www.wfp.org/nutrition/special-nutritional-products Special Nutritional Products]. World Food Programme. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref> 7.8 million malnourished children received special nutritional support in 2013, and 18.6 million children received school meals or take-home rations.\n\nIn 2015, the WFP reached 76.7 million people in 81 countries. In emergencies, more than 50 million people were reached in order to improve their nutrition and food security. School meals were provided to 17.4 million children, helping keep them in school to ensure uninterrupted access to education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.wfp.org/en/annual-report/2015/|title=WFP - Year in Review 2015|website=publications.wfp.org}}</ref>\n\nThe WFP has scaled up its use of cash and vouchers as food assistance tools. Cash or voucher programmes supported 7.9 million people in 2013. In the same year, the WFP purchased food in 91 countries; 86% of that food came from developing countries.<ref>[http://documents.wfp.org/stellent/groups/public/documents/newsroom/wfp261411.jpg All about the World Food Programme]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref>\n\nIn 2017 WTF launched the Building Blocks Program. It aims to distribute money-for-food assistance to Syrian refugees in Jordan. The project uses [[blockchain]] technology to digitize identities and allow refugees to receive food with eye scanning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/610806/inside-the-jordan-refugee-camp-that-runs-on-blockchain/|title=Inside the Jordan refugee camp that runs on blockchain|last=Juskalian|first=Russ|website=MIT Technology Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\n[[File:World Food Programme in Liberia 002.jpg|thumb|The WFP unloads [[humanitarian aid]] at the [[Freeport of Monrovia]] during [[Joint Task Force Liberia]].|left]]\n\nAmong its other activities, the WFP has coordinated the five-year Purchase for Progress (P4P) pilot project. Launched in September 2008, P4P assists [[smallholding]] farmers by offering them opportunities to access agricultural markets and to become competitive players in the marketplace. The project spanned across 20 countries in Africa, Asia, and Latin America and trained 800,000 farmers in improved agricultural production, post-harvest handling, quality assurance, group marketing, agricultural finance, and contracting with the WFP. The project resulted in 366,000 metric tons of food produced and generated more than US$148 million in income for its smallholder farmers.<ref>[http://www.wfp.org/sites/default/files/P4P%20-%20Reflections%20on%20the%20pilot%2C%20February%202015.pdf Purchase for Progress: Reflections on the pilot, February 2015]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref>\n\nThe WFP focuses its food assistance on those who are most vulnerable to hunger, which most frequently means women, children, the sick and the elderly. In fact, part of the response to the 2010 Haiti earthquake consisted of distributing food aid only to women as experience built up over almost five decades of working in emergency situations has demonstrated that giving food only to women helps to ensure that it is spread evenly among all household members. School-feeding and/or take-home ration programmes in 71 countries help students focus on their studies and encourage parents to send their children, especially girls, to school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.wfp.org/api/documents/3f66543adf5c482a95810d57a2b1518b/download/?_ga=2.212632660.1762357695.1495937773-1834641711.1495319110|title=Contributions to WFP: Comparative Figures and Five-Year Aggregate Ranking|last=|first=|date=2020-04-19|website=United Nations World Food Programme|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Emergency Response Classifications===\nThe WFP has a system of classifications known as the Emergency Response Classifications designed for situations that require immediate response.\n\nThis response is activated under the following criteria:\n\n# When human suffering exists and domestic governments cannot respond adequately\n# The United Nations reputation is under scrutiny\n# When there is an obvious need for aid from the WFP\n\nThe Emergency Response Classifications are divided as follows, with emergency intensity increasing with each level:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://documents.wfp.org/stellent/groups/public/documents/resources/wfp264770.pdf|title=WFP Emergency Response Classifications|date=8 May 2014|website=World Food Programme|access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n* '''Level 1''' \u2013 Response is activated. Resources are allocated to prepare for the WFP's local office to respond\n* '''Level 2''' \u2013 A country's resources require regional assistance with an emergency across one or multiple countries/territories\n* '''Level 3 (L3)''' \u2013 The emergency overpowers the WFP's local offices and requires a global response from the entire WFP organisation\n\n====Current L3 emergencies====\n{{asof|April 2020}} the following are classified as L3 emergencies:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/articles/understanding-l3-emergencies/|title=Understanding L3 Emergencies|website=World Food Program USA|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref>\n\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic]] \n* [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] \n* Northeastern [[Nigeria]] \n* The [[Sahel]]\n* [[South Sudan]] \n* [[Syria]]\n* [[Yemen]]\n\n==Official partnerships and initiatives==\nThe WFP coordinates and cooperates with a number of official partners in emergencies and development projects. These partners include national government agencies such as [[DFID]], [[ECHO (European Commission)|ECHO]], [[EuropeAid Development and Cooperation|EuropeAid]], [[USAID]]; UN agencies such as the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD); [[non-governmental organizations]] such as [[Save the Children]], [[Catholic Relief Services]] and [[Norwegian Refugee Council]]; as well as corporate partners such as [[Boston Consulting Group]], [http://www.dsm.com DSM N.V.], and [[Cargill]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wfp.org/partners/private-sector/meet-our-partners |title=WFP's Partners |publisher=World Food Programme |accessdate=2014-07-27}}</ref>\n\n===Grassroots efforts===\nIn 2004, the WFP tasked [[Auburn University]] in [[Auburn, Alabama|Auburn]], [[Alabama]] with heading the first student-led War on Hunger effort, after a 2002 [[Northwestern University]] pilot. Auburn founded the [[Committee of 19]], which has not only led campus and community hunger awareness events but also developed a War on Hunger model for use on campuses across the country.\n\nThe WFP has launched a global advocacy and fundraising event called [[Walk the World]]. On one single day each year, hundreds of thousands of people in every time zone all over the world walk to call for the end of child hunger. In 2005, more than 200,000 people walked in 296 locations. In 2006, there were 760,000 participants in 118 countries all over the world. This event is part of the campaign to achieve the [[Millennium Development Goals]], specifically to halve the number of people who suffer from hunger and poverty by 2015.\n\nA growing number of grassroots global events and celebrations such as [[International Day of Peace]], [[World Party Day]] participants, and [[Peace One Day]] recommend the WFP on radio broadcasts as an immediate reach out action, putting help within reach of anyone with the information that a quarter feeds a child for a day. [[Fill the Cup]] campaign takes just 25 US cents to fill one of the \"red cups\" that the World Food Programme uses to give hungry children a regular school meal of porridge, rice or beans.<ref>[http://www.wfp.org/node/222 Fill the cup: turning hunger into hope for millions of children]. Wfp.org. Retrieved on 2015-04-08.</ref><ref>[http://www.wfp.org/how-to-help How To Help]. Wfp.org. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref><ref>[http://www.grassrootsonline.org/term/human-right-food Grassroots International]. Grassrootsonline.org. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> [[Christina Aguilera]], Drew Barrymore and [[Sean Penn]] are among notable celebrities who endorse the WFP.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wE8GByc0SXE Drew Barrymore on CNN about WFP], YouTube video</ref><ref>[http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera Christina Aguilera \u2013 A Voice for the Hungry | United Nations World Food Programme \u2013 Fighting Hunger Worldwide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104151429/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|date=2013-01-04}}. WFP. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> The British singer [[Sami Yusuf]] joined with the WFP to support the drought-stricken in Horn of Africa<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/news/news-release/singer-sami-yusuf-and-wfp-join-support-drought-stricken-horn-africa|title=Singer Sami Yusuf And WFP Join In Support For Drought-Stricken Horn Of Africa|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> through his personal campaign, LiveFeedAfrica<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livefeedafrica.org/|title=Live Feed: Help the Horn of Africa with Sami Yusuf and WFP|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> and music video, ''Forgotten Promises''.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKV2oeS4vw8|title=Sami Yusuf - Forgotten Promises|date=31 January 2012|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, composer and WFP supporter [[Benson Taylor]], travelled to the [[Bidi Bidi Refugee Settlement]] in [[Uganda]] with the [[WFP]] to raise awareness for [[World Refugee Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/_bensontaylor/status/658646066473078784 |title=United Nations Support |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=2017-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelondoneconomic.com/entertainment/music/composer-benson-taylor-joins-the-united-nations-world-food-programme-in-uganda-to-highlight-world-refugee-day/20/06/|title=Composer Benson Taylor joins the United Nations World Food Programme to highlight World Refugee Day|date=20 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vulturehound.co.uk/2018/06/uk-composer-producer-benson-taylor-joins-the-united-nations-world-food-programme-in-uganda-to-highlight-world-refugee-day/|title=UK Composer & Producer Benson Taylor Joins the United Nations World Food Programme in Uganda to highlight World Refugee Day|first=Michael|last=Dickinson|date=20 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===World Hunger Relief Week===\nIn 2007, the WFP joined with [[Yum! Brands]], the world's largest restaurant company, to launch the first annual World Hunger Relief Week, a global campaign to increase awareness about hunger, engage volunteers, and raise critically needed funds to help the WFP serve the world's areas of greatest need. World Hunger Relief Week 2007 leveraged the power of nearly 35,000 restaurants around the world, sparking a global movement to end hunger and generating an overwhelming outpouring of support from millions of customers, employees, franchisees and their families. Nearly one million Yum!, KFC, Pizza Hut, Taco Bell, Long John Silver's and A&W All American Food employees, franchisees and their families volunteered close to 4 million hours to aid hunger relief efforts in communities worldwide, while helping to raise $16 million throughout the World Hunger Relief Week initiative for the World Food Programme and other hunger relief agencies around the world. The initiative has been repeated every year since.\n\n===World Food Program USA===\nWorld Food Program USA, before 2010 known as Friends of the World Food Program,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfp.org/stories/wfp%E2%80%99s-us-partner-organisation-new-name-new-site-new-online-tools|title=WFP\u2019s USA Partner Organisation: New Name, New Site, New Online Tools|author=UN World Food Programme|date=16 July 2010|language=en}}</ref> works to solve global hunger, building a world where everyone has the food and nutrition needed to lead healthy, productive lives. WFP USA raises support for these efforts in the United States by engaging individuals, organizations and businesses, shaping public policy and generating resources for WFP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wfpusa.org/wfp-usas-mission/|title=Our Mission \u2013 A world without hunger|author=World Food Program USA|work=World Food Program USA|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe current chairman is Randy Russell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/about-us/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|website=World Food Program USA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Previously, the Chairman of the Board of World Food Program USA was Hunter Biden, son of former U.S. Vice President Joe Biden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111203422/http://www.energysecurityforum.org/speakers/186-hunter-biden-s|title=Hunter Biden|date=2019-11-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Joe Biden\u2019s son Hunter ordered to Arkansas court for contempt hearing in paternity case |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/22/hunter-biden-ordered-to-arkansas-court-for-paternity-case.html |accessdate=17 February 2020 |work=CNBC |quote=World Food Program USA Board Chairman Hunter Biden}}</ref> The chairman at inception of the current organization in 2010 was Randall Russell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/WFP_USA_Annual_Report_2010.pdf|title=Nourish to Empover|last=|first=|date=2010|website=World Food Program USA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===WFP Innovation Accelerator===\nThe [http://innovation.wfp.org World Food Programme's Innovation Accelerator], located in Munich, Germany, has operated since 2016 to source, support, test, and scale innovative approaches to address hunger and food insecurity. Innovative ideas may be found from within WFP global staff, entrepreneurs, start-ups, companies and non-governmental organizations, and are invited to apply on a rolling basis, and through annual Innovation Challenges. Short-listed ideas may be invited to Innovation Bootcamps where innovation teams meet with professional facilitators, mentors and experts from a variety of disciplines in order to fine-tune their proposals and pitch their ideas to potential investors, business supports, and WFP operations. Successful innovations may qualify for financial support to develop the innovation, 3-6 month field testing in WFP's global operations, or scale-up support to expand proven concepts for regional or global impact. \n\nThe WFP Innovation Accelerator provides innovation services not only to WFP, but also other United Nations organizations, such as UNFPA, UNICEF, UNHCR; other non-profit or non-governmental organizations such as the [https://www.gatesfoundation.org/ Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation], the [https://humanitariangrandchallenge.org/ Humanitarian Grand Challenge], and [https://www.xprize.org/ XPRIZE]; and has partnered with various private sector companies such as [https://www.cargill.com/ Cargill], [http://www.google.com/ Google], [https://www.bcg.com/ BCG], and others.\n\nSuccessful innovations that came through the WFP Innovation Accelerator include: \n[https://innovation.wfp.org/project/h2grow-hydroponics H2Grow Hydroponics]: to grow food and animal fodder in extreme environments, using no soil and minimal water. \n[https://innovation.wfp.org/project/scope-coda SCOPE CODA]: Personal smartcards are issued to people which replace paper-based health records with digital records, and enable frontline workers track nutritional needs, and make informed decisions with real-time data. \n[https://innovation.wfp.org/project/empact EMPACT]: Digital skills training to prepare conflict-affected youth for the future of work, and enabling them to provide for themselves and their families. \n[https://sharethemeal.org ShareTheMeal]: WFP's first crowdfunding app, ShareTheMeal enables microdonations from mobile phones and its website, based on the estimation that it costs USD $0.50 to provide 1 meal. In December 2019, ShareTheMeal funded over 50 million meals globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insight.wfp.org/50-million-meals-for-families-in-need-b0da26c818b8|title=50 million meals for families in need|last=Programme|first=World Food|date=2020-02-20|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n[[Kenya]]n economist [[James Shikwati]] said in a 2005 interview with ''[[Der Spiegel]]'': \"aid to Africa does more harm than good\".<ref name=\"DS Interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/0,1518,363663,00.html|title=Spiegel Interview with African Economics Expert: \"For God's Sake, Please Stop the Aid!\"|date=3 July 2005|work=Spiegel Online|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref>  According to him, the food aid increases [[corruption]] as local politicians have the opportunity to steal some of the aid to [[bribery|bribe]] voters or to sell the aid in the [[black market]]s killing the [[Subsistence agriculture|local agriculture]].<ref name=\"AP Sell Aid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/9798947|title=Removed: news agency feed article|work=the Guardian|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> He claims that the WFP people as an organization \"are in the absurd situation of, on the one hand, being dedicated to the fight against hunger while, on the other hand, being faced with unemployment were hunger actually eliminated\". He suggests that WFP answers too easily to the calls of the corrupted governments, and supplies too much of food aid leading to reduction of the production of [[local farming|local farmers]] as \"no one can compete with the UN's World Food Programme\".\n\nThe World Food Programme was also criticized by Jos\u00e9 Ciro Mart\u00ednez and Brent Eng in an essay''The Unintended Consequences of Emergency Food Aid: Neutrality, Sovereignty and Politics in the [[Syrian Civil War]], 2012-15''.  In an interview, an employee of the WFP stated: \"Most aid is still subject to strict control measures by the government, who also requests that it be distributed through state approved bodies such as [[Syrian Arab Red Crescent|SARC]]. I believe the government closely oversees if not completely controls these organizations.\" The authors added that food aid given in Syria would go to the military and its men first.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Martinez, Eng|first=Jose, Brent|year=2015|title=\"The Unintended Consequences of Emergency Food Aid: Neutrality, Sovereignty and Politics in the Syrian Civil War, 2012-15.\"|url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/publications/ia/INTA92_1_08_MartinezEng.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==List of executive directors==\nThe following is a chronological list of those who have held the Executive Director of the World Food Programme position:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wfp.org/about/previous-executive-directors | title=Previous WFP Executive Directors | publisher=World Food Programme | accessdate=2012-04-16}}</ref>\n\n#[[Addeke Hendrik Boerma]] (May 1962 \u2013 December 1967)\n# Sushil K. Dev (acting) (January 1968 \u2013 August 1968)\n# Franciso Aquino (July 1968 \u2013 May 1976)\n# Thomas C. M. Robinson (May 1976 \u2013 June 1977 acting; July 1977 \u2013 September 1977)\n# Garson N. Vogel (October 1977 \u2013 April 1981)\n# Bernardo de Azevedo Brito (acting) (May 1981 \u2013 February 1982)\n# Juan Felipe Yriart (acting) ([[:de:Juan Felipe Yriart|de]]) (February 1982 \u2013 April 1982)\n# [[James Ingram (diplomat)|James Ingram]] (April 1982 \u2013 April 1992)\n# [[Catherine Bertini]] (April 1992 \u2013 April 2002)\n# James T. Morris (April 2002 \u2013 April 2007)\n# [[Josette Sheeran]] (April 2007 \u2013 April 2012)\n# [[Ertharin Cousin]] (April 2012\u2013April 2017)\n# [[David Beasley]] (April 2017\u2013 )\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Asia Emergency Response Facility]]\n* [[Fight Hunger]]: Walk the World<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Food Force]], an educational game\n* [[Food security]]\n* [[Walk the World]]\n* [[World Food Council]]\n* [[Logistics Cluster]]\n\n==Notes==\n===Footnotes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|United Nations World Food Program|World Food Programme}}\n* {{official website}} World Food Programme\n\n{{United Nations}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:United Nations Development Group]]\n[[Category:World Food Programme| ]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in society]]\n[[Category:International medical and health organizations]]\n[[Category:Malnutrition organizations]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Executive Directors of the World Food Programme| ]]\n[[Category:Hunger relief organizations]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Rome]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1963]]\n[[Category:Italy and the United Nations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Food-assistance branch of the United Nations}}\n{{redirect|WFP}}\n{{Infobox United Nations\n| image         = Emblem of the United Nations.svg\n| image_size    = 120px\n| name         = World Food Programme\n| map        = World Food Programme Logo Simple.svg\n| map_size   = 200\n| map_caption      = The World Food Programme logo\n| type         = [[Intergovernmental organization]], [[Regulatory body]], [[Advisory board]]\n| abbreviation     = WFP\n| leader_title  = Head\n| leader_name         = [[David Beasley]]\n| status       = Active\n| formation  = {{start date and age|1961|12|19|df=yes}}\n| headquarters = [[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n| website      = [http://www1.wfp.org www.wfp.org]\n| parent_organization       = [[United Nations General Assembly]]\n| subsidiaries = \n| footnotes    = {{portal-inline|Politics|size=tiny}}\n}}\nThe '''World Food Programme'''{{efn|[[French language|French]]: '''''Programme alimentaire mondial'''''; [[Italian language|Italian]]: '''''Programma alimentare mondiale'''''; [[Spanish language|Spanish]]: '''''Programa Mundial de Alimentos'''''; [[Arabic]]: '''\u0628\u0631\u0646\u0627\u0645\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0623\u063a\u0630\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a''', ''barnamaj al'aghdhiat alealami''; [[Russian language|Russian]]: '''''\u0412\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430''''', ''Vsemirnaya prodovol'stvennaya programma''; Chinese: '''\u8054\u5408\u56fd\u4e16\u754c\u7cae\u98df\u8ba1\u5212\u7f72''', ''Li\u00e1nh\u00e9gu\u00f3 sh\u00ecji\u00e8 li\u00e1ngsh\u00ed j\u00echu\u00e0 sh\u01d4''}} ('''WFP''') is the [[aid|food-assistance]] branch of the [[United Nations]] and the world's largest [[humanitarian]] organization addressing [[hunger]] and promoting [[food security]].<ref>{{cite web |last= WFP |title= Mission Statement |url= http://www.wfp.org/about/mission-statement |publisher= WFP |accessdate= 2 November 2013}}</ref> According to the WFP, it provides food assistance to an average of 91.4 million people in 83 countries each year.<ref>[http://www1.wfp.org/overview Overview]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2018-11-19</ref> From its headquarters in [[Rome]] and from more than 80 country offices around the world, the WFP works to help people who cannot produce or obtain enough food for themselves and their families. It is a member of the [[United Nations Development Group]] and part of its executive committee.<ref>\n[http://www.undg.org/index.cfm?P=23 Executive Committee] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511150052/http://www.undg.org/index.cfm?P=23 |date=2011-05-11 }}. Undg.org. Retrieved on 2012-01-15\n</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:World Food Programme.jpg|thumb|WFP Headquarters in [[Rome]]]]\n\nWFP was established in 1961<ref>{{cite web |publisher=World Food Program |title=About |url=http://www.wfp.org/about |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> after the 1960 [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO) Conference, when [[George McGovern]], director of the US [[Food for Peace]] Programmes, proposed establishing a multilateral food aid programme. The WFP was formally established in 1963 by the FAO and the [[United Nations General Assembly]] on a three-year experimental basis. In 1965, the programme was extended to a continuing basis.\n\n===Goals and strategies===\n[[File:Armored vehicle from the UN World Food Program.JPG|thumb|A WFP armoured vehicle.]]\nThe WFP strives to eradicate [[hunger]] and [[malnutrition]], with the ultimate goal in mind of eliminating the need for food aid itself.\n\nThe objectives that the WFP hopes to achieve are to:<ref>{{cite web |last=WFP |title=Our Work |url=http://www.wfp.org/our-work |publisher=WFP |accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n# \"Save lives and protect livelihoods in emergencies\"\n# \"Support food security and nutrition and (re)build livelihoods in fragile settings and following emergencies\"\n# \"Reduce risk and enable people, communities and countries to meet their own food and nutrition needs\"\n# \"Reduce under-nutrition and break the inter-generational cycle of hunger\"\n# \"Zero Hunger in 2030\"\n\nWFP food aid is also directed to fight [[micronutrient]] deficiencies, reduce [[child mortality]], improve maternal health, and combat disease, including [[HIV]] and [[AIDS]].  Food-for-work programmes help promote environmental and economic stability and agricultural production.\n\n===Funding===\nThe WFP operations are funded by voluntary donations from governments of the world, corporations and private donors. The organization's administrative costs are only six and half percent\u2014one of the lowest and best among [[aid agency|aid agencies]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} \nFrom 2008-2012, private voluntary donors donated around $500 million.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\nIn 2016, WFP received from donors in total US$5,933,529,247. The USA was the major donor of WFP with 2 billion US$, followed by the European Commission (894 million US$) and Germany (884 million US$).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfp.org/funding/year/2016|title=Contributions to WFP in 2016 - WFP - United Nations World Food Programme - Fighting Hunger Worldwide|website=wfp.org}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe WFP is governed by an executive board which consists of representatives from 36 member states. [[David Beasley]], from [[South Carolina]], [[United States of America|United States]], is the current executive director, appointed jointly by the [[UN Secretary General]] and the director-general of the FAO for a five-year term. He heads the secretariat of the WFP. The [[European Union]] is a permanent observer in the WFP and, as a major donor, participates in the work of its executive board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eeas.europa.eu/delegations/rome/eu_united_nations/work_with_3_un_agencies_rome/index_en.htm|title=European Union|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> \n[[File:GovernorBeasley.JPG|thumb|[[David Beasley]], executive director of the World Food Programme|150px]]\n\nIts vision is a \"world in which every man, woman and child has access at all times to the food needed for an active and healthy life.\"\n\nThe WFP has a staff of about 18,555 people,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfp.org/world-humanitarian-summit/using-technology-leave-no-one-behind|title=Using Technology to Leave No One Behind - WFP - United Nations World Food Programme - Fighting Hunger Worldwide|website=wfp.org}}</ref> the majority of whom work in remote areas.\n\n===Logistics Cluster===\nThe [[Logistics Cluster]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logcluster.org/|publisher=Logistics Cluster|title=Logistics Cluster|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> is an [[Inter-Agency Standing Committee]] (IASC) humanitarian coordination mechanism whose primary role is supporting emergency responses. One of eleven sectoral coordination bodies, it was set by [[United Nations|UN]] [[United Nations General Assembly|General Assembly]] resolution 46/182 in December 1991 and extended in the Humanitarian Reform of 2005, with new elements adopted to improve capacity, predictability, accountability, leadership and partnership.\n\nThe Logistics Cluster provides coordination and information management services to support operational decision-making and improve the predictability, timeliness and efficiency of humanitarian emergency responses. Where necessary, the Logistics Cluster also facilitates access to common [[logistics]] services. Due to its expertise in the field of [[Humanitarian Logistics|humanitarian logistics]], the World Food Programme (WFP) was chosen by the IASC as the lead agency for the Logistics Cluster. WFP hosts the Global Logistics Cluster support team in its headquarters in Rome. WFP also acts as a \u2018provider of last resort\u2019 offering common logistics services, when critical gaps hamper the humanitarian response.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://logcluster.org|title=Logistics Cluster|website=logcluster.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n[[File:Un c-130 food delivery rumbek sudan.jpg|thumb|United Nations [[C-130 Hercules]] transports deliver food for the [[Rumbek]] region of southern [[Sudan]] (2004).]]\n\nIn 2013, the WFP reached 80.9 million people in 75 countries and provided 3.1 million tonnes of food,<ref>[http://publications.wfp.org/en/apr/2013/ The World Food Programme's Achievements in 2013]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref> including nutritionally enriched ready-to-use [[therapeutic food]]s.<ref>[https://www.wfp.org/nutrition/special-nutritional-products Special Nutritional Products]. World Food Programme. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref> 7.8 million malnourished children received special nutritional support in 2013, and 18.6 million children received school meals or take-home rations.\n\nIn 2015, the WFP reached 76.7 million people in 81 countries. In emergencies, more than 50 million people were reached in order to improve their nutrition and food security. School meals were provided to 17.4 million children, helping keep them in school to ensure uninterrupted access to education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.wfp.org/en/annual-report/2015/|title=WFP - Year in Review 2015|website=publications.wfp.org}}</ref>\n\nThe WFP has scaled up its use of cash and vouchers as food assistance tools. Cash or voucher programmes supported 7.9 million people in 2013. In the same year, the WFP purchased food in 91 countries; 86% of that food came from developing countries.<ref>[http://documents.wfp.org/stellent/groups/public/documents/newsroom/wfp261411.jpg All about the World Food Programme]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref>\n\nIn 2017 WTF launched the Building Blocks Program. It aims to distribute money-for-food assistance to Syrian refugees in Jordan. The project uses [[blockchain]] technology to digitize identities and allow refugees to receive food with eye scanning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/610806/inside-the-jordan-refugee-camp-that-runs-on-blockchain/|title=Inside the Jordan refugee camp that runs on blockchain|last=Juskalian|first=Russ|website=MIT Technology Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\n[[File:World Food Programme in Liberia 002.jpg|thumb|The WFP unloads [[humanitarian aid]] at the [[Freeport of Monrovia]] during [[Joint Task Force Liberia]].|left]]\n\nAmong its other activities, the WFP has coordinated the five-year Purchase for Progress (P4P) pilot project. Launched in September 2008, P4P assists [[smallholding]] farmers by offering them opportunities to access agricultural markets and to become competitive players in the marketplace. The project spanned across 20 countries in Africa, Asia, and Latin America and trained 800,000 farmers in improved agricultural production, post-harvest handling, quality assurance, group marketing, agricultural finance, and contracting with the WFP. The project resulted in 366,000 metric tons of food produced and generated more than US$148 million in income for its smallholder farmers.<ref>[http://www.wfp.org/sites/default/files/P4P%20-%20Reflections%20on%20the%20pilot%2C%20February%202015.pdf Purchase for Progress: Reflections on the pilot, February 2015]. WFP.org. Retrieved 2015-04-08.</ref>\n\nThe WFP focuses its food assistance on those who are most vulnerable to hunger, which most frequently means women, children, the sick and the elderly. In fact, part of the response to the 2010 Haiti earthquake consisted of distributing food aid only to women as experience built up over almost five decades of working in emergency situations has demonstrated that giving food only to women helps to ensure that it is spread evenly among all household members. School-feeding and/or take-home ration programmes in 71 countries help students focus on their studies and encourage parents to send their children, especially girls, to school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.wfp.org/api/documents/3f66543adf5c482a95810d57a2b1518b/download/?_ga=2.212632660.1762357695.1495937773-1834641711.1495319110|title=Contributions to WFP: Comparative Figures and Five-Year Aggregate Ranking|last=|first=|date=2020-04-19|website=United Nations World Food Programme|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Emergency Response Classifications===\nThe WFP has a system of classifications known as the Emergency Response Classifications designed for situations that require immediate response.\n\nThis response is activated under the following criteria:\n\n# When human suffering exists and domestic governments cannot respond adequately\n# The United Nations reputation is under scrutiny\n# When there is an obvious need for aid from the WFP\n\nThe Emergency Response Classifications are divided as follows, with emergency intensity increasing with each level:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://documents.wfp.org/stellent/groups/public/documents/resources/wfp264770.pdf|title=WFP Emergency Response Classifications|date=8 May 2014|website=World Food Programme|access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n* '''Level 1''' \u2013 Response is activated. Resources are allocated to prepare for the WFP's local office to respond\n* '''Level 2''' \u2013 A country's resources require regional assistance with an emergency across one or multiple countries/territories\n* '''Level 3 (L3)''' \u2013 The emergency overpowers the WFP's local offices and requires a global response from the entire WFP organisation\n\n====Current L3 emergencies====\n{{asof|April 2020}} the following are classified as L3 emergencies:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/articles/understanding-l3-emergencies/|title=Understanding L3 Emergencies|website=World Food Program USA|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref>\n\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic]] \n* [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] \n* Northeastern [[Nigeria]] \n* The [[Sahel]]\n* [[South Sudan]] \n* [[Syria]]\n* [[Yemen]]\n\n==Official partnerships and initiatives==\nThe WFP coordinates and cooperates with a number of official partners in emergencies and development projects. These partners include national government agencies such as [[DFID]], [[ECHO (European Commission)|ECHO]], [[EuropeAid Development and Cooperation|EuropeAid]], [[USAID]]; UN agencies such as the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD); [[non-governmental organizations]] such as [[Save the Children]], [[Catholic Relief Services]] and [[Norwegian Refugee Council]]; as well as corporate partners such as [[Boston Consulting Group]], [http://www.dsm.com DSM N.V.], and [[Cargill]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wfp.org/partners/private-sector/meet-our-partners |title=WFP's Partners |publisher=World Food Programme |accessdate=2014-07-27}}</ref>\n\n===Grassroots efforts===\nIn 2004, the WFP tasked [[Auburn University]] in [[Auburn, Alabama|Auburn]], [[Alabama]] with heading the first student-led War on Hunger effort, after a 2002 [[Northwestern University]] pilot. Auburn founded the [[Committee of 19]], which has not only led campus and community hunger awareness events but also developed a War on Hunger model for use on campuses across the country.\n\nThe WFP has launched a global advocacy and fundraising event called [[Walk the World]]. On one single day each year, hundreds of thousands of people in every time zone all over the world walk to call for the end of child hunger. In 2005, more than 200,000 people walked in 296 locations. In 2006, there were 760,000 participants in 118 countries all over the world. This event is part of the campaign to achieve the [[Millennium Development Goals]], specifically to halve the number of people who suffer from hunger and poverty by 2015.\n\nA growing number of grassroots global events and celebrations such as [[International Day of Peace]], [[World Party Day]] participants, and [[Peace One Day]] recommend the WFP on radio broadcasts as an immediate reach out action, putting help within reach of anyone with the information that a quarter feeds a child for a day. [[Fill the Cup]] campaign takes just 25 US cents to fill one of the \"red cups\" that the World Food Programme uses to give hungry children a regular school meal of porridge, rice or beans.<ref>[http://www.wfp.org/node/222 Fill the cup: turning hunger into hope for millions of children]. Wfp.org. Retrieved on 2015-04-08.</ref><ref>[http://www.wfp.org/how-to-help How To Help]. Wfp.org. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref><ref>[http://www.grassrootsonline.org/term/human-right-food Grassroots International]. Grassrootsonline.org. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> [[Christina Aguilera]], Drew Barrymore and [[Sean Penn]] are among notable celebrities who endorse the WFP.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wE8GByc0SXE Drew Barrymore on CNN about WFP], YouTube video</ref><ref>[http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera Christina Aguilera \u2013 A Voice for the Hungry | United Nations World Food Programme \u2013 Fighting Hunger Worldwide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104151429/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|date=2013-01-04}}. WFP. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref> The British singer [[Sami Yusuf]] joined with the WFP to support the drought-stricken in Horn of Africa<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/news/news-release/singer-sami-yusuf-and-wfp-join-support-drought-stricken-horn-africa|title=Singer Sami Yusuf And WFP Join In Support For Drought-Stricken Horn Of Africa|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> through his personal campaign, LiveFeedAfrica<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livefeedafrica.org/|title=Live Feed: Help the Horn of Africa with Sami Yusuf and WFP|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> and music video, ''Forgotten Promises''.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKV2oeS4vw8|title=Sami Yusuf - Forgotten Promises|date=31 January 2012|publisher=|accessdate=17 May 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, composer and WFP supporter [[Benson Taylor]], travelled to the [[Bidi Bidi Refugee Settlement]] in [[Uganda]] with the [[WFP]] to raise awareness for [[World Refugee Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/_bensontaylor/status/658646066473078784 |title=United Nations Support |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=2017-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelondoneconomic.com/entertainment/music/composer-benson-taylor-joins-the-united-nations-world-food-programme-in-uganda-to-highlight-world-refugee-day/20/06/|title=Composer Benson Taylor joins the United Nations World Food Programme to highlight World Refugee Day|date=20 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vulturehound.co.uk/2018/06/uk-composer-producer-benson-taylor-joins-the-united-nations-world-food-programme-in-uganda-to-highlight-world-refugee-day/|title=UK Composer & Producer Benson Taylor Joins the United Nations World Food Programme in Uganda to highlight World Refugee Day|first=Michael|last=Dickinson|date=20 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===World Hunger Relief Week===\nIn 2007, the WFP joined with [[Yum! Brands]], the world's largest restaurant company, to launch the first annual World Hunger Relief Week, a global campaign to increase awareness about hunger, engage volunteers, and raise critically needed funds to help the WFP serve the world's areas of greatest need. World Hunger Relief Week 2007 leveraged the power of nearly 35,000 restaurants around the world, sparking a global movement to end hunger and generating an overwhelming outpouring of support from millions of customers, employees, franchisees and their families. Nearly one million Yum!, KFC, Pizza Hut, Taco Bell, Long John Silver's and A&W All American Food employees, franchisees and their families volunteered close to 4 million hours to aid hunger relief efforts in communities worldwide, while helping to raise $16 million throughout the World Hunger Relief Week initiative for the World Food Programme and other hunger relief agencies around the world. The initiative has been repeated every year since.\n\n===World Food Program USA===\nWorld Food Program USA, before 2010 known as Friends of the World Food Program,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfp.org/stories/wfp%E2%80%99s-us-partner-organisation-new-name-new-site-new-online-tools|title=WFP\u2019s USA Partner Organisation: New Name, New Site, New Online Tools|author=UN World Food Programme|date=16 July 2010|language=en}}</ref> works to solve global hunger, building a world where everyone has the food and nutrition needed to lead healthy, productive lives. WFP USA raises support for these efforts in the United States by engaging individuals, organizations and businesses, shaping public policy and generating resources for WFP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wfpusa.org/wfp-usas-mission/|title=Our Mission \u2013 A world without hunger|author=World Food Program USA|work=World Food Program USA|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe current chairman is Randy Russell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/about-us/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|website=World Food Program USA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Previously, the Chairman of the Board of World Food Program USA was Hunter Biden, son of former U.S. Vice President Joe Biden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111203422/http://www.energysecurityforum.org/speakers/186-hunter-biden-s|title=Hunter Biden|date=2019-11-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Joe Biden\u2019s son Hunter ordered to Arkansas court for contempt hearing in paternity case |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/22/hunter-biden-ordered-to-arkansas-court-for-paternity-case.html |accessdate=17 February 2020 |work=CNBC |quote=World Food Program USA Board Chairman Hunter Biden}}</ref> The chairman at inception of the current organization in 2010 was Randall Russell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/WFP_USA_Annual_Report_2010.pdf|title=Nourish to Empover|last=|first=|date=2010|website=World Food Program USA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===WFP Innovation Accelerator===\nThe [http://innovation.wfp.org World Food Programme's Innovation Accelerator], located in Munich, Germany, has operated since 2016 to source, support, test, and scale innovative approaches to address hunger and food insecurity. Innovative ideas may be found from within WFP global staff, entrepreneurs, start-ups, companies and non-governmental organizations, and are invited to apply on a rolling basis, and through annual Innovation Challenges. Short-listed ideas may be invited to Innovation Bootcamps where innovation teams meet with professional facilitators, mentors and experts from a variety of disciplines in order to fine-tune their proposals and pitch their ideas to potential investors, business supports, and WFP operations. Successful innovations may qualify for financial support to develop the innovation, 3-6 month field testing in WFP's global operations, or scale-up support to expand proven concepts for regional or global impact. \n\nThe WFP Innovation Accelerator provides innovation services not only to WFP, but also other United Nations organizations, such as UNFPA, UNICEF, UNHCR; other non-profit or non-governmental organizations such as the [https://www.gatesfoundation.org/ Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation], the [https://humanitariangrandchallenge.org/ Humanitarian Grand Challenge], and [https://www.xprize.org/ XPRIZE]; and has partnered with various private sector companies such as [https://www.cargill.com/ Cargill], [http://www.google.com/ Google], [https://www.bcg.com/ BCG], and others.\n\nSuccessful innovations that came through the WFP Innovation Accelerator include: \n[https://innovation.wfp.org/project/h2grow-hydroponics H2Grow Hydroponics]: to grow food and animal fodder in extreme environments, using no soil and minimal water. \n[https://innovation.wfp.org/project/scope-coda SCOPE CODA]: Personal smartcards are issued to people which replace paper-based health records with digital records, and enable frontline workers track nutritional needs, and make informed decisions with real-time data. \n[https://innovation.wfp.org/project/empact EMPACT]: Digital skills training to prepare conflict-affected youth for the future of work, and enabling them to provide for themselves and their families. \n[https://sharethemeal.org ShareTheMeal]: WFP's first crowdfunding app, ShareTheMeal enables microdonations from mobile phones and its website, based on the estimation that it costs USD $0.50 to provide 1 meal. In December 2019, ShareTheMeal funded over 50 million meals globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insight.wfp.org/50-million-meals-for-families-in-need-b0da26c818b8|title=50 million meals for families in need|last=Programme|first=World Food|date=2020-02-20|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n[[Kenya]]n economist [[James Shikwati]] said in a 2005 interview with ''[[Der Spiegel]]'': \"aid to Africa does more harm than good\".<ref name=\"DS Interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/0,1518,363663,00.html|title=Spiegel Interview with African Economics Expert: \"For God's Sake, Please Stop the Aid!\"|date=3 July 2005|work=Spiegel Online|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref>  According to him, the food aid increases [[corruption]] as local politicians have the opportunity to steal some of the aid to [[bribery|bribe]] voters or to sell the aid in the [[black market]]s killing the [[Subsistence agriculture|local agriculture]].<ref name=\"AP Sell Aid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/9798947|title=Removed: news agency feed article|work=the Guardian|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> He claims that the WFP people as an organization \"are in the absurd situation of, on the one hand, being dedicated to the fight against hunger while, on the other hand, being faced with unemployment were hunger actually eliminated\". He suggests that WFP answers too easily to the calls of the corrupted governments, and supplies too much of food aid leading to reduction of the production of [[local farming|local farmers]] as \"no one can compete with the UN's World Food Programme\".\n\nThe World Food Programme was also criticized by Jos\u00e9 Ciro Mart\u00ednez and Brent Eng in an essay''The Unintended Consequences of Emergency Food Aid: Neutrality, Sovereignty and Politics in the [[Syrian Civil War]], 2012-15''.  In an interview, an employee of the WFP stated: \"Most aid is still subject to strict control measures by the government, who also requests that it be distributed through state approved bodies such as [[Syrian Arab Red Crescent|SARC]]. I believe the government closely oversees if not completely controls these organizations.\" The authors added that food aid given in Syria would go to the military and its men first.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Martinez, Eng|first=Jose, Brent|year=2015|title=\"The Unintended Consequences of Emergency Food Aid: Neutrality, Sovereignty and Politics in the Syrian Civil War, 2012-15.\"|url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/publications/ia/INTA92_1_08_MartinezEng.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==List of executive directors==\nThe following is a chronological list of those who have held the Executive Director of the World Food Programme position:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wfp.org/about/previous-executive-directors | title=Previous WFP Executive Directors | publisher=World Food Programme | accessdate=2012-04-16}}</ref>\n\n#[[Addeke Hendrik Boerma]] (May 1962 \u2013 December 1967)\n# Sushil K. Dev (acting) (January 1968 \u2013 August 1968)\n# Franciso Aquino (July 1968 \u2013 May 1976)\n# Thomas C. M. Robinson (May 1976 \u2013 June 1977 acting; July 1977 \u2013 September 1977)\n# Garson N. Vogel (October 1977 \u2013 April 1981)\n# Bernardo de Azevedo Brito (acting) (May 1981 \u2013 February 1982)\n# Juan Felipe Yriart (acting) ([[:de:Juan Felipe Yriart|de]]) (February 1982 \u2013 April 1982)\n# [[James Ingram (diplomat)|James Ingram]] (April 1982 \u2013 April 1992)\n# [[Catherine Bertini]] (April 1992 \u2013 April 2002)\n# James T. Morris (April 2002 \u2013 April 2007)\n# [[Josette Sheeran]] (April 2007 \u2013 April 2012)\n# [[Ertharin Cousin]] (April 2012 \u2013 April 2017)\n# [[David Beasley]] (April 2017 \u2013 present)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Asia Emergency Response Facility]]\n* [[Fight Hunger]]: Walk the World<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Food Force]], an educational game\n* [[Food security]]\n* [[Walk the World]]\n* [[World Food Council]]\n* [[Logistics Cluster]]\n\n==Notes==\n===Footnotes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|United Nations World Food Program|World Food Programme}}\n* {{official website}} World Food Programme\n\n{{United Nations}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:United Nations Development Group]]\n[[Category:World Food Programme| ]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in society]]\n[[Category:International medical and health organizations]]\n[[Category:Malnutrition organizations]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Executive Directors of the World Food Programme| ]]\n[[Category:Hunger relief organizations]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Rome]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1963]]\n[[Category:Italy and the United Nations]]\n", "name_user": "Seligne", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList of executive directors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Food_Programme"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delhi", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Delhi, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{update|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| map1            = Location map India Delhi EN.svg\n| legend1         = {{legend|#d40000ff|Confirmed cases reported}}\n| image           = Jobless migrant workers at Delhi during lockdown IMG 20200414 144754.jpg\n| caption         = Keeping social distance jobless migrant workers at Delhi at a que for free lunch during lockdown on 14 April 2020\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Delhi]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = 2 March 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 2156<ref>{{cite web |title=ANI {{!}} Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/ANI/status/1252604934404493312/photo/1/ |website=twitter |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n|active_cases     = 1498\n| recovery_cases  = 611\n| deaths          = 47\n| website         =\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was confirmed in the Indian state of [[Delhi]] and the state has been under lockdown along with the country. First case was reported on 2 March 2020. Total infected people reported as on 21 April 2020 is 2156 consisting of 47 deaths.<ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus cases in Delhi rise to 2,156; no fresh deaths: Authorities|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/coronavirus-cases-in-delhi-rise-to-2156-no-fresh-deaths-authorities/articleshow/75277468.cms|work=[[Times Of India]]|date=21 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Here's a quick read on the COVID-19 related updates:|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-cases-in-india-live-news-latest-updates-april15/liveblog/75150277.cms|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2020 Delhi observed  a 14-hour voluntary public curfew named [[Janata curfew]] along with 75 district in India at the directive from PM,<ref name=\"CNN lockdown\">\nHelen Regan, Esha Mitra Swati Gupta, [https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html Millions in India under coronavirus lockdown as major cities restrict daily life], CNN, 23 March 2020\n</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Deserted roads in Delhi as people observe Janata Curfew|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/deserted-roads-in-delhi-as-people-observe-janata-curfew-1658356-2020-03-22|work=India Today|date=22 March 2020}}</ref> prior to his order of [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] for 21 days from 24 March 2020.<ref>{{citation|title=Modi Orders 3-Week Total Lockdown for All 1.3 Billion Indians|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html|work=The new York Times|date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThousands of migrants from [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Bihar]] gathered in Anand Vihar Bus Station on 29 March 2020.<ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus: Stranded migrant workers throng Delhi bus terminal in effort to get back home |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/migrant-worker-delhi-up-border-buses-coronavirus-community-spread-1660822-2020-03-29 |work=[[India Today]] |date=29 March 2020 }}</ref> More than 200 people from a religious gathering in Alami Markaz Banglewali Masjid in Nizamuddin area were quarantined after suspected contact with infected people.1300 tabligi were found stuck including foreigins in Markaz.<ref>{{citation |title=Covid-19: 200 quarantined, contact tracing on after Delhi mosque gathering |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/police-cordon-off-part-of-nizamuddin-after-people-show-covid-19-symptoms/story-ChOXzLNx3mSl490JgyqvKK.html |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Gross act of negligence: Delhi govt assures action against Nizamuddin Markaz that put over 500 in danger of Covid-19 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/gross-act-negligence-delhi-govt-action-against-nizamuddin-markaz-gathering-covid19-coronavirus-1661507-2020-03-30 |work=[[India Today]] |date=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus: 10 deaths, 300 hospitalisations linked to Tablighi Jamaat meet in Nizamuddin |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-10-deaths-300-hospitalisations-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-meet/articleshow/74902930.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=31 March 2020 }}</ref> However, now The Delhi High Court Declined to Entertain the Plea to Restrain the Delhi Government from Classifying COVID-19 Cases Under \u201cTabhigi\u201d Category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libertatem.in/law/high-court/delhi-high-court-declines-to-entertain-the-plea-to-restrain-the-delhi-government-from-classifying-covid-19-cases-under-tabhligi-category/|title=Delhi High Court Declines to Entertain the Plea to Restrain the Delhi Government from Classifying COVID-19 Cases Under \u201cTabhligi\u201d Category \u00bb Libertatem.in|date=2020-04-22|website=Libertatem.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that air quality index of Delhi improved on 28 March 2020 after the lockdown and reduced vehicular movements.<ref>{{citation |title=Corona blue: Clear skies, clean air in Delhi |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/delhi/corona-blue-clear-skies-clean-air/articleshow/74855039.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Delhi medical cases chart}}\n\n== Government responses ==\n===Closures and restrictions===\nOn 12 March, the Delhi chief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] declared COVID-19 an epidemic in Delhi. This made the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]] applicable to the territory. Schools, colleges and cinema halls were ordered to be closed until 31 March. Other public places including offices and shopping malls were to be compulsorily disinfected. Kerjiwal advised people to stay away from public gatherings.<ref>\n[https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/kejriwal-declares-coronavirus-epidemic-in-delhi-shuts-schools-and-colleges-120031201097_1.html Kejriwal declares coronavirus epidemic in Delhi, shuts schools and colleges], Business Standard, 12 March 2020.\n</ref><ref>\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/coronavirus-kejriwal-shuts-cinema-halls-schools-orders-offices-to-disinfect-premises-daily/story-byo42DCkhFA4aCLUynXKbJ.html Coronavirus: Kejriwal shuts cinema halls, schools; orders offices to disinfect premises daily], Hindustan Times, 12 March 2020.\n</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the [[Indian Premier League]] matches were banned in Delhi, as were all sports gatherings. Conferences and seminars beyond 200 people were also banned. The deputy chief minister [[Manish Sisodia]] invoked the example of the [[Super-spreader#COVID-19 outbreak 2019|religious superspreader]] in South Korea, and said that the Delhi government was determined to prevent such incidents.<ref>\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-delhi-govt-to-ban-sports-activities-in-wake-of-covid-19-threat-says-deputy-cm-manish-sisodia/story-889ss25ZqbJoG1eUoWn7aJ.html IPL, all big events banned in Delhi amid coronavirus outbreak: Manish Sisodia], Hindustan Times, 13 March 2020.\n</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the ban was strengthened to all gatherings over 50 people, including those for religious, social, cultural, political, academic, sports etc. reasons.\n\nOn 19 March, it was strengthened to gatherings over 20 people and, on 21 March, to those over 5 people.<ref name=\"Beg\">Mirza Arif Beg, [https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-corona-outbreak-afflicted-by-communal-virus-blaming-tablighi-jamaat-could-be-misdirected/349784 Communal Corona? Is It Justified To Blame Tablighi Jamaat For Nizamuddin Outbreak?], Outlook, 31 March 2020.\n</ref><ref name=\"IANS blame game\">IANS, [https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/authorities-playing-blame-game-over-nizamuddin-markaz/1787031 Authorities playing blame game over Nizamuddin Markaz], Outlook, 1 April 2020.\n</ref>\n\n===Travel and entry restrictions===\nChief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced that from 23 to 31 March 2020, all domestic/international flights arriving to [[Delhi]] would be suspended.<ref name=\"EcoTimes23March\"/>\n\n\n===Lockdown===\n{{multiple_image\n|header_align=left\n|header=\n|image1=Empty streets and establishment closures during the COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi IMG 20200407 145130 11.jpg\n|alt1=New Delhi Railway Station main entrance.\n|caption1=During lockdown empty [[New Delhi railway station]] main gate on 7 April 2020\n|image2=Empty streets and establishment closures during the COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi IMG 20200407 145130 09.jpg\n|alt2=A street at Paharganj, Delhi\n|caption2=During lockdown empty [[Paharganj]] main bazar on 7 April 2020\n|footer_align=right\n|footer=\n}}\n* '''22 March'''\n:*CM Kejriwal had announced [[lockdown]] from 23 March 6 a.m. to 31 March midnight. Except essential services every services had been closed due to [[COVID-19]] pandemic. Borders had been sealed except for transportation of essential services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus in Delhi: CM Kejriwal announces lockdown from March 23 to 31|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-in-delhi-cm-kejriwal-announces-lockdown-from-march-23-to-31/videoshow/74761871.cms|accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''24 March'''\n:*Lockdown further extended till 14 April 2020 after PM [[Narendra Modi]] announced a complete nationwide lockdown, starting from midnight of 24 March 2020 for 21 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/narendra-modi-on-coronavirus-speech-live-updates-streaming-watch-india-pm-address-to-nation-on-covid-19-today-latest-news-lockdown-janata-curfew-8182241.html|title=Narendra Modi on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: India under complete shutdown for 21 days starting 12 pm tonight, says PM|date=|work=The Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*'''14 April'''\n:*Modi extended lockdown  till 3 May 2020<ref name=\"lockdownext\">\n{{cite news |first1=Utpal|last1=Bhaskar|title=PM Modi announces extension of lockdown till 3 May | url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-announces-extension-of-lockdown-till-3-may-11586839412073.html |work=The Livemint |date=14 April 2020}}\n</ref> after recommendation from several state governments.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Rounak|last1=Jain|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/lockdown-in-telangana-extended-till-june-3/articleshow/75014509.cms|title=Telangana CM suggests lockdown extension by two weeks|date=|work=The Business Insder|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''19 April'''\n:*CM Kejriwal announced that keeping in mind the current situation of Delhi, there will be no exemption in ongoing lockdown till next week.<ref name=\"No exemption\">{{cite news |title=Delhi witnessing surge in Covid-19 cases, no relaxation in lockdown: Kejriwal |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/delhi-witnessing-surge-in-covid-19-cases-no-relaxation-in-lockdown-measures-cm-arvind-kejriwal/story-8g9byg552IaCbEHTuIWWoJ.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Disinfection drive ===\n[[File:Delhi Govt disinfection drive during COVID-19 pandemic in DelhiVID 20200416 132044.webm|thumb|Delhi Govt disinfection drive during COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi]]\nDelhi government had initiated a disinfection drive in Delhi from 13 April 2020<ref>{{citation |title=Covid-19: Delhi govt to sanitise city's red, orange zones from Monday, says Arvind Kejriwal|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-delhi-govt-to-sanitise-city-s-red-orange-zones-from-monday-says-arvind-kejriwal-1666196-2020-04-12|work=[[India Today]] |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== State government's relief ===\n\n====Ration====\n*'''4 April''': CM Kejriwal announced that people who don't have ration card can avail free ration from fair price shops.<ref>{{citation|title=People without Ration Cards in Delhi can now avail free ration from Fair Price Shops: Delhi govt|url=http://newsonair.com/News?title=People-without-Ration-Cards-in-Delhi-can-now-avail-free-ration-from-Fair-Price-Shops%3A-Delhi-govt&id=384700|work=News On Air|date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''5 April''':  Out of 71 lakh ration card holders in Delhi, it was reported that 60% had received ration.<ref name=\"ration\">{{citation|title=Delhi: 60% of 71 lakh people under PDS given ration, those without cards can fill forms|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-60-of-71-lakh-people-under-pds-given-ration-those-without-cards-can-fill-forms-6347808/|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=5 April 2020}}</ref> As per the government till 5 April, 50,000 to 60,000 people who do not have ration cards, have applied for coupons to avail 5&nbsp;kg of wheat, rice and sugar as free of cost.<ref  name=\"ration\"/> Some people complained about distribution, in a video conference with area MLAs including other party. Kejriwal requested that they should reach out to people in distress and help them register to avail ration.<ref  name=\"ration\"/>\n*'''21 April''', since 38 lakh people who don't have ration card applied for ration, Govt will provide free ration to 31 lakh people. Delhi CM conveyed that Govt is providing half of the total population of Delhi free ration.<ref>{{cite news |title=We will be providing free ration to nearly half of Delhi: Kejriwal |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/we-will-be-providing-free-ration-to-nearly-half-of-delhi-kejriwal/article31400640.ece |accessdate=21 April 020 |work=The Hindu |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Free food====\n*On 23 March, the CM of Delhi had announced that 4 lakh people will get free food in Delhi from 24 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=4 lakh people to get free food in Delhi, coronavirus treatment capacity to be raised to 1,000 patients per day |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/4-lakh-people-to-get-free-food-in-delhi-coronavirus-treatment-capacity-to-be-raised-to-1000-patients-per-day/story/399405.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=Business Today |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 4 April, the Delhi Government had initiated to provide free food for 6.5 lakh people including distress migrant workers who are jobless in current lockdown. To provide food across the all areas of Delhi, to maintain physical distance, hygiene and sanitation, Govt. had converted night shelters and schools into free food distribution centers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi govt provides food to around 6.5 lakh people in one day |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-govt-provides-food-to-around-6-5-lakh-people-in-one-day-statement/articleshow/74996223.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Food Coupon====\non 21 April, as conveyed by CM Delhi, each MP, MLA of Delhi will get 2000 food coupon for their constituency to distribute to poor who don't have any documents like ration card or Adhar card.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi MPs, MLAs to get 2,000 food coupons each for poor, says Arvind Kejriwal |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-mps-mlas-to-get-2-000-food-coupons-each-for-poor-says-arvind-kejriwal-11587475770876.html |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=Live Mint |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====One time financial support for transport service provider====\nAs one time financial help, Delhi govt had announced to support  affected transport service provider like Auto, E-Rickshaw, Rural transport Vehicle and Gramin seva of Delhi Rs 5,000/- each to their bank account who will apply with their current driving licence of  Para-Transit vehicles and valid badge<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19: Delhi govt to give \u20b95,000 each to transport service providers: Kejriwal |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/covid-19-delhi-govt-to-give-5000-each-to-transport-service-providers-kejriwal/article31239144.ece |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Govt starts disbursing 1-time Rs 5K to drivers |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/state-editions/govt-starts-disbursing-1-time-rs-5k-to-drivers.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Financial support to next to kin of deceased health staff====\nDelhi CM had announced a financial support of Rs 1 crore for the family of any deceased health staff who had died while dealing with coronavirus cases in Delhi.<ref name=\"Support of kin of healthcare staff\">{{cite news |title=Arvind Kejriwal announces Rs 1 crore for kin of healthcare staff who die dealing with Covid cases |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-announces-rs-1-crore-for-kin-of-healthcare-staff-who-die-dealing-with-covid-cases/articleshow/74929464.cms |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=Economic Times |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> He had mentioned them as \"not less than warrior\" and this support as tribute to their noble service.<ref name=\"Support of kin of healthcare staff\"/>\n\n==Testing==\nOn 13 April, in Delhi 14,036, [[COVID-19 testing]] had been done in which positive cases are 1,154 in total and percentage wise its 8.22%. Population of Delhi is 201,78,879 (20 million plus) falls under category of the states having population 11 to 37 million and till 13 April 2020, 696 test/million had been conducted in Delhi which is second highest after Kerala in this category.<ref>{{cite news |title=Decoding India's Covid-19 testing, state by state |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/news-analysis/story/decoding-india-s-covid-19-testing-state-by-state-1666587-2020-04-13 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=India Today |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April, the Delhi Govt. announced free COVID-19 test for media persons in Delhi after the incident of some journalists in Mumbai tested positive..<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi to start Covid-19 testing for media persons after 53 Mumbai journalists test positive |url=https://theprint.in/india/delhi-to-start-covid-19-testing-for-media-persons-after-53-mumbai-journalists-test-positive/406262/ |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=The Print |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n===Testing data===\n\n{{updated|22 April 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 200px; height: 200px;\"\n|+ COVID-19 sample testing status<ref name=\"State Health Bulletin\">{{cite web |title=Delhi State Health Bulletin _COVID -19 |url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/pdf/Districtreporting408.pdf |publisher=Govt. of India (MoHFW) |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n!  !!Total!!Positive!!Negative!!Pending\n|-\n| Govt. Labs ||19893 ||1875||15848||1881\n|-\n| Private labs ||6734 ||281||5962||473\n|-\n| Total|| 26627||2156||21810||2354\n|}\n==Treatment==\n*13 April, [[ICMR]] requested researcher to give clinical trial on critically ill patient of [[COVID-19]] using convalescent plasma therapy.<ref name=\"Plasma Therapy\"/>\n*15 April, after a meeting  Lieutenant Governor of Delhi, [[Anil Baijal]] had declared Delhi may use plasma technique to combat COVID-19. He mentioned that it will be on trial basis with proper guideline.<ref name=\"Plasma Therapy\">{{cite news |title=Delhi to use plasma technique for covid treatment on trial basis |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/delhi-to-use-plasma-technique-for-covid-treatment-on-trial-basis/articleshow/75161985.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=Economic Times |date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n*20 April, a 49 year old, critically ill patient of COVID-19 who was on ventilator support is out from ventilator after receiving plasma therapy. This is the first successful trial of plasma therapy in India. <ref>{{cite news |title=Plasma Therapy For COVID-19 Works In Delhi, 49-year-old Recovers |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/plasma-therapy-for-covid-19-works-in-delhi-49-year-old-recovers-2215191 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=NDTV |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 Hospital Status===\n\n{{updated|22 April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 500px; height: 200px;\"\n|+ COVID-19 Hospital status <ref name=\"State Health Bulletin\"/>\n! Name of The COVID Hospital !!Total No. of positive cases including patient of '''I''' and '''V''' (as of 22 April)!!Cumulative no of deaths!!No. of positive cases in ICU ('''I''') !!No of positive cases on Ventilator ('''V''')\n|-\n| LNJP ||214||5||4||0\n|-\n| RGSSH ||54 ||2||9||0\n|-\n| LHMC||18||0||1||0\n|-\n| RML ||33||20||2||0\n|-\n| SJH ||29 ||4||0||0\n|-\n| AIIMS Jhajjar||68||2||0||0\n|-\n| Apollo Hospital||28||5||5||3\n|-\n| Max Hospital ||60 ||1||6||2\n|-\n| Ganga Ram||9||0||0||0\n|-\n|'''Total'''||'''513'''||'''39*'''||'''27'''||'''5'''\n|}\n*Rest of the deaths reported from other hospitals\n\n===COVID-19 Care Centre Status===\n\n{{updated|22 April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 500px; height: 200px;\"\n\n|+ COVID-19 Care Centre Status <ref name=\"State Health Bulletin\"/>\n! Name of COVID care centre!! Total No. of positive cases as of 22 April\n|-\n| CCC Terapanth Bhawan || 06\n|-\n| CCC DDA Flats Narela|| 397\n|-\n| CCC DUSIB Flats Sultanpuri|| 78\n|-\n| CCC DUSIB flats Bakkarwala|| 63 \n|-\n| CCC Badarpur|| 24\n|-\n| CCC Mandoli|| 142 \n|-\n| CCC New Friends Colony||15 \n|-\n| CCC Joga Bai|| 37 \n|-\n| CCC Birla Mandir Dharamshala|| 2 \n|-\n| CCC PTS Wazirabad|| 8 \n|-\n|'''Total'''|| '''772'''\n|}\n\n==Impact==\nAs of 6 March 2020 all primary schools were closed by Delhi Govt till 31 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus threat: Delhi govt orders closure of all primary schools till March 31 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/coronavirus-threat-delhi-govt-orders-closure-of-all-primary-schools-till-march-31/story-ExewEmJeLCZ6egWDW6Ss2N.html |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306042604/https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/coronavirus-threat-delhi-govt-orders-closure-of-all-primary-schools-till-march-31/story-ExewEmJeLCZ6egWDW6Ss2N.html |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day in fear of [[COVID-19]], [[Fashion Design Council of India]] had postpone their show till further notice.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indulgexpress.com/fashion/2020/mar/06/fdci-postpones-lotus-makeup-india-fashion-week-amidst-covid-19-fears-22914.html|title=FDCI postpones Lotus Makeup India Fashion Week amidst COVID-19 fears|work=Indulge Express|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 ISSF World Cup]] has been postponed which was scheduled to be held in May 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms|title=Virus hits Indian sports|date=6 March 2020|work=Economic Times|accessdate=7 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> On 14 March 2020 [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF) had also postpone their all tournaments due to same reason.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/sports-news-coronavirus-india-open-badminton-tournament-cancelled/348760|title=Coronavirus: India Open Badminton Tournament Cancelled|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=Outlook|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Commercial establishments===\nOn 19 March, Arvind Kejriwal announced that all restaurants will be closed till 31 March in view of the ever increasing case of coronavirus. He said that there will be a take away system from restaurants without any eating facilities in the venue. He also said that 20 or more people will not be allowed to unite anywhere in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kejriwal govt orders Delhi restaurants to shut shop with immediate effect until 31 March| url=https://theprint.in/india/kejriwal-govt-orders-delhi-restaurants-to-shut-shop-with-immediate-effect-until-31-march/384034/|website=theprint|author=}}</ref>\nAll shops, industries, commercial establishments, offices shall be closed.<ref name=\"EcoTimes23March\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Fallout: Delhi CM Arvind Kejriwal announces lockdown until March 31 |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-fallout-delhi-cm-arvind-kejriwal-announces-lockdown-until-march-31/articleshow/74761137.cms |accessdate=17 April 2020 |publisher=The Economic Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Hotspot ==\n[[File:Minister visiting the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre 2.jpg|thumb|The Minister of State for Home Affairs, [[Nityanand Rai]] visiting evacuees at the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre, after completion of their requisite quarantine period, at the ITBP Chhawla Centre, in New Delhi on 13 March 2020.]]\n*'''14 April'''  after adding eight new hotspots, now total hotspot numbers are 55 in Delhi.<ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus lockdown: 8 more hotspots in Delhi, 55 areas sealed in Delhi|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-lockdown-8-more-hotspots-in-delhi-55-areas-sealed-in-delhi-check-full-list-here-1667005-2020-04-14|work=[[India Today]]|date=14 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n*'''15 April''' after adding two more places, total hotspot numbers are 57.<ref name=15AprilIndiaToday>{{citation |title=Coronavirus: Delhi adds 2 areas in containment zone list, city tally rises to 1,578|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/complete-list-of-57-coronavirus-containment-zones-in-delhi-1667371-2020-04-15|work=[[India Today]]|date=15 April 2020 }}</ref>\n*'''19 April''' now there are total 77 containment zones and all 11 districts of Delhi are declared as hotspots as conveyed by Delhi CM<ref name=\"No exemption\"/>\n*'''21 April''' the number of containment zones rises to 87 <ref name=21AprilTimesOfIndia>{{citation |title=Covid-19: Number of containment zones rises to 87 in Delhi|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/covid-19-number-of-containment-zones-rises-to-87-in-delhi/articleshow/75279020.cms|work=[[Times of India]]|date=21 April 2020 }}</ref>\n=== SHIELD plan ===\nThe Delhi Government announced operation SHIELD in order to curb the spread of the virus in the containment zones or the hotspots. It is a six layers plan,<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Delhi govt announces Operation SHIELD to take on COVID-19 |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/coronavirus-delhi-govt-announces-operation-shield-to-take-on-covid-19/story/400648.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=The Business Today |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> where \n*'''S''' refers to sealing the immediate area, \n\n*'''H''' refers to home quarantine to all people living in the area, \n\n*'''I''' refers to isolation and contact tracing of people,\n*'''E''' refers to essential supply of commodities, \n\n*'''L''' refers to local sanitization and \n\n*'''D''' refers to door to door health check of people in the area.\n\nThe first success of the operation came from [[Dilshad Garden]], an area where the virus was widely spreaded. The Delhi Government announced on 10 April, that the operation SHIELD was successful in containing the spread of the virus in this area. The state Health Minister, [[Satyendra Kumar Jain|Satyendra Jain]] said that the area was virus-free after the implementation of the six layer operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Operation SHIELD successful in containing COVID-19 spread in Dilshad Garden: Delhi health minister |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/operation-shield-successful-in-containing-covid-19-spread-in-dilshad-garden-delhi-health-minister/articleshow/75082473.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> On 17 April, Deputy CM of Delhi, [[Manish Sisodia]] annouced that the operation was also successful in two other hotspots, [[Vasundhara Enclave]] and Khichripur.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manish Sisodia lauds locals for making 'Operation SHIELD' successful |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/manish-sisodia-lauds-locals-for-making-operation-shield-successful/articleshow/75200268.cms |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cases ==\n=== Cases by districts ===\n[[File:Effect of Janata curfew road near New Delhi railway station IMG 20200322 163711 05.jpg|thumb|alt=A flexible bitumen road in Delhi|Deserted road during the Janata Curfew: Baburam Sokanki Marg, a road near the [[New Delhi railway station]]]]\n\n{{updated|21 April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Administrative districts and confirmed cases<ref>{{cite web |title=State/District wise Details of COVID-19 positive cases |url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/pdf/Districtreporting408.pdf |publisher=Govt. of India (MoHFW) |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n! District !! Number of cases\n|-\n| Central Delhi || 184\n|-\n| East Delhi|| 38\n|-\n| New Delhi || 37\n|-\n| North Delhi || 60 \n|-\n| North-East Delhi || 25\n|-\n| North-West Delhi || 32\n|-\n| Shahadara  || 48\n|-\n| South Delhi || 70\n|-\n| South-East Delhi|| 130\n|-\n| South-West Delhi || 42\n|-\n| West Delhi || 122\n|-\n|  TJ from Quarantine  || 1,080\n|-\n|  Others non traceable  || 213\n|-\n| Total  || 2,081\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by city|Delhi]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Delhi]]\n[[Category:2020s in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Health in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Delhi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Delhi, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{update|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| map1            = Location map India Delhi EN.svg\n| legend1         = {{legend|#d40000ff|Confirmed cases reported}}\n| image           = Jobless migrant workers at Delhi during lockdown IMG 20200414 144754.jpg\n| caption         = Keeping social distance jobless migrant workers at Delhi at a que for free lunch during lockdown on 14 April 2020\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Delhi]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = 2 March 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 2156<ref>{{cite web |title=ANI {{!}} Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/ANI/status/1252604934404493312/photo/1/ |website=twitter |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n|active_cases     = 1498\n| recovery_cases  = 611\n| deaths          = 47\n| website         =\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was confirmed in the Indian state of [[Delhi]] and the state has been under lockdown along with the country. First case was reported on 2 March 2020. Total infected people reported as on 21 April 2020 is 2156 consisting of 47 deaths.<ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus cases in Delhi rise to 2,156; no fresh deaths: Authorities|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/coronavirus-cases-in-delhi-rise-to-2156-no-fresh-deaths-authorities/articleshow/75277468.cms|work=[[Times Of India]]|date=21 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Here's a quick read on the COVID-19 related updates:|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-cases-in-india-live-news-latest-updates-april15/liveblog/75150277.cms|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2020 Delhi observed  a 14-hour voluntary public curfew named [[Janata curfew]] along with 75 district in India at the directive from PM,<ref name=\"CNN lockdown\">\nHelen Regan, Esha Mitra Swati Gupta, [https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html Millions in India under coronavirus lockdown as major cities restrict daily life], CNN, 23 March 2020\n</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Deserted roads in Delhi as people observe Janata Curfew|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/deserted-roads-in-delhi-as-people-observe-janata-curfew-1658356-2020-03-22|work=India Today|date=22 March 2020}}</ref> prior to his order of [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] for 21 days from 24 March 2020.<ref>{{citation|title=Modi Orders 3-Week Total Lockdown for All 1.3 Billion Indians|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html|work=The new York Times|date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThousands of migrants from [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Bihar]] gathered in Anand Vihar Bus Station on 29 March 2020.<ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus: Stranded migrant workers throng Delhi bus terminal in effort to get back home |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/migrant-worker-delhi-up-border-buses-coronavirus-community-spread-1660822-2020-03-29 |work=[[India Today]] |date=29 March 2020 }}</ref> More than 200 people from a religious gathering in Alami Markaz Banglewali Masjid in Nizamuddin area were quarantined after suspected contact with infected people.1300 tabligi were found stuck including foreigins in Markaz.<ref>{{citation |title=Covid-19: 200 quarantined, contact tracing on after Delhi mosque gathering |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/police-cordon-off-part-of-nizamuddin-after-people-show-covid-19-symptoms/story-ChOXzLNx3mSl490JgyqvKK.html |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Gross act of negligence: Delhi govt assures action against Nizamuddin Markaz that put over 500 in danger of Covid-19 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/gross-act-negligence-delhi-govt-action-against-nizamuddin-markaz-gathering-covid19-coronavirus-1661507-2020-03-30 |work=[[India Today]] |date=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus: 10 deaths, 300 hospitalisations linked to Tablighi Jamaat meet in Nizamuddin |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-10-deaths-300-hospitalisations-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-meet/articleshow/74902930.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=31 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that air quality index of Delhi improved on 28 March 2020 after the lockdown and reduced vehicular movements.<ref>{{citation |title=Corona blue: Clear skies, clean air in Delhi |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/delhi/corona-blue-clear-skies-clean-air/articleshow/74855039.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Delhi medical cases chart}}\n\n== Government responses ==\n===Closures and restrictions===\nOn 12 March, the Delhi chief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] declared COVID-19 an epidemic in Delhi. This made the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]] applicable to the territory. Schools, colleges and cinema halls were ordered to be closed until 31 March. Other public places including offices and shopping malls were to be compulsorily disinfected. Kerjiwal advised people to stay away from public gatherings.<ref>\n[https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/kejriwal-declares-coronavirus-epidemic-in-delhi-shuts-schools-and-colleges-120031201097_1.html Kejriwal declares coronavirus epidemic in Delhi, shuts schools and colleges], Business Standard, 12 March 2020.\n</ref><ref>\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/coronavirus-kejriwal-shuts-cinema-halls-schools-orders-offices-to-disinfect-premises-daily/story-byo42DCkhFA4aCLUynXKbJ.html Coronavirus: Kejriwal shuts cinema halls, schools; orders offices to disinfect premises daily], Hindustan Times, 12 March 2020.\n</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the [[Indian Premier League]] matches were banned in Delhi, as were all sports gatherings. Conferences and seminars beyond 200 people were also banned. The deputy chief minister [[Manish Sisodia]] invoked the example of the [[Super-spreader#COVID-19 outbreak 2019|religious superspreader]] in South Korea, and said that the Delhi government was determined to prevent such incidents.<ref>\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-delhi-govt-to-ban-sports-activities-in-wake-of-covid-19-threat-says-deputy-cm-manish-sisodia/story-889ss25ZqbJoG1eUoWn7aJ.html IPL, all big events banned in Delhi amid coronavirus outbreak: Manish Sisodia], Hindustan Times, 13 March 2020.\n</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the ban was strengthened to all gatherings over 50 people, including those for religious, social, cultural, political, academic, sports etc. reasons.\n\nOn 19 March, it was strengthened to gatherings over 20 people and, on 21 March, to those over 5 people.<ref name=\"Beg\">Mirza Arif Beg, [https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-corona-outbreak-afflicted-by-communal-virus-blaming-tablighi-jamaat-could-be-misdirected/349784 Communal Corona? Is It Justified To Blame Tablighi Jamaat For Nizamuddin Outbreak?], Outlook, 31 March 2020.\n</ref><ref name=\"IANS blame game\">IANS, [https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/authorities-playing-blame-game-over-nizamuddin-markaz/1787031 Authorities playing blame game over Nizamuddin Markaz], Outlook, 1 April 2020.\n</ref>\n\n===Travel and entry restrictions===\nChief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced that from 23 to 31 March 2020, all domestic/international flights arriving to [[Delhi]] would be suspended.<ref name=\"EcoTimes23March\"/>\n\n\n===Lockdown===\n{{multiple_image\n|header_align=left\n|header=\n|image1=Empty streets and establishment closures during the COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi IMG 20200407 145130 11.jpg\n|alt1=New Delhi Railway Station main entrance.\n|caption1=During lockdown empty [[New Delhi railway station]] main gate on 7 April 2020\n|image2=Empty streets and establishment closures during the COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi IMG 20200407 145130 09.jpg\n|alt2=A street at Paharganj, Delhi\n|caption2=During lockdown empty [[Paharganj]] main bazar on 7 April 2020\n|footer_align=right\n|footer=\n}}\n* '''22 March'''\n:*CM Kejriwal had announced [[lockdown]] from 23 March 6 a.m. to 31 March midnight. Except essential services every services had been closed due to [[COVID-19]] pandemic. Borders had been sealed except for transportation of essential services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus in Delhi: CM Kejriwal announces lockdown from March 23 to 31|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-in-delhi-cm-kejriwal-announces-lockdown-from-march-23-to-31/videoshow/74761871.cms|accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''24 March'''\n:*Lockdown further extended till 14 April 2020 after PM [[Narendra Modi]] announced a complete nationwide lockdown, starting from midnight of 24 March 2020 for 21 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/narendra-modi-on-coronavirus-speech-live-updates-streaming-watch-india-pm-address-to-nation-on-covid-19-today-latest-news-lockdown-janata-curfew-8182241.html|title=Narendra Modi on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: India under complete shutdown for 21 days starting 12 pm tonight, says PM|date=|work=The Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*'''14 April'''\n:*Modi extended lockdown  till 3 May 2020<ref name=\"lockdownext\">\n{{cite news |first1=Utpal|last1=Bhaskar|title=PM Modi announces extension of lockdown till 3 May | url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-announces-extension-of-lockdown-till-3-may-11586839412073.html |work=The Livemint |date=14 April 2020}}\n</ref> after recommendation from several state governments.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Rounak|last1=Jain|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/lockdown-in-telangana-extended-till-june-3/articleshow/75014509.cms|title=Telangana CM suggests lockdown extension by two weeks|date=|work=The Business Insder|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''19 April'''\n:*CM Kejriwal announced that keeping in mind the current situation of Delhi, there will be no exemption in ongoing lockdown till next week.<ref name=\"No exemption\">{{cite news |title=Delhi witnessing surge in Covid-19 cases, no relaxation in lockdown: Kejriwal |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/delhi-witnessing-surge-in-covid-19-cases-no-relaxation-in-lockdown-measures-cm-arvind-kejriwal/story-8g9byg552IaCbEHTuIWWoJ.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Disinfection drive ===\n[[File:Delhi Govt disinfection drive during COVID-19 pandemic in DelhiVID 20200416 132044.webm|thumb|Delhi Govt disinfection drive during COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi]]\nDelhi government had initiated a disinfection drive in Delhi from 13 April 2020<ref>{{citation |title=Covid-19: Delhi govt to sanitise city's red, orange zones from Monday, says Arvind Kejriwal|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-delhi-govt-to-sanitise-city-s-red-orange-zones-from-monday-says-arvind-kejriwal-1666196-2020-04-12|work=[[India Today]] |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== State government's relief ===\n\n====Ration====\n*'''4 April''': CM Kejriwal announced that people who don't have ration card can avail free ration from fair price shops.<ref>{{citation|title=People without Ration Cards in Delhi can now avail free ration from Fair Price Shops: Delhi govt|url=http://newsonair.com/News?title=People-without-Ration-Cards-in-Delhi-can-now-avail-free-ration-from-Fair-Price-Shops%3A-Delhi-govt&id=384700|work=News On Air|date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''5 April''':  Out of 71 lakh ration card holders in Delhi, it was reported that 60% had received ration.<ref name=\"ration\">{{citation|title=Delhi: 60% of 71 lakh people under PDS given ration, those without cards can fill forms|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-60-of-71-lakh-people-under-pds-given-ration-those-without-cards-can-fill-forms-6347808/|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=5 April 2020}}</ref> As per the government till 5 April, 50,000 to 60,000 people who do not have ration cards, have applied for coupons to avail 5&nbsp;kg of wheat, rice and sugar as free of cost.<ref  name=\"ration\"/> Some people complained about distribution, in a video conference with area MLAs including other party. Kejriwal requested that they should reach out to people in distress and help them register to avail ration.<ref  name=\"ration\"/>\n*'''21 April''', since 38 lakh people who don't have ration card applied for ration, Govt will provide free ration to 31 lakh people. Delhi CM conveyed that Govt is providing half of the total population of Delhi free ration.<ref>{{cite news |title=We will be providing free ration to nearly half of Delhi: Kejriwal |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/we-will-be-providing-free-ration-to-nearly-half-of-delhi-kejriwal/article31400640.ece |accessdate=21 April 020 |work=The Hindu |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Free food====\n*On 23 March, the CM of Delhi had announced that 4 lakh people will get free food in Delhi from 24 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=4 lakh people to get free food in Delhi, coronavirus treatment capacity to be raised to 1,000 patients per day |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/4-lakh-people-to-get-free-food-in-delhi-coronavirus-treatment-capacity-to-be-raised-to-1000-patients-per-day/story/399405.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=Business Today |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 4 April, the Delhi Government had initiated to provide free food for 6.5 lakh people including distress migrant workers who are jobless in current lockdown. To provide food across the all areas of Delhi, to maintain physical distance, hygiene and sanitation, Govt. had converted night shelters and schools into free food distribution centers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi govt provides food to around 6.5 lakh people in one day |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-govt-provides-food-to-around-6-5-lakh-people-in-one-day-statement/articleshow/74996223.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Food Coupon====\non 21 April, as conveyed by CM Delhi, each MP, MLA of Delhi will get 2000 food coupon for their constituency to distribute to poor who don't have any documents like ration card or Adhar card.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi MPs, MLAs to get 2,000 food coupons each for poor, says Arvind Kejriwal |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-mps-mlas-to-get-2-000-food-coupons-each-for-poor-says-arvind-kejriwal-11587475770876.html |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=Live Mint |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====One time financial support for transport service provider====\nAs one time financial help, Delhi govt had announced to support  affected transport service provider like Auto, E-Rickshaw, Rural transport Vehicle and Gramin seva of Delhi Rs 5,000/- each to their bank account who will apply with their current driving licence of  Para-Transit vehicles and valid badge<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19: Delhi govt to give \u20b95,000 each to transport service providers: Kejriwal |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/covid-19-delhi-govt-to-give-5000-each-to-transport-service-providers-kejriwal/article31239144.ece |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Govt starts disbursing 1-time Rs 5K to drivers |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/state-editions/govt-starts-disbursing-1-time-rs-5k-to-drivers.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Financial support to next to kin of deceased health staff====\nDelhi CM had announced a financial support of Rs 1 crore for the family of any deceased health staff who had died while dealing with coronavirus cases in Delhi.<ref name=\"Support of kin of healthcare staff\">{{cite news |title=Arvind Kejriwal announces Rs 1 crore for kin of healthcare staff who die dealing with Covid cases |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-announces-rs-1-crore-for-kin-of-healthcare-staff-who-die-dealing-with-covid-cases/articleshow/74929464.cms |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=Economic Times |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> He had mentioned them as \"not less than warrior\" and this support as tribute to their noble service.<ref name=\"Support of kin of healthcare staff\"/>\n\n==Testing==\nOn 13 April, in Delhi 14,036, [[COVID-19 testing]] had been done in which positive cases are 1,154 in total and percentage wise its 8.22%. Population of Delhi is 201,78,879 (20 million plus) falls under category of the states having population 11 to 37 million and till 13 April 2020, 696 test/million had been conducted in Delhi which is second highest after Kerala in this category.<ref>{{cite news |title=Decoding India's Covid-19 testing, state by state |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/news-analysis/story/decoding-india-s-covid-19-testing-state-by-state-1666587-2020-04-13 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=India Today |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April, the Delhi Govt. announced free COVID-19 test for media persons in Delhi after the incident of some journalists in Mumbai tested positive..<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi to start Covid-19 testing for media persons after 53 Mumbai journalists test positive |url=https://theprint.in/india/delhi-to-start-covid-19-testing-for-media-persons-after-53-mumbai-journalists-test-positive/406262/ |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=The Print |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n===Testing data===\n\n{{updated|22 April 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 200px; height: 200px;\"\n|+ COVID-19 sample testing status<ref name=\"State Health Bulletin\">{{cite web |title=Delhi State Healt