8.76 (1982 & 1988), 8.75 (1987), 8.72 (1988) and 8.71 (1984).\n*[[Larry Myricks]] also jumped 8.70 (1989).\n*[[Mike Powell (athlete)|Mike Powell]] also jumped 8.70 (1993).\n*[[Ivan Pedroso]] also jumped 8.70 (1995).\n\n====Wind-assisted jumps====\n\nThere are many more exceptionally long jumps in the history of long jumping that are not listed in the record books because of excessive wind from behind the jumper. The limit for the wind speed to allow a jump to enter the record books is 2 m/s. The following contains a list of other notable jumps in which the wind speed exceeded this limit.\n\n*[[Mike Powell (athlete)|Mike Powell]] (USA) jumped 8.99 (+4.4) at altitude in Sestriere, Italy on 21 July 1992.\n*[[Iv\u00e1n Pedroso]] (CUB) jumped 8.96  (+1.2) at altitude in Sestriere, Italy on 29 July 1995. The jump was ruled invalid due to an obstructed wind-gauge.\n*[[Juan Miguel Echevarr\u00eda]] (CUB) jumped 8.92 (+3.3) on 10 March 2019 in Havana, Cuba.\n*[[Carl Lewis]] (USA) jumped 8.91 (+3.0) on 30 August 1991 at the World Championships in Tokyo, Japan.\n*[[Fabrice Lapierre]] (AUS) jumped 8.78 (+3.1) on 18 April 2010 in Perth, Australia.\n*[[James Beckford (athlete)|James Beckford]] (JAM) jumped 8.68 (+4.9) on 20 May 1995 in Odessa, Ukraine.\n*[[Joe Greene (athlete)|Joe Greene]] (USA) jumped 8.68 (+4.0) at altitude on 21 July 1995 in Sestriere, Italy.\n*[[Marquis Dendy]] (USA) jumped 8.68 (+3.7) on 25 June 2015 in Eugene, Oregon.\n*[[Kareem Streete-Thompson]] (USA) jumped 8.64 (+3.5) on 18 June 1995 in Knoxville, Tennessee.\n*[[Mike Conley, Sr.|Mike Conley]] (USA) jumped 8.63 (+3.9) on 20 June 1986 in Eugene, Oregon.\n*[[Jeff Henderson (athlete)|Jeff Henderson]] (USA) jumped 8.59 (+2.9) on 3 July 2016 in Eugene, Oregon.\n*[[Jason Grimes]] (USA) jumped 8.57 (+5.2) on 27 June 1982 in Durham, North Carolina.\n*[[Kevin Dilworth]] (USA) jumped 8.53 (+4.9) on 27 April 2002 in Fort-de-France, Martinique.\n\n===Women===\n* {{As of|2020|02|01}}.<ref name=AlltimeWO>[http://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/jumps/long-jump/outdoor/women/senior Long Jump \u2013 women \u2013 senior \u2013 outdoor]. IAAF. Retrieved on 25 January 2014.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Mark !! Wind (m/s) !! Athlete !! Date !! Place !! Ref\n|-\n! 1\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.52}} || 1.4 || {{flagathlete|[[Galina Chistyakova]]|URS}} || 11 June 1988 || [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]] ||\n|-\n! 2\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.49}} || 1.3 || {{flagathlete|[[Jackie Joyner-Kersee]]|USA}} || 22 May 1994 || [[New York City]] ||\n|-\n! 3\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.48}} || 1.2 || {{flagathlete|[[Heike Drechsler]]|GDR}} || 9 July 1988 || [[Neubrandenburg]] ||\n|-\n! 4\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.43}} || 1.4 || {{flagathlete|[[Ani\u015foara Cu\u015fmir-Stanciu|Ani\u015foara Cu\u015fmir]]|ROM|1965}} || 4 June 1983 || [[Bucharest]] ||\n|-\n! 5\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.42}} || 2.0 || {{flagathlete|[[Tatyana Kotova]]|RUS}} || 23 June 2002 || [[Annecy]] ||\n|-\n! 6\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.39}} || 0.5 || {{flagathlete|[[Yelena Belevskaya]]|URS}} || 18 July 1987 || [[Bryansk]] ||\n|-\n! 7\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.37}} || N/A || {{flagathlete|[[Inessa Kravets]]|UKR}} || 13 June 1992 || [[Kiev]] ||\n|-\n! 8\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.33}} || 0.4 || {{flagathlete|[[Tatyana Lebedeva]]|RUS}} || 31 July 2004 || [[Tula, Russia|Tula]] ||\n|-\n! rowspan=3 | 9\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.31}} || 1.5 || {{flagathlete|[[Olena Khlopotnova]]|URS}} || 12 September 1985 || [[Almaty|Alma Ata]] ||\n|-\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.31}} || \u22120.1 || {{flagathlete|[[Marion Jones]]|USA}} || 12 August 1998 || [[Zurich]] ||\n|-\n| {{T&Fcalc|7.31}} || 1.7 || {{flagathlete|[[Brittney Reese]]|USA}} || 2 July 2016 || [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]] || <ref>{{cite news|title=Reese\u2019s big leap highlights early action at US Olympic Trials|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/us-olympic-trials-2016-reese|publisher=IAAF|author=Roy Jordan|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n!12\n|{{T&Fcalc|7.30}}\n| \u22120.8\n|{{flagathlete|[[Malaika Mihambo]]|GER}}\n|6 October 2019\n|[[Doha]]\n|<ref>{{c