03}} || [[Niki Xanthou]]\n|18 August 1997\n|[[Bellinzona]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Czechoslovakia}}/<br>{{Flagu|Slovakia}} || {{T&Fcalc|7.01}} || [[Eva Murkov\u00e1]]\n|26 May 1984\n|[[Leningrad]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|People's Republic of China}} || {{T&Fcalc|7.01}} || [[Weili Yao]]\n|4 June 1993\n|[[Jinan]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Bulgaria}} || {{T&Fcalc|7.00}} || [[Silvia Khristova-Moneva]]\n|3 August 1986\n|[[Sofia]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Cuba}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.99}} || [[Lissette Cuza]]\n|3 June 2000\n|[[Jena]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Sweden}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.99}} || [[Erica Johansson]]\n|5 July 2000\n|[[Lausanne]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Canada}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.99}} || [[Christabel Nettey]]\n|29 May 2015\n|[[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Poland}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.97}} || [[Agata Karczmarek]]\n|6 August 1988\n|[[Lublin]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Puerto Rico}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.96}} {{AthAbbr|A}} || [[Madeline de Jesus]]\n|24 July 1988\n|[[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Denmark}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.96}} || [[Renata Nielsen]]\n|5 June 1994\n|[[Sevilla]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|South Africa}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.93}} || [[Karin Mey Melis]]\n|7 July 2007\n|[[Bad Langensalza]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Colombia}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.93}} || [[Caterine Ibarguen]]\n|9 September 2018\n|[[Ostrava]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Latvia}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.92}} || [[Ineta Rad\u0113vi\u010da]]\n|28 July 2010\n|[[Barcelona]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|British Virgin Islands}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.90}} || [[Chantel Malone]]\n|26 April 2019\n|[[Athens, Georgia|Athens]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Czech Republic}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.89}} || [[Jarmila Strej\u010dkov\u00e1]]\n|18 September 1982\n|[[Prague]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Turkey}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.87}} || [[Karin Mey Melis]]\n|31 July 2009\n|[[Leverkusen]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Estonia}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.87}} || [[Ksenija Balta]]\n|8 August 2010\n|[[Tallinn]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Hungary}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.86}} || [[T\u00fcnde Vaszi]]\n|7 August 2001\n|[[Edmonton]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Japan}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.86}} || [[Kumiko Imura]]\n|6 May 2006\n|[[Osaka]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Belgium}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.86}} || [[Nafissatou Thiam]]\n|18 August 2019\n|[[Birmingham]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Finland}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.85}} || [[Ringa Ropo-Junnila]]\n|11 August 1990\n|[[Lahti]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Switzerland}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.84}} || [[Irene Pusterla]]\n|20 August 2011\n|[[Chiasso]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Sierra Leone}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.83}} || [[Eunice Barber]]\n|9 May 1999\n|[[Reims]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|India}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.83}} || [[Anju Bobby George]]\n|27 August 2004\n|[[Athens]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Bahamas}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.83}} || [[Bianca Stuart]]\n|26 June 2015\n|[[Nassau (Bahamas)|Nassau]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Trinidad and Tobago}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.82}} || [[Rhonda Watkins]]\n|25 May 2007\n|[[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Guyana}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.81}} || [[Jennifer Inniss]]\n|18 June 1983\n|[[Indianapolis]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Uzbekistan}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.81}} || [[Yuliya Tarasova]]\n|4 June 2010\n|[[Tashkent]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Cyprus}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.80}} || [[Maroula Lambrou]]\n|25 March 1985\n|[[Limassol]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Slovenia}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.78}} || [[Nina Kolari\u010d]]\n|29 June 2008\n|[[Ptuj]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Netherlands}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.78}} || [[Dafne Schippers]]\n|26 July 2014\n|[[Amsterdam]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Syria}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.77}} || [[Ghada Shouaa]]\n|26 May 1996\n|[[G\u00f6tzis]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Korea}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.76}} || [[Soon-ok Jung]]\n|4 June 2009\n|[[Daegu]]\n|-\n|{{Flagu|Barbados}} || {{T&Fcalc|6.75}} || [[Akela Jones]]\n|14 May 2016\n|[[Fort Worth]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Cited sources==\n* {{cite book|ref=Miller|author=Stephen G. Miller|title= Ancient Greek Athletics|url=https://archive.org/details/ancientgreekathl00mill|url-access=registration|place= New Haven|publisher= Yale University Press|year= 2004|isbn=0300115296}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n | last = Guthrie\n | first = Mark\n | title = Coach Track & Field Successfully\n | publisher = Human Kinetics\n | year = 2003\n | location = Champaign, Illinois\n | pages = [https://archive.org/details/coachingtrackfie0000guth/page/149 149\u2013155]\n | isbn = 0-7360-4274-1\n | url = https://archive.org/details/coachingtrackfie0000guth/page/149\n }}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Rogers\n | first = Joseph L.\n | title = USA Track & Field Coaching Manual\n | publisher = Human Kinetics\n | year = 2000\n | location = Champaign, Illinois\n | pages = [https://archive.org/details/usatrackfieldcoa0000unse/page/141 141\u2013157]\n | isbn = 0-88011-604-8\n | url = https://archive.org/details/usatrackfieldcoa0000unse/page/141\n }}\n* {{cite video\n | people = Ernie Gregoire, Larry Myricks\n | title = World Class Track & Field Series: Long Jump\n | medium = VHS\n | publisher = Championship Books & Video Productions\n | location = Ames, Iowa\n | date= 1991 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Long jump}}\n* [http://www.iaaf.org/disciplines/throws/long-jump IAAF long jump homepage]\n* [https://iaaf.gekko.de/?a=jumps&d=long-jump IAAF list of long-jump records in XML]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4C8qG50w_rw Powell vs Lewis Tokyo 91 (video)]\n\n{{Athletics events}}\n{{Portal bar|Athletics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Jump}}\n[[Category:Long jump|*]]\n[[Category:Events in track and field]]\n[[Category:Ancient Olympic sports]]\n[[Category:Summer Olympic disciplines in athletics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Jumping sports]]\n", "name_user": "116.88.210.194", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_jump"}
{"title_page": "Italian War of 1551\u20131559", "text_new": "{{short description|1550s war between France and the Holy Roman Empire}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Italian War of 1551\u20131559\n| partof      = the [[Italian Wars]]\n| image       = Scannagallo Vasari.jpg\n| image_size  = 300px\n| caption     = ''[[Battle of Marciano|The Battle of Scannagallo]]'' in 1554 by [[Giorgio Vasari]], in the [[Palazzo Vecchio]] of [[Florence]]\n| date        = 1551\u20131559\n| place       = [[France]], [[Flanders]], [[Italy]] and the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]\n| territory   = ''See [[Italian War of 1551\u20131559#Clauses|\u00a7 Territorial changes]]''\n| result      = [[Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis]] (1559)\n\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Kingdom of France|valois}}\n* {{flagicon|Old Swiss Confederacy}} [[Swiss mercenaries]]\n{{flagicon image|Bandera de Siena.png}} [[Republic of Siena]]\n[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| combatant2  = {{plainlist}}\n* {{flag|Holy Roman Empire}}\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Spanish Empire]]\n* [[File:Mantua Flag 1575-1707 (new).svg|border|22px]] [[Duchy of Mantua]]\n* {{flag|Kingdom of England}}\n* [[File:Bandiera del granducato di Toscana (1562-1737 ).png|border|22px]] [[Duchy of Florence]]\n* {{flag|Duchy of Savoy}}\n{{endplainlist}}\n| combatant3  =\n| commander1  = {{plainlist}}\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Henry II of France|Henry II]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Francis, Duke of Guise|Duke of Guise]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Anne de Montmorency|Duke of Montmorency]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Paul de Thermes]]\n* {{flagicon image|Bandera de Siena.png}} {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Piero Strozzi]]\n* [[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman I]]\n* [[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Koca Sinan Pasha]]\n* [[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Dragut]]\n{{endplainlist}}\n| commander2  = {{plainlist}}\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles I-V]]\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]]\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Ferrante Gonzaga|Ferrante I Gonzaga]]\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[William the Silent|William of Orange]]\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Philip II of Spain|Philip II]]\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Fernando \u00c1lvarez de Toledo, 3rd Duke of Alba|Duke of Alba]]\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Lamoral, Count of Egmont|Count of Egmont]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Mary I of England|Mary I]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Thomas Wentworth, 2nd Baron Wentworth|Baron Wentworth]]\n* [[File:Bandiera del granducato di Toscana (1562-1737 ).png|border|22px]] [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]]\n* [[File:Bandiera del granducato di Toscana (1562-1737 ).png|border|22px]] [[Gian Giacomo Medici]]\n* {{flagicon|Duchy of Savoy}} {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy|Emmanuel Philibert of Savoy]]\n{{endplainlist}}\n|\n| notes       =\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Italian War of 1551-1559}}\n{{Campaignbox Italian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Anglo-French wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Franco-Spanish wars}}\n\nThe '''Italian War of 1551\u20131559''', sometimes known as the '''Habsburg\u2013Valois War''' and the '''Last Italian War''', began when [[Henry II of France]], who had succeeded [[Francis I of France|Francis I]] to the throne, declared war against Holy Roman Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] with the intent of recapturing Italy and ensuring French, rather than [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]], domination of European affairs. Historians have emphasized the importance of gunpowder technology, new styles of fortification to resist cannon fire, and the increased professionalization of the soldiers.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Reader_s_Guide_to_Military_History.html?id=VT7fAQAAQBAJ |title=Reader's Guide to Military History |date=2013-10-31 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-95970-8 |editor-last=Messenger |editor-first=Charles |pages=635\u2013636 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\n===Mediterranean campaigns===\n[[File:Bataille de Renty.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Henry II remitting the [[Order of Saint-Michel]] to Marshall de Tavannes after the [[Battle of Renty]], on 13 August 1554]]\nHenry II sealed [[Franco-Ottoman alliance|a treaty]] with [[Suleiman the Magnificent]] in order to cooperate against the Habsburgs in the Mediterranean.<ref name=\"Miller, p.2\">Miller, p.2</ref> This was triggered by the conquest of [[Mahdiya]] by the Genoese Admiral [[Andrea Doria]] on 8 September 1550, for the account of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]. The alliance allowed Henry II to push for French conquests towards the [[Rhine]], while a [[Franco-Ottoman alliance|Franco-Ottoman fleet]] defended southern France.<ref>{{Cite book |editor-last=Lambton |editor-first=Ann Katherine Swynford |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4AuJvd2Tyt8C&pg=PA328 |title=The Cambridge History of Islam: The central Islamic lands since 1918. Vol. 1B |editor2-last=Lewis |editor2-first=Bernard |date=1977 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-29135-4 |pages=328 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe 1551 Ottoman [[Siege of Tripoli (1551)|Siege of Tripoli]] was the first step of the all-out Italian War of 1551\u201359 in the European theater, and in the Mediterranean the French galleys of [[Marseille]] were ordered to join the Ottoman fleet.<ref name=\"Braudel\">{{Cite book |last=Braudel |first=Fernand |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LPp63EKb9moC&pg=PA920 |title=The Mediterranean and the Mediterranean World in the Age of Philip II |date=1995 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-20330-3 |volume=2 |pages=920}}</ref> In 1552, when Henry II attacked Charles V, the Ottomans sent 100 galleys to the Western Mediterranean,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Black |first=Jeremy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dz_JaYpWSGUC&pg=PA177 |title=European Warfare, 1494-1660 |date=2002 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-415-27532-3 |pages=177 |language=en}}</ref> which were accompanied by three French galleys under [[Gabriel de Luetz d'Aramon]] in their raids along the coast of [[Calabria]] in Southern Italy, capturing the city of [[Reggio Calabria|Reggio]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Sharon |url=http://archive.org/details/historyenglandf09turngoog |title=The history of England: from the earliest period to the death of Elizabeth |date=1839 |publisher=Longman, Orme, Brown, Green, and Longmans |location=London |pages=311}}</ref> In the [[Battle of Ponza (1552)|Battle of Ponza]] in front of the island of [[Ponza]], the fleet met with 40 galleys of [[Andrea Doria]], and managed to vanquish the Genoese and capture seven galleys. This alliance would also lead to the combined [[Invasion of Corsica (1553)|Invasion of Corsica]] in 1553. The Ottomans continued harassing the Habsburg possessions with various operations in the Mediterranean, such as the [[Ottoman invasion of the Balearic Islands (1558)|Ottoman invasion of the Balearic islands]] in 1558, following a request by Henry II.<ref>Setton, pp. 698''ff''.</ref>\n\n===Land campaigns===\nOn the Continental front, Henry II allied with German Protestant princes at the [[Treaty of Chambord]] in 1552. An early offensive into [[Lorraine (province)|Lorraine]] was successful, with Henry capturing the three episcopal cities of [[Metz]], [[Toul]], and [[Verdun]], and securing them by defeating the invading Habsburg army at the [[Battle of Renty]] in 1554. However, the French invasion of [[Tuscany]] in 1553, in support of [[Siena]] attacked by an imperial\u2010Florentine army, was defeated at the [[Battle of Marciano]] by [[Gian Giacomo Medici]] in 1554.  Siena fell in 1555 and eventually became part of the [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany]] founded by [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany]].<ref name=\"Oman\">{{Cite book |last=Oman |first=Charles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XHZUDwAAQBAJ |title=A History of the Art of War in the Sixteenth Century |date=2018-04-03 |publisher=Pickle Partners Publishing |isbn=978-1-78912-137-7 |author-link=Charles Oman |orig-year=1937 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{pn|date=April 2020}}\n\nA treaty in Vaucelles was signed on 5 February 1556 between Charles V and Henry II of France.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Robertson |first=William |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xDpAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA279&dq=Vaucelles+Charles+V&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIxMfjn6XlAhUCDewKHQNuCMsQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Vaucelles%2520Charles%2520V&f=false |title=The history of the reign of emperor Charles V, book 8-12 |last2=Stewart |first2=Dugald |date=1840 |publisher=T. Cadell |pages=279}}</ref> After emperor Charles' abdication in 1556 split the Habsburg empire between Philip II of Spain and [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]], the focus of the war shifted to [[Flanders]]. However, the truce was broken shortly afterwards. Pope Paul IV was displeased and urged Henry II to join the Papal States in an invasion of Spanish Naples. On 1 September 1556, Philip II responded by preemptively invading the Papal States with 12,000 men under the Duke of Alba, but French forces approaching from the north were defeated and forced to withdraw at Civitella in August 1557.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Woodward |first=Geoffrey |title=Philip II |date=2013 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=1317897730 |location=London, New York |chapter=8}}</ref> The Spanish attempted to blockade Rome by occupying the port of Ostia, but were driven back by the Papal armies in a surprise attack. However, when French troops were unable to come to their aid, the Papal armies were left exposed and were defeated, with Spanish troops arriving at the edge of Rome. Out of fear of another sack of Rome, Paul IV agreed to the Duke of Alba's demand for the Papal States to declare neutrality. Emperor Charles V criticized the peace agreement as being overly generous to the Pope.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pattenden |first1=Miles |title=Pius IV and the Fall of The Carafa: Nepotism and Papal Authority in Counter-Reformation Rome |date=2013 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=0191649619 |pages=21-22}}</ref>\n\nPhilip, in conjunction with [[Emmanuel Philibert]] of [[Savoy]], defeated the French at [[Battle of St. Quentin (1557)|St. Quentin]]. England's entry into the war later that year led to the French capture of [[Calais]], and French armies plundered Spanish possessions in the [[Low Countries]]. Nonetheless, Henry was forced to accept a peace agreement in which he renounced any further claims to Italy.<ref name=\"Oman\" />{{pn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe wars ended for other reasons, including \"the Double Default of 1557\", when the Spanish Empire, followed quickly by the French, defaulted on its debts. In addition, Henry II had to confront a growing Protestant movement at home, which he hoped to crush.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Elliott, J.H. |title=Europe Divided: 1559\u20131598 |publisher=HarperCollins |year=1968 |isbn=978-0-06-131414-8 |pages=11}}</ref>\n\n===Military technology===\nOman (1937) argues that the inconclusive campaigns which generally lack a decisive engagement were largely due to an effective leadership and lack of offensive spirit. He notes that mercenary troops were used too often and proved unreliable. Hale emphasizes the defensive strength of [[bastion fort]]<nowiki/>s newly designed at angles to dissipate cannon fire. Cavalry, which had traditionally used shock tactics to overawe the infantry, largely abandoned them and relied on pistol attacks by successive ranks of attackers. Hale notes the use of old-fashioned mass formations, which he attributes to lingering conservatism. Overall, Hale emphasizes new levels of tactical proficiency.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Hale |first=J. R. |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_New_Cambridge_Modern_History_Volume.html?id=59Pae06JSiUC |title=The New Cambridge Modern History: Volume 2, The Reformation, 1520\u20131559 |date=1990-08-02 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-34536-1 |editor-last=Elton |editor-first=G. R. |volume=2 |pages=481\u2013509 |chapter=Armies, navies and the art of war |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Finance ===\nIn 1552 Charles V had borrowed over 4 million ducats, with the [[Metz]] campaign alone costing 2.5&nbsp;million ducats. Shipments of treasure from the Indies totalled over two million ducats between 1552 and 1553. By 1554, the cash deficit for the year was calculated to be over 4.3&nbsp;million ducats, even after all tax receipts for the six ensuing years had been pledged and the proceeds spent in advance. Credit at this point began costing the crown 43 percent interest (largely financed by the [[Fugger]] and [[Welser]] banking families). By 1557 the crown was refusing payment from the Indies since even this was required for payment of the war effort (used in the offensive and Spanish victory at the battle of St. Quentin in August 1557).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lynch |first=John |title=Spain Under the Habsburgs |publisher=New York University Press |year=1984 |isbn=0-8147-5010-9 |edition=2nd |location=New York |pages=62\u201363}}</ref>\n\nFrench finances during the war were mainly financed by the increase in the [[taille]] tax, as well as indirect taxes like the [[Gabelle of salt|gabelle]] and customs fees. The French monarchy also resorted to heavy borrowings during the war from financiers at rates of 10\u201316 percent interest.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers|last=Kennedy|first=Paul|publisher=Vintage Books|year=1989|isbn=0-679-72019-7|location=New York|pages=56\u201357|quote=|via=}}</ref> The taille was estimated in collection for 1551 at around six million [[Livre tournois|livres]].{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nDuring the 1550s, Spain had an estimated military manpower of around 150,000 soldiers, whereas France had an estimated manpower of 50,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis (1559) ==\n{{wikisourcelang|en|Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis (England and France)}}\n\n=== Summary ===\nThe Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis (1559) consisted of two treaties: the first one was signed between [[Elizabeth I of England]] and [[Henri II of France]] on April 2; the second one was signed between Henri II of France and [[Philip II of Spain]] on April 3.<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/pace-di-cateau-cambresis/ Treccani encyclopedia]</ref> The two treaties also defined the conclusion of the Imperial-French wars, and therefore the end of the Habsburg-Valois conflict as a whole, with the approval of [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor]].{{efn|1=The Holy Roman Empire was not an actual signatory of the treaties of Cateau-Cambresis but they also ended Imperial conflict with France in Italy, allowing Emperor Ferdinand effectively to change his foreign policy.<ref>{{Cite book |last=DeVries |first=Kelly |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXILIMYFhXoC&pg=PA31&dq=European+warfare+Cateau+Cambresis&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk-Znz_K3lAhUQ8hQKHX7WDnQQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=European%2520warfare%2520Cateau%2520Cambresis&f=false |title=European Warfare, 1350\u20131750 |date=2010-01-28 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-88628-4 |editor-last=Tallett |editor-first=Frank |pages=31 |chapter=Warfare and the International State System |editor-last2=Trim |editor-first2=D. J. B. |df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}{{efn|1=The Peace of Cateau-Cambresis was also presented at a Diet of german princes in Augsburg, with Imperial-French talks occurring on March 21,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/calendarofstatep01grea_1/page/n729 <!-- pg=641 quote=Occasion to restore peace. -->]</ref> April 12,<ref name=\"StatePapers\">{{Cite book |last=Office |first=Great Britain Public Record |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VFwMAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA212 |title=Calendar of State Papers, Foreign Series, of the Reign of Elizabeth: Preserved in the State Paper Department of Her Majesty's Public Record Office |date=1863 |publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, Roberts, & Green |pages=212 |language=en}}</ref> and April 26.<ref name=\"StatePapers\" />}} The four monarchs did not meet in person; they were represented by ambassadors and delegations.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ruble |first=Alphonse de |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54051604.image |title=Le trait\u00e9 de Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis |year=1889}}{{pn|date=April 2020}}</ref> Some Italian states also attended the conference.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Roio |first=Anna Maria Razzoli |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A5u47hj0lTsC&pg=PA20&dq=curzio+gonzaga+cateau+cambresis&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj60N7NoK_lAhUks4sKHccpApIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=curzio%2520gonzaga%2520cateau%2520cambresis&f=false |title=Cavalieri ed eroi alla corte di Mantova: il Fido amante di Curzio Gonzaga |date=2008 |publisher=Verso l'Arte Edizioni |isbn=978-88-95894-01-0 |pages=20 |language=it}}</ref>\n\nThe peace was facilitated by the abdication of Charles V in 1556 and the division of the [[Habsburg empire]] between Spain and Austria: [[Philip II of Spain]] received the kingdoms of Spain, southern Italy ([[Kingdom of Naples|Naples]], [[Sicily]], and [[Sardinia]]) and the colonies in the Americas; and [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand of Austria]] became ruler of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] extending from [[Kingdom of Germany|Germany]] to [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)|northern Italy]], with [[suo jure]] control of the [[Danube monarchy]]. The [[Duchy of Milan]] and the [[Habsburg Netherlands]] were left in personal union to the King of Spain while continuing to be part of the Holy Roman Empire. With the end of the personal union of the Holy Roman Empire and Spain (\"Habsburg encirclement\"), France was open to peace talks. A truce was reached in Vaucelles around 1556, but it was broken shortly after. The condition of economic and religious turmoil in which the war resumed forced the parties to make peace in 1559.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Knecht |first=Robert Jean |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Catherine_De_Medici.html?id=qAojAQAAIAAJ |title=Catherine De' Medici |date=1998 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0-582-08242-7 |pages=54 |author-link=Robert Knecht}}</ref> \n\nBy the terms of the treaties, France ended military operations in the [[Spanish Netherlands]] and the [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)#Imperial fiefs|Imperial fiefs of northern Italy]] bringing an end to most of the French occupation in Corsica, Tuscany and Piedmont. England and the Habsburgs, in exchange, ended their opposition to French occupation of the [[Pale of Calais]], the [[Three Bishoprics]], and a number of fortresses. For [[Spain]], despite no new gains and the restoration of some occupied territories to France, the peace was a positive result as it confirmed its control of the [[Habsburg Netherlands]], the [[Duchy of Milan]], and southern Italy (Sardinia, Naples, Sicily). [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] left the Three Bishoprics under French occupation, but the Netherlands and most of northern Italy remained part of the Holy Roman Empire in the form of imperial fiefs. Furthermore, his position of Holy Roman Emperor was recognized by the Pope who had refused to do so as long as the war between France and the Habsburgs continued. England fared poorly during the war, and the loss of its last stronghold on the continent damaged its reputation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tudorsociety.com/an-overview-of-the-results-of-the-treaty-of-cateau-cambresis-1569/ |title=An Overview of the Results of the Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis 1559 |last=Ridgway |first=Claire |date=2017-04-03 |website=The Tudor Society |df=dmy-all |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the conflict, Italy was therefore divided between [[viceroyalties]] of the Spanish Habsburgs in the south and [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)|formal fiefs]] of the Austrian Habsburgs in the north. The imperial states were ruled by the [[Doria family|Doria]] in Genoa, the [[House of Medici|Medici]] in Tuscany, the Spanish Habsburgs in Milan, the [[House of Farnese|Farnese]] in Parma, the [[House of Este|Estensi]] in Modena, and an ''Italianized'' [[House of Savoy]] in Piedmont. The southern Kingdoms of Naples, Sicily and Sardinia were under direct rule of the Spanish Habsburgs. This situation continued until the European wars of succession of the 18th century, when northern Italy passed to the Austrian house of [[Habsburg-Lorraine]] and the south passed to the [[Spanish Bourbons]]. The Papacy in [[central Italy]] maintained major [[baroque|cultural]] and political influence during the [[Catholic Reformation]] initiated by the conclusion of the Tridentine council (resumed by the terms of the treaty).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mallett |first=Michael |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnnJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA298&dq=dual+protection+King+of+spain+and+emperor&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzipHsvMTjAhUN-6QKHa5qCYgQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=dual%2520protection%2520King%2520of%2520spain%2520and%2520emperor&f=false |title=The Italian Wars 1494-1559: War, State and Society in Early Modern Europe |last2=Shaw |first2=Christine |date=2014-06-11 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-89939-6 |pages=298 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Clauses ===\n[[File:It\u00e0lia - Fin dei Gu\u00e8rras d'It\u00e0lia (1559).png|thumb|Map of Italy in 1559 after the Treaties of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis]]\nAccording to the treaties signed in [[Le Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis]]:\n*Henry II of France renounced his hereditary claim to the [[Duchy of Milan]] (held by Spain and fief of the Holy Roman Empire)<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/event/Peace-of-Cateau-Cambresis |title=Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis |author=Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica |work=Encyclopaedia Britannica |date=27 March 2019 |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref> and recognised Spanish control over the [[Kingdom of Naples]],<ref name=\"Setton709\"/> the [[Kingdom of Sicily]], and the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sarti |first=Roland |date=2004 |title=Italy: A Reference Guide from the Renaissance to the Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xhoLorFC1iwC&pg=PA189 |location=New York |publisher=Facts on File, Inc. |page=189 |isbn=9780816074747 |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n*France ceded the island of [[Corsica]] to the [[Republic of Genoa]] (fief of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] and allied with Spain).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/> French and Genoese merchants were granted full access to each other's ports.<ref name=\"Setton709\">Setton, 709.</ref>\n*France gave the [[Duchy of Savoy]]\u2013[[Principality of Piedmont|Piedmont]] (allied with Spain and fief of the Holy Roman Empire) back to [[Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy]]<ref name=\"Britannica\"/> due to his victory at [[Battle of St. Quentin (1557)|St. Quentin]]. Savoy declared neutrality between the Spain and France, and later moved its capital to [[Turin]]. \n*France retained five fortresses in Northern Italy, including those near [[Turin]], [[Saluzzo]] and [[Pinerolo]] (Pignerol).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/><ref name=\"Visconti\">{{Cite book |last=Visconti |first=Joseph |date=2003 |title=The Waldensian Way to God |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4TmARujuu-EC&pg=PA299 |location= |publisher=Xulon Press |page=299\u2013300 |isbn=9781591607922 |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n*France retained the [[Three Bishoprics]] of [[Bishopric of Toul|Toul]], [[Bishopric of Metz|Metz]] and [[Bishopric of Verdun|Verdun]] (seized from Charles V during the [[Second Schmalkaldic War]] in 1552).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/>\n*France retained the [[Pale of Calais]] (seized from England in 1558).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/>\n*France retained [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint Quentin]], [[Ham, Somme|Ham]], [[Le Catelet]] and other places in northern France seized by Spain during the war.<ref name=\"Setton708\"/>\n*The [[Duchy of Florence]] (fief of the Holy Roman Empire and allied with Spain) absorbed the [[Republic of Siena]] (allied with France) into what became the [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany|Duchy of Tuscany]].<ref name=\"Setton709\"/>\n*The [[March of Montferrat]] was given back to [[Guglielmo Gonzaga, Duke of Mantua]] (fief of the Holy Roman Empire and allied with Spain).<ref name=\"Setton708\"/>\n* All signatories of the treaty needed to 'purge their lands of heresy'; in other words, all their subjects had to be forcefully reverted to Catholicism. When pressured by [[Spanish Empire|Spain]] to implement this obligation, [[Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy]] proclaimed the Edict of Nice (15 February 1560), prohibiting Protestantism on pains of a large fine, enslavement or banishment, which soon led to an armed revolt by the Protestant [[Waldensians]] in his domain that would last until July 1561.<ref name=\"Visconti\"/>\n*Henri II of France and Philip II of Spain agreed in the treaty to ask the Pope and Emperor Ferdinand to reconvene the [[Council of Trent]]. The peace allowed Ferdinand to be recognized as Emperor by the Pope. <ref name=\"Setton708\">Setton, 708.</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Thalheimer |first=Mary Elsie |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=imEAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA208&dq=Pope+pius+IV+recognizes+Ferdinand&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik7YCfpf3kAhVQ3KQKHZ-GD3sQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Pope%2520pius%2520IV%2520recognizes%2520Ferdinand&f=false |title=A Manual of Medi\u00e6val and Modern History |date=1874 |publisher=Wilson Hinkle & Company |pages=208}}</ref>{{efn|1=[[Paolo Sarpi]], Istoria del Concilio Tridentino, Book 5. Ferdinand became Emperor in 1556 after the abdication of Charles V, ratified in 1558, but the Pope refused to recognize him until the Peace of 1559.{{cn|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n=== Celebrations ===\n[[Emmanuel Philibert]], Duke of [[Savoy]] married [[Margaret of France, Duchess of Berry]], the sister of [[Henry II of France]]. Philip II of Spain married [[Elisabeth of Valois|Elisabeth]], the daughter of Henry II of France.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Konnert |first=Mark |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t6TXB9RbwbYC&pg=PA122 |title=Early Modern Europe: The Age of Religious War, 1559\u20131715 |date=2008-08-23 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |isbn=978-1-4426-0004-1 |pages=122 |language=en}}</ref> Henry died during a [[tournament (medieval)|tournament]] when a sliver from the shattered lance of [[Gabriel Montgomery]], captain of the Scottish Guard at the French Court, pierced his eye and entered his brain. The death of Henry II caused his 15-year-old son Francis II to take the throne, beginning a period of political instability that ultimately led to the [[French Wars of Religion]].\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Cateau-Cambresis.jpg|The Peace of Cateau-Cambresis (1559). [[Henry II of France]] and [[Philip II of Spain]] were in reality absent, and the peace was signed by their ambassadors.\nFile:Tournament between Henry II and Lorges.jpg|The fatal tournament between [[Henry II of France|Henry II]] and [[Gabriel, comte de Montgomery|Montgomery]] (Lord of \"Lorges\")\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Franco-Ottoman alliance]]\n* [[Historical states of Italy#Italy in the year 1559|States of Italy in 1559]]\n* [[Elizabeth I of England]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* Baumgartner, Frederic J. ''Henry II, King of France 1547\u20131559'' (Duke Univ Press, 1988).\n* Oman, Charles W.C. ''A History of the Art of War in the Sixteenth Century'' (1937).\n* Pepper, Simon, and Nicholas Adams. ''Firearms & Fortifications: Military Architecture and Siege Warfare in Sixteenth-century Siena'' (University of Chicago Press, 1986).\n* Setton, Kenneth M. [https://books.google.com/books?id=SrUNi2m_qZAC&pg=PA698 ''The Papacy and the Levant (1204\u20131571)''] (American Philosophical Society, 1984).\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Cateau-Cambr%C3%A9sis_(England_and_France) Modern English version of the Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis between England and France]\n*[https://books.openedition.org/cvz/642 The original French-language Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis between France and Spain]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Italian War of 1551-1559}}\n[[Category:1550s conflicts]]\n[[Category:1550s in Italy]]\n[[Category:1551 in Italy]]\n[[Category:1556 in law]]\n[[Category:1559 in Italy]]\n[[Category:1559 in law]]\n[[Category:1550s in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:16th-century military history of the Kingdom of England]]\n[[Category:16th-century military history of France]]\n[[Category:16th-century military history of Spain]]\n[[Category:Italian Wars]]\n[[Category:Wars involving England]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1550s war between France and the Holy Roman Empire}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Italian War of 1551\u20131559\n| partof      = the [[Italian Wars]]\n| image       = Scannagallo Vasari.jpg\n| image_size  = 300px\n| caption     = ''[[Battle of Marciano|The Battle of Scannagallo]]'' in 1554 by [[Giorgio Vasari]], in the [[Palazzo Vecchio]] of [[Florence]]\n| date        = 1551\u20131559\n| place       = [[France]], [[Flanders]], [[Italy]] and the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]\n| territory   = ''See [[Italian War of 1551\u20131559#Clauses|\u00a7 Territorial changes]]''\n| result      = [[Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis]] (1559)\n\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Kingdom of France|valois}}\n* {{flagicon|Old Swiss Confederacy}} [[Swiss mercenaries]]\n{{flagicon image|Bandera de Siena.png}} [[Republic of Siena]]\n[[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| combatant2  = {{plainlist}}\n* {{flag|Holy Roman Empire}}\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Spanish Empire]]\n* [[File:Mantua Flag 1575-1707 (new).svg|border|22px]] [[Duchy of Mantua]]\n* {{flag|Kingdom of England}}\n* [[File:Bandiera del granducato di Toscana (1562-1737 ).png|border|22px]] [[Duchy of Florence]]\n* {{flag|Duchy of Savoy}}\n{{endplainlist}}\n| combatant3  =\n| commander1  = {{plainlist}}\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Henry II of France|Henry II]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Francis, Duke of Guise|Duke of Guise]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Anne de Montmorency|Duke of Montmorency]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Paul de Thermes]]\n* {{flagicon image|Bandera de Siena.png}} {{flagicon|Kingdom of France|valois}} [[Piero Strozzi]]\n* [[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman I]]\n* [[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Koca Sinan Pasha]]\n* [[File:Flag of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1517).svg|25px]] [[Dragut]]\n{{endplainlist}}\n| commander2  = {{plainlist}}\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles I-V]]\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]]\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Ferrante Gonzaga|Ferrante I Gonzaga]]\n* {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[William the Silent|William of Orange]]\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Philip II of Spain|Philip II]]\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Fernando \u00c1lvarez de Toledo, 3rd Duke of Alba|Duke of Alba]]\n* {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Lamoral, Count of Egmont|Count of Egmont]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Mary I of England|Mary I]]\n* {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Thomas Wentworth, 2nd Baron Wentworth|Baron Wentworth]]\n* [[File:Bandiera del granducato di Toscana (1562-1737 ).png|border|22px]] [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]]\n* [[File:Bandiera del granducato di Toscana (1562-1737 ).png|border|22px]] [[Gian Giacomo Medici]]\n* {{flagicon|Duchy of Savoy}} {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy|Emmanuel Philibert of Savoy]]\n{{endplainlist}}\n|\n| notes       =\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Italian War of 1551-1559}}\n{{Campaignbox Italian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Anglo-French wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Franco-Spanish wars}}\n\nThe '''Italian War of 1551\u20131559''', sometimes known as the '''Habsburg\u2013Valois War''' and the '''Last Italian War''', began when [[Henry II of France]], who had succeeded [[Francis I of France|Francis I]] to the throne, declared war against Holy Roman Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] with the intent of recapturing Italy and ensuring French, rather than [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]], domination of European affairs. Historians have emphasized the importance of gunpowder technology, new styles of fortification to resist cannon fire, and the increased professionalization of the soldiers.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Reader_s_Guide_to_Military_History.html?id=VT7fAQAAQBAJ |title=Reader's Guide to Military History |date=2013-10-31 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-95970-8 |editor-last=Messenger |editor-first=Charles |pages=635\u2013636 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\n===Mediterranean campaigns===\n[[File:Bataille de Renty.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Henry II remitting the [[Order of Saint-Michel]] to Marshall de Tavannes after the [[Battle of Renty]], on 13 August 1554]]\nHenry II sealed [[Franco-Ottoman alliance|a treaty]] with [[Suleiman the Magnificent]] in order to cooperate against the Habsburgs in the Mediterranean.<ref name=\"Miller, p.2\">Miller, p.2</ref> This was triggered by the conquest of [[Mahdiya]] by the Genoese Admiral [[Andrea Doria]] on 8 September 1550, for the account of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]. The alliance allowed Henry II to push for French conquests towards the [[Rhine]], while a [[Franco-Ottoman alliance|Franco-Ottoman fleet]] defended southern France.<ref>{{Cite book |editor-last=Lambton |editor-first=Ann Katherine Swynford |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4AuJvd2Tyt8C&pg=PA328 |title=The Cambridge History of Islam: The central Islamic lands since 1918. Vol. 1B |editor2-last=Lewis |editor2-first=Bernard |date=1977 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-29135-4 |pages=328 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe 1551 Ottoman [[Siege of Tripoli (1551)|Siege of Tripoli]] was the first step of the all-out Italian War of 1551\u201359 in the European theater, and in the Mediterranean the French galleys of [[Marseille]] were ordered to join the Ottoman fleet.<ref name=\"Braudel\">{{Cite book |last=Braudel |first=Fernand |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LPp63EKb9moC&pg=PA920 |title=The Mediterranean and the Mediterranean World in the Age of Philip II |date=1995 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-20330-3 |volume=2 |pages=920}}</ref> In 1552, when Henry II attacked Charles V, the Ottomans sent 100 galleys to the Western Mediterranean,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Black |first=Jeremy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dz_JaYpWSGUC&pg=PA177 |title=European Warfare, 1494-1660 |date=2002 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-415-27532-3 |pages=177 |language=en}}</ref> which were accompanied by three French galleys under [[Gabriel de Luetz d'Aramon]] in their raids along the coast of [[Calabria]] in Southern Italy, capturing the city of [[Reggio Calabria|Reggio]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Sharon |url=http://archive.org/details/historyenglandf09turngoog |title=The history of England: from the earliest period to the death of Elizabeth |date=1839 |publisher=Longman, Orme, Brown, Green, and Longmans |location=London |pages=311}}</ref> In the [[Battle of Ponza (1552)|Battle of Ponza]] in front of the island of [[Ponza]], the fleet met with 40 galleys of [[Andrea Doria]], and managed to vanquish the Genoese and capture seven galleys. This alliance would also lead to the combined [[Invasion of Corsica (1553)|Invasion of Corsica]] in 1553. The Ottomans continued harassing the Habsburg possessions with various operations in the Mediterranean, such as the [[Ottoman invasion of the Balearic Islands (1558)|Ottoman invasion of the Balearic islands]] in 1558, following a request by Henry II.<ref>Setton, pp. 698''ff''.</ref>\n\n===Land campaigns===\nOn the Continental front, Henry II allied with German Protestant princes at the [[Treaty of Chambord]] in 1552. An early offensive into [[Lorraine (province)|Lorraine]] was successful, with Henry capturing the three episcopal cities of [[Metz]], [[Toul]], and [[Verdun]], and securing them by defeating the invading Habsburg army at the [[Battle of Renty]] in 1554. However, the French invasion of [[Tuscany]] in 1553, in support of [[Siena]] attacked by an imperial\u2010Florentine army, was defeated at the [[Battle of Marciano]] by [[Gian Giacomo Medici]] in 1554.  Siena fell in 1555 and eventually became part of the [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany]] founded by [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany]].<ref name=\"Oman\">{{Cite book |last=Oman |first=Charles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XHZUDwAAQBAJ |title=A History of the Art of War in the Sixteenth Century |date=2018-04-03 |publisher=Pickle Partners Publishing |isbn=978-1-78912-137-7 |author-link=Charles Oman |orig-year=1937 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{pn|date=April 2020}}\n\nA treaty in Vaucelles was signed on 5 February 1556 between Charles V and Henry II of France.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Robertson |first=William |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xDpAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA279&dq=Vaucelles+Charles+V&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIxMfjn6XlAhUCDewKHQNuCMsQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Vaucelles%2520Charles%2520V&f=false |title=The history of the reign of the emperor Charles V, book 8-12 |last2=Stewart |first2=Dugald |date=1840 |publisher=T. Cadell |pages=279}}</ref> After Charles' abdication in 1556 split the Habsburg empire between Philip II of Spain and [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]], the focus of the war shifted to [[Flanders]]. However, the truce was broken shortly afterwards. Pope Paul IV was displeased and urged Henry II to join the Papal States in an invasion of Spanish Naples. On 1 September 1556, Philip II responded by preemptively invading the Papal States with 12,000 men under the Duke of Alba, but French forces approaching from the north were defeated and forced to withdraw at Civitella in August 1557.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Woodward |first=Geoffrey |title=Philip II |date=2013 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=1317897730 |location=London, New York |chapter=8}}</ref> The Spanish attempted to blockade Rome by occupying the port of Ostia but were driven back by the Papal armies in a surprise attack. However, when French troops were unable to come to their aid, the Papal armies were left exposed and were defeated, with Spanish troops arriving at the edge of Rome. Out of fear of another sack of Rome, Paul IV agreed to the Duke of Alba's demand for the Papal States to declare neutrality. Emperor Charles V criticized the peace agreement as being overly generous to the Pope.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pattenden |first1=Miles |title=Pius IV and the Fall of The Carafa: Nepotism and Papal Authority in Counter-Reformation Rome |date=2013 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=0191649619 |pages=21-22}}</ref>\n\nPhilip, in conjunction with [[Emmanuel Philibert]] of [[Savoy]], defeated the French at [[Battle of St. Quentin (1557)|St. Quentin]]. England's entry into the war later that year led to the French capture of [[Calais]], and French armies plundered Spanish possessions in the [[Low Countries]]. Nonetheless, Henry was forced to accept a peace agreement in which he renounced any further claims to Italy.<ref name=\"Oman\" />{{pn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe wars ended for other reasons, including the Double Default of 1557, when the Spanish Empire, followed quickly by the French, defaulted on its debts. In addition, Henry had to confront a growing Protestant movement at home, which he hoped to crush.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Elliott, J.H. |title=Europe Divided: 1559\u20131598 |publisher=HarperCollins |year=1968 |isbn=978-0-06-131414-8 |pages=11}}</ref>\n\n===Military technology===\nOman (1937) argues that the inconclusive campaigns which generally lack a decisive engagement were largely due to an effective leadership and lack of offensive spirit. He notes that mercenary troops were used too often and proved unreliable. Hale emphasizes the defensive strength of [[bastion fort]]<nowiki/>s newly designed at angles to dissipate cannon fire. Cavalry, which had traditionally used shock tactics to overawe the infantry, largely abandoned them and relied on pistol attacks by successive ranks of attackers. Hale notes the use of old-fashioned mass formations, which he attributes to lingering conservatism. Overall, Hale emphasizes new levels of tactical proficiency.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Hale |first=J. R. |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_New_Cambridge_Modern_History_Volume.html?id=59Pae06JSiUC |title=The New Cambridge Modern History: Volume 2, The Reformation, 1520\u20131559 |date=1990-08-02 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-34536-1 |editor-last=Elton |editor-first=G. R. |volume=2 |pages=481\u2013509 |chapter=Armies, navies and the art of war |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Finance ===\nIn 1552 Charles V had borrowed over 4 million ducats, with the [[Metz]] campaign alone costing 2.5&nbsp;million ducats. Shipments of treasure from the Indies totalled over two million ducats between 1552 and 1553. By 1554, the cash deficit for the year was calculated to be over 4.3&nbsp;million ducats, even after all tax receipts for the six ensuing years had been pledged and the proceeds spent in advance. Credit at this point began costing the crown 43 percent interest (largely financed by the [[Fugger]] and [[Welser]] banking families). By 1557 the crown was refusing payment from the Indies since even this was required for payment of the war effort (used in the offensive and Spanish victory at the battle of St. Quentin in August 1557).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lynch |first=John |title=Spain Under the Habsburgs |publisher=New York University Press |year=1984 |isbn=0-8147-5010-9 |edition=2nd |location=New York |pages=62\u201363}}</ref>\n\nFrench finances during the war were mainly financed by the increase in the [[taille]] tax, as well as indirect taxes like the [[Gabelle of salt|gabelle]] and customs fees. The French monarchy also resorted to heavy borrowings during the war from financiers at rates of 10\u201316 percent interest.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers|last=Kennedy|first=Paul|publisher=Vintage Books|year=1989|isbn=0-679-72019-7|location=New York|pages=56\u201357|quote=|via=}}</ref> The taille was estimated in collection for 1551 at around six million [[Livre tournois|livres]].{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nDuring the 1550s, Spain had an estimated military manpower of around 150,000 soldiers, whereas France had an estimated manpower of 50,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis (1559) ==\n{{wikisourcelang|en|Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis (England and France)}}\n\n=== Summary ===\nThe Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis (1559) consisted of two treaties: the first one was signed between [[Elizabeth I of England]] and [[Henri II of France]] on April 2; the second one was signed between Henri II of France and [[Philip II of Spain]] on April 3.<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/pace-di-cateau-cambresis/ Treccani encyclopedia]</ref> The two treaties also defined the conclusion of the Imperial-French wars, and therefore the end of the Habsburg-Valois conflict as a whole, with the approval of [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor]].{{efn|1=The Holy Roman Empire was not an actual signatory of the treaties of Cateau-Cambresis but they also ended Imperial conflict with France in Italy, allowing Emperor Ferdinand effectively to change his foreign policy.<ref>{{Cite book |last=DeVries |first=Kelly |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXILIMYFhXoC&pg=PA31&dq=European+warfare+Cateau+Cambresis&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk-Znz_K3lAhUQ8hQKHX7WDnQQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=European%2520warfare%2520Cateau%2520Cambresis&f=false |title=European Warfare, 1350\u20131750 |date=2010-01-28 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-88628-4 |editor-last=Tallett |editor-first=Frank |pages=31 |chapter=Warfare and the International State System |editor-last2=Trim |editor-first2=D. J. B. |df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}{{efn|1=The Peace of Cateau-Cambresis was also presented at a Diet of german princes in Augsburg, with Imperial-French talks occurring on March 21,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/calendarofstatep01grea_1/page/n729 <!-- pg=641 quote=Occasion to restore peace. -->]</ref> April 12,<ref name=\"StatePapers\">{{Cite book |last=Office |first=Great Britain Public Record |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VFwMAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA212 |title=Calendar of State Papers, Foreign Series, of the Reign of Elizabeth: Preserved in the State Paper Department of Her Majesty's Public Record Office |date=1863 |publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, Roberts, & Green |pages=212 |language=en}}</ref> and April 26.<ref name=\"StatePapers\" />}} The four monarchs did not meet in person; they were represented by ambassadors and delegations.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ruble |first=Alphonse de |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54051604.image |title=Le trait\u00e9 de Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis |year=1889}}{{pn|date=April 2020}}</ref> Some Italian states also attended the conference.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Roio |first=Anna Maria Razzoli |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A5u47hj0lTsC&pg=PA20&dq=curzio+gonzaga+cateau+cambresis&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj60N7NoK_lAhUks4sKHccpApIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=curzio%2520gonzaga%2520cateau%2520cambresis&f=false |title=Cavalieri ed eroi alla corte di Mantova: il Fido amante di Curzio Gonzaga |date=2008 |publisher=Verso l'Arte Edizioni |isbn=978-88-95894-01-0 |pages=20 |language=it}}</ref>\n\nThe peace was facilitated by the abdication of Charles V in 1556 and the division of the [[Habsburg empire]] between Spain and Austria: [[Philip II of Spain]] received the kingdoms of Spain, southern Italy ([[Kingdom of Naples|Naples]], [[Sicily]], and [[Sardinia]]) and the colonies in the Americas; and [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand of Austria]] became ruler of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] extending from [[Kingdom of Germany|Germany]] to [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)|northern Italy]], with [[suo jure]] control of the [[Danube monarchy]]. The [[Duchy of Milan]] and the [[Habsburg Netherlands]] were left in personal union to the King of Spain while continuing to be part of the Holy Roman Empire. With the end of the personal union of the Holy Roman Empire and Spain (\"Habsburg encirclement\"), France was open to peace talks. A truce was reached in Vaucelles around 1556, but it was broken shortly after. The condition of economic and religious turmoil in which the war resumed forced the parties to make peace in 1559.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Knecht |first=Robert Jean |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Catherine_De_Medici.html?id=qAojAQAAIAAJ |title=Catherine De' Medici |date=1998 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0-582-08242-7 |pages=54 |author-link=Robert Knecht}}</ref> \n\nBy the terms of the treaties, France ended military operations in the [[Spanish Netherlands]] and the [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)#Imperial fiefs|Imperial fiefs of northern Italy]] bringing an end to most of the French occupation in Corsica, Tuscany and Piedmont. England and the Habsburgs, in exchange, ended their opposition to French occupation of the [[Pale of Calais]], the [[Three Bishoprics]], and a number of fortresses. For [[Spain]], despite no new gains and the restoration of some occupied territories to France, the peace was a positive result as it confirmed its control of the [[Habsburg Netherlands]], the [[Duchy of Milan]], and southern Italy (Sardinia, Naples, Sicily). [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] left the Three Bishoprics under French occupation, but the Netherlands and most of northern Italy remained part of the Holy Roman Empire in the form of imperial fiefs. Furthermore, his position of Holy Roman Emperor was recognized by the Pope who had refused to do so as long as the war between France and the Habsburgs continued. England fared poorly during the war, and the loss of its last stronghold on the continent damaged its reputation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tudorsociety.com/an-overview-of-the-results-of-the-treaty-of-cateau-cambresis-1569/ |title=An Overview of the Results of the Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis 1559 |last=Ridgway |first=Claire |date=2017-04-03 |website=The Tudor Society |df=dmy-all |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the conflict, Italy was therefore divided between [[viceroyalties]] of the Spanish Habsburgs in the south and [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)|formal fiefs]] of the Austrian Habsburgs in the north. The imperial states were ruled by the [[Doria family|Doria]] in Genoa, the [[House of Medici|Medici]] in Tuscany, the Spanish Habsburgs in Milan, the [[House of Farnese|Farnese]] in Parma, the [[House of Este|Estensi]] in Modena, and an ''Italianized'' [[House of Savoy]] in Piedmont. The southern Kingdoms of Naples, Sicily and Sardinia were under direct rule of the Spanish Habsburgs. This situation continued until the European wars of succession of the 18th century, when northern Italy passed to the Austrian house of [[Habsburg-Lorraine]] and the south passed to the [[Spanish Bourbons]]. The Papacy in [[central Italy]] maintained major [[baroque|cultural]] and political influence during the [[Catholic Reformation]] initiated by the conclusion of the Tridentine council (resumed by the terms of the treaty).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mallett |first=Michael |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnnJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA298&dq=dual+protection+King+of+spain+and+emperor&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzipHsvMTjAhUN-6QKHa5qCYgQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=dual%2520protection%2520King%2520of%2520spain%2520and%2520emperor&f=false |title=The Italian Wars 1494-1559: War, State and Society in Early Modern Europe |last2=Shaw |first2=Christine |date=2014-06-11 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-89939-6 |pages=298 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Clauses ===\n[[File:It\u00e0lia - Fin dei Gu\u00e8rras d'It\u00e0lia (1559).png|thumb|Map of Italy in 1559 after the Treaties of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis]]\nAccording to the treaties signed in [[Le Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis]]:\n*Henry II of France renounced his hereditary claim to the [[Duchy of Milan]] (held by Spain and fief of the Holy Roman Empire)<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/event/Peace-of-Cateau-Cambresis |title=Peace of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis |author=Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica |work=Encyclopaedia Britannica |date=27 March 2019 |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref> and recognised Spanish control over the [[Kingdom of Naples]],<ref name=\"Setton709\"/> the [[Kingdom of Sicily]], and the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sarti |first=Roland |date=2004 |title=Italy: A Reference Guide from the Renaissance to the Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xhoLorFC1iwC&pg=PA189 |location=New York |publisher=Facts on File, Inc. |page=189 |isbn=9780816074747 |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n*France ceded the island of [[Corsica]] to the [[Republic of Genoa]] (fief of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] and allied with Spain).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/> French and Genoese merchants were granted full access to each other's ports.<ref name=\"Setton709\">Setton, 709.</ref>\n*France gave the [[Duchy of Savoy]]\u2013[[Principality of Piedmont|Piedmont]] (allied with Spain and fief of the Holy Roman Empire) back to [[Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy]]<ref name=\"Britannica\"/> due to his victory at [[Battle of St. Quentin (1557)|St. Quentin]]. Savoy declared neutrality between the Spain and France, and later moved its capital to [[Turin]]. \n*France retained five fortresses in Northern Italy, including those near [[Turin]], [[Saluzzo]] and [[Pinerolo]] (Pignerol).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/><ref name=\"Visconti\">{{Cite book |last=Visconti |first=Joseph |date=2003 |title=The Waldensian Way to God |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4TmARujuu-EC&pg=PA299 |location= |publisher=Xulon Press |page=299\u2013300 |isbn=9781591607922 |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n*France retained the [[Three Bishoprics]] of [[Bishopric of Toul|Toul]], [[Bishopric of Metz|Metz]] and [[Bishopric of Verdun|Verdun]] (seized from Charles V during the [[Second Schmalkaldic War]] in 1552).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/>\n*France retained the [[Pale of Calais]] (seized from England in 1558).<ref name=\"Britannica\"/>\n*France retained [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint Quentin]], [[Ham, Somme|Ham]], [[Le Catelet]] and other places in northern France seized by Spain during the war.<ref name=\"Setton708\"/>\n*The [[Duchy of Florence]] (fief of the Holy Roman Empire and allied with Spain) absorbed the [[Republic of Siena]] (allied with France) into what became the [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany|Duchy of Tuscany]].<ref name=\"Setton709\"/>\n*The [[March of Montferrat]] was given back to [[Guglielmo Gonzaga, Duke of Mantua]] (fief of the Holy Roman Empire and allied with Spain).<ref name=\"Setton708\"/>\n* All signatories of the treaty needed to 'purge their lands of heresy'; in other words, all their subjects had to be forcefully reverted to Catholicism. When pressured by [[Spanish Empire|Spain]] to implement this obligation, [[Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy]] proclaimed the Edict of Nice (15 February 1560), prohibiting Protestantism on pains of a large fine, enslavement or banishment, which soon led to an armed revolt by the Protestant [[Waldensians]] in his domain that would last until July 1561.<ref name=\"Visconti\"/>\n*Henri II of France and Philip II of Spain agreed in the treaty to ask the Pope and Emperor Ferdinand to reconvene the [[Council of Trent]]. The peace allowed Ferdinand to be recognized as Emperor by the Pope. <ref name=\"Setton708\">Setton, 708.</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Thalheimer |first=Mary Elsie |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=imEAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA208&dq=Pope+pius+IV+recognizes+Ferdinand&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik7YCfpf3kAhVQ3KQKHZ-GD3sQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Pope%2520pius%2520IV%2520recognizes%2520Ferdinand&f=false |title=A Manual of Medi\u00e6val and Modern History |date=1874 |publisher=Wilson Hinkle & Company |pages=208}}</ref>{{efn|1=[[Paolo Sarpi]], Istoria del Concilio Tridentino, Book 5. Ferdinand became Emperor in 1556 after the abdication of Charles V, ratified in 1558, but the Pope refused to recognize him until the Peace of 1559.{{cn|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n=== Celebrations ===\n[[Emmanuel Philibert]], Duke of [[Savoy]] married [[Margaret of France, Duchess of Berry]], the sister of [[Henry II of France]]. Philip II of Spain married [[Elisabeth of Valois|Elisabeth]], the daughter of Henry II of France.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Konnert |first=Mark |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t6TXB9RbwbYC&pg=PA122 |title=Early Modern Europe: The Age of Religious War, 1559\u20131715 |date=2008-08-23 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |isbn=978-1-4426-0004-1 |pages=122 |language=en}}</ref> Henry died during a [[tournament (medieval)|tournament]] when a sliver from the shattered lance of [[Gabriel Montgomery]], captain of the Scottish Guard at the French Court, pierced his eye and entered his brain. The death of Henry II caused his 15-year-old son Francis II to take the throne, beginning a period of political instability that ultimately led to the [[French Wars of Religion]].\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Cateau-Cambresis.jpg|The Peace of Cateau-Cambresis (1559). [[Henry II of France]] and [[Philip II of Spain]] were in reality absent, and the peace was signed by their ambassadors.\nFile:Tournament between Henry II and Lorges.jpg|The fatal tournament between [[Henry II of France|Henry II]] and [[Gabriel, comte de Montgomery|Montgomery]] (Lord of \"Lorges\")\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Franco-Ottoman alliance]]\n* [[Historical states of Italy#Italy in the year 1559|States of Italy in 1559]]\n* [[Elizabeth I of England]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* Baumgartner, Frederic J. ''Henry II, King of France 1547\u20131559'' (Duke Univ Press, 1988).\n* Oman, Charles W.C. ''A History of the Art of War in the Sixteenth Century'' (1937).\n* Pepper, Simon, and Nicholas Adams. ''Firearms & Fortifications: Military Architecture and Siege Warfare in Sixteenth-century Siena'' (University of Chicago Press, 1986).\n* Setton, Kenneth M. [https://books.google.com/books?id=SrUNi2m_qZAC&pg=PA698 ''The Papacy and the Levant (1204\u20131571)''] (American Philosophical Society, 1984).\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Cateau-Cambr%C3%A9sis_(England_and_France) Modern English version of the Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis between England and France]\n*[https://books.openedition.org/cvz/642 The original French-language Treaty of Cateau-Cambr\u00e9sis between France and Spain]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Italian War of 1551-1559}}\n[[Category:1550s conflicts]]\n[[Category:1550s in Italy]]\n[[Category:1551 in Italy]]\n[[Category:1556 in law]]\n[[Category:1559 in Italy]]\n[[Category:1559 in law]]\n[[Category:1550s in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:16th-century military history of the Kingdom of England]]\n[[Category:16th-century military history of France]]\n[[Category:16th-century military history of Spain]]\n[[Category:Italian Wars]]\n[[Category:Wars involving England]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Hilmorel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLand campaigns", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_War_of_1551%E2%80%931559"}
{"title_page": "Religious Zionism", "text_new": "{{short description|Ideology that combines Zionism and Orthodox Judaism}}\n[[File:Kippot.jpg|thumb|Crocheted [[kippot]]]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 7273 \u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e6\u05d9quot;\u05d1 \u05e2\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05ea\u05d9\u05d9\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionist pioneers found Kibbutz [[Ein HaNatziv]], 1946]]\n\n'''Religious Zionism''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05b4\u05d9\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05e0\u05d5\u05bc\u05ea \u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9\u05ea}}, [[Romanization of Hebrew|translit.]] ''Tziyonut Datit'', or {{Hebrew|\u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9 \u05dc\u05b0\u05d0\u05bb\u05de\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9}} ''Dati Leumi'' \"National Religious\", or {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4 \u05e1\u05b0\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d2\u05b8\u05d4}} ''Kippah seruga'', literally, \"knitted skullcap\") is an ideology that combines [[Zionism]] and [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\nBefore the establishment of [[Israel|the State of Israel]], Religious Zionists were mainly observant Jews who supported Zionist efforts to build a [[Jewish state]] in the [[Land of Israel]].\n\nAfter the [[Six-Day War]], and the capture of the [[West Bank]], a territory referred to in Jewish terms as [[Judea and Samaria]], right-wing components of the Religious Zionist movement integrated nationalist revindication{{explain|This term is not defined here, nor under the Ideology heading, and has no page or definition at the encyclopedia|date=July 2018}}, and evolved into [[Neo-Zionism]]. Their ideology revolves around three pillars: the Land of Israel, the People of Israel, and the Torah of Israel.<ref>[[Adriana Kemp]], ''Israelis in Conflict: Hegemonies, Identities, and Challenges'', Sussex Academic Press, 2004, pp.314\u2013315.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Abraham Isaac Kook 1924.jpg|thumb|[[Abraham Isaac Kook]], 1924]]\n\nIn 1862, German Orthodox [[Rabbi]] [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]] published his tractate ''Derishat Zion'', positing that the salvation of the Jews, promised by the [[Nevi'im|Prophets]], can come about only by self-help.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=56&letter=K Zvi Hirsch Kalischer] (Jewish Encyclopedia)</ref> Rabbi [[Moshe Shmuel Glasner]] was another prominent rabbi who supported Zionism. The main ideologue of modern Religious Zionism was Rabbi [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], who justified Zionism according to [[Halakha|Jewish law]], and urged young religious Jews to support efforts to settle the land, and the secular [[Labour Zionist]]s to give more consideration to Judaism. Kook saw Zionism as a part of a divine scheme which would result in the resettlement of the Jewish people in its homeland. This would bring salvation (\"Geula\") to Jews, and then to the entire world. After world harmony is achieved by the refoundation of the Jewish homeland, the [[Messiah]] will come. Although this has not yet happened, Kook emphasized that it would take time, and that the ultimate redemption happens in stages, often not apparent while happening. In 1924, when Kook became the [[Ashkenazi]] [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], he tried to reconcile Zionism with [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\n== Ideology ==\n[[File:Jerusalem Day.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionists celebrating [[Jerusalem Day]]]]\nReligious Zionists believe that \"[[Eretz Israel|Eretz Yisrael]]\" (the Land of Israel) was promised to the ancient [[Israelites]] by [[God in Judaism|God]].  Furthermore, modern Jews have the obligation to possess and defend the land in ways that comport with the [[Torah]]'s high standards of justice.<ref>Novak, David.  [https://mosaicmagazine.com/response/politics-current-affairs/2020/01/what-unites-people-of-faith-across-religions-and-divides-them-from-others/ \"What Unites People of Faith across Religions, and Divides Them from Others.\"] ''Mosaic''.  23 January 2020.  23 January 2020.</ref> To generations of [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora Jews]], [[Jerusalem]] has been a symbol of the [[Holy Land]] and of their return to it, as promised by God in numerous [[Bible|Biblical prophecies]]. Despite this, many Jews did not embrace Zionism before the 1930s, and certain religious groups opposed it then, as some groups still do now, on the grounds that an attempt to re-establish Jewish rule in Israel by [[human agency]] was blasphemous. Hastening salvation and the coming of the Messiah was considered religiously forbidden, and Zionism was seen as a sign of disbelief in God's power, and therefore, a rebellion against God. Rabbi Kook developed a [[theology|theological]] answer to that claim, which gave Zionism a religious legitimation: \"Zionism was not merely a political movement by secular Jews. It was actually a tool of [[God]] to promote His divine scheme, and to initiate the return of the Jews to their homeland \u2013 the land He promised to [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[Jacob]]. God wants the [[children of Israel]] to return to their home in order to establish a Jewish sovereign state in which Jews could live according to the laws of [[Torah]] and [[Halakha]], and commit the [[Mitzvah|Mitzvot]] of Eretz Israel (these are religious commandments which can be performed only in the [[Land of Israel]]). Moreover, to cultivate the Land of Israel was a Mitzvah by itself, and it should be carried out. Therefore, settling [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is an obligation of the religious Jews, and helping Zionism is actually following God's will.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Torat Eretz Yisrael|first=David|last=Samson|author2=Tzvi Fishman |publisher=Torat Eretz Yisrael Publications|location=Jerusalem |year=1991}}</ref>\n\nReligious Jews also disapproved of the Zionists because many were secular Jews or [[atheist]]s, taking their cue from [[Marxism]]. [[Labour Zionism|Socialist Zionism]] envisaged the movement as a tool for building an advanced [[socialist]] society in the land of Israel, while solving the problem of [[antisemitism]]. The early [[kibbutz]] was a communal settlement that focused on national goals, unencumbered by religion and precepts of Jewish law such as [[kashrut]]. Socialist Zionists were one of the results of a long process of modernization within the Jewish communities of Europe, known as the [[Haskalah]], or Jewish Enlightenment. Rabbi Kook's answer was as follows:\n\n:''Secular Zionists may think they do it for political, national, or socialist reasons, but in fact \u2013 the actual reason for them coming to resettle in [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is a religious Jewish spark (\"Nitzotz\") in their [[soul]], planted by God. Without their knowledge, they are contributing to the divine scheme and actually committing a great [[Mitzvah]].''\n\n:''The role of religious Zionists is to help them to establish a Jewish state and turn the religious spark in them into a great light. They should show them that the real source of Zionism and the longed-for Zion is [[Judaism]] and teach them [[Torah]] with love and kindness. In the end, they will understand that the laws of [[Torah]] are the key to true [[harmony]] and a [[socialist]] state (not in the [[Marxist]] [[Socialist mode of production|meaning]]) that will be a light for the [[goyim|nations]] and bring salvation to the world.''\n\n[[Shlomo Avineri]] explained the last part of Kook's answer: \"... and the end of those pioneers, who scout into the blindness of secularism and atheism, but the treasured light inside them leads them into the path of salvation \u2013 their end is that from doing Mitzva without purpose, they will do Mitzva with a purpose.\" (page 222, <sup>[[Religious Zionist Movement#References|1]]</sup>)\n\n== Organizations ==\n[[File:Bnei akiva logo.jpg|thumb|100px|left|[[Bnei Akiva]] youth movement, combining Torah and work]]\n\nThe first rabbis to support Zionism were [[Judah Alkalai|Yehuda Shlomo Alkalai]] and [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]. They argued that the change in the status of [[Western Europe]]'s Jews following [[Jewish emancipation|emancipation]] was the first step toward redemption (\u05d2\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4), and that, therefore, one must hasten the messianic salvation by a natural salvation \u2013 whose main pillars are the [[Kibbutz Galuyot]] (\"Gathering of the Exiles\"), the return to Eretz Israel, agricultural work (\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05ea \u05d0\u05d3\u05de\u05d4), and the revival of the everyday use of the [[Hebrew language]].\n\nThe [[Mizrachi (Religious Zionism)|Mizrachi]] organization was established in 1902 in [[Vilna]] at a world conference of Religious Zionists. It operates a [[Zionist youth movement|youth movement]], [[Bnei Akiva]], which was founded in 1929. Mizrachi believes that the [[Torah]] should be at the centre of [[Zionism]], a sentiment expressed in the Mizrachi Zionist slogan ''Am Yisrael B'Eretz Yisrael al pi Torat Yisrael'' (\"The people of Israel in the land of Israel according to the Torah of Israel\"). It also sees Jewish nationalism as a tool for achieving religious objectives. Mizrachi was the first official Religious Zionist party. It also built a network of religious schools that exist to this day.\n\nIn 1937-1948, the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]] established three settlement blocs of three kibbutzim each. The first was in the [[Beit Shean]] Valley, the second was in the [[Hebron]] mountains south of [[Bethlehem]] (known as [[Gush Etzion]]), and the third was in the western [[Negev]]. Kibbutz [[Yavne]] was founded in the center of the country as the core of a fourth bloc that came into being after the establishment of the state.<ref>\"Settlement clustering on a socio-cultural basis: The bloc settlement policy of the Religious Kibbutz Movement in Palestine,\" Yossi Katz, ''Journal of Rural Studies'', vol. 11, no. 2, pp. 161\u2013171, 1995</ref>\n\n== Political parties ==\nThe [[Labor Movement]] wing of Religious Zionism, founded in 1921 under the Zionist slogan \"Torah va'Avodah\" (Torah and Labor), was called [[Hapoel HaMizrachi]]. It represented religiously traditional [[Labour Zionism|Labour Zionists]], both in Europe and in the Land of Israel, where it represented religious Jews in the [[Histadrut]]. In 1956, Mizrachi, Hapoel HaMizrachi, and other religious Zionists formed the [[National Religious Party]] to advance the rights of religious Zionist Jews in Israel. Other parties and groups affiliated with religious Zionism are [[Gush Emunim]], [[Tkuma (political party)|Tkuma]], and [[Meimad]]. [[Kahanism]], a radical branch of religious Zionism, was founded by Rabbi [[Meir Kahane]], whose party, [[Kach and Kahane Chai|Kach]], was eventually banned for [[racism]]. Today, [[Otzma Yehudit]] is the leading wing of this school of thought.\n\n== Educational institutions ==\n:''See: [[Yeshiva #Israel]]; [[:Category:Religious Zionist yeshivot]]; [[List of Midrashot]].''\n[[File:Mercaz HaRav01.JPG|thumb|[[Mercaz Harav]], Jerusalem]]\nThe flagship religious institution of the Religious Zionist movement is the [[yeshiva]] founded by Rabbi Abraham Isaac Kook in 1924, called in his honor \"[[Mercaz haRav]]\" (lit., the Rabbi's center). \nOther Religious Zionist yeshivot include [[Ateret Cohanim]], [[Beit El yeshiva]] and Yeshivat [[Or Etzion]], founded by Rav [[Haim Druckman]], a foremost disciple of Rabbi [[Tzvi Yehuda Kook]].\n\nThere are also approximately 90 ''[[Hesder]]'' yeshivot, allowing students to continue [[Torah study]] during their National Service (see [[#Military_service|below]]).\nThe first was [[Yeshivat Kerem B'Yavneh]], established in 1954; the largest is the [[Hesder Yeshiva of Sderot]] with over 800 students.\nOthers well known include [[Machon Meir|Yeshivat Machon Meir]], [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], [[Yeshivat HaKotel]], [[Yeshivat Birkat Moshe]] in [[Maale Adumim]], [[Yeshiva Har Bracha|Yeshivat Har Bracha]] and Yeshivat Har Hamor.  \n\nThese institutions usually offer a [[kollel]] for ''[[Semikha]]'', or Rabbinic ordination. Students generally prepare for the ''Semikha'' test of the [[Chief Rabbinate of Israel]]; often for that of the [[posek]] R. [[Zalman Nechemia Goldberg]].\nTraining as a [[Dayan (rabbinic judge)]] in this community is usually through [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d0\u05dc|''Machon Ariel'']] (''[[Machon Harry Fischel]]''), also founded by Rav Kook, or [[:he:\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5_\u05d7\u05de\u05d3\u05d4_(\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05dc) |''Kollel Eretz Hemda'']].\n\nWomen study in institutions known as ''Midrashot'' (sing. [[Midrasha]]) - examples are [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv Women's Seminary]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]]. Some also offer degree studies (and may then be known as a ''machon'').\n[[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] trains women as [[Yoetzet Halacha|Yoatzot Halacha]]; see also [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] and [[Matan Women's Institute for Torah Studies|Matan]], which similarly offer Talmud focused learning to women.\n\nHigh school students study at [[Education_in_Israel#Educational_tracks|''Mamlachti dati'']] schools, often associated with ''[[Bnei Akiva]]''. The first of these was at [[Kfar Haroeh]] established by [[Moshe-Zvi Neria]]. A girls' high school is referred to as an ''[[Ulpana]]''.\nFor degree studies, many attend [[Bar Ilan University]], which allows students to combine Yeshiva studies with university study; \n[[Jerusalem College of Technology]] similarly (which also offers a Haredi track).\nThere are also [[List_of_Israeli_universities_and_colleges#Colleges|several colleges of education]] associated with Hesder and the ''Midrashot'', such as [[Herzog College]] and the [[Lifshitz College of Education]]. These often allow specializations in [[Tanach]] and ''Machshava'' ([[Jewish thought]]).\n\nSome institutions are aligned with the ''[[Hardal]]'' (\u1e24aredi Le'umi) community, with an ideology that is slightly more \"statist\".\nThe leading Yeshiva here is [[Har Hamor]]; [[Hardal#Schools|several high schools]] also operate.\n\n== Dress ==\nReligious Zionists are often called ''Kippot sruggot'', referring to the knitted or crocheted [[kippot|skullcaps]] (Hebrew ''kippa'', pl. ''kippot'') worn by many of the men. (However, there are also men who wear other types of headcoverings, such as ''kippot'' in black velvet.) \nTheir dress, otherwise, is largely the same as for secular Israelis.\nWomen usually wear skirts, and often cover their hair.\nSee under [[Tzniut]]: [[Tzniut#Dress|#Dress]] and [[Tzniut#Hair covering|#Hair covering]]\n\nIn the ''Hardal'' community, the dress is generally more formal, with an emphasis on appearing neat;  \nthe Kippot, also knitted, are significantly larger, and it is common for [[tzitzit]] to be worn visibly, as is the [[Haredi]] practice. \nWomen invariably cover their hair - often with a [[snood]], or with a ''mitpachat'' (Hebrew for \"kerchief\") - and often wear sandals.\n\nAt prayer, members of the community use the [[Koren Siddur]] or ''[[Rinat Yisrael]]''.\n\n== Politics ==\nMost Religious Zionists embrace [[right-wing]] politics, especially the religious right-wing [[Jewish Home]] party, but also support the mainstream right-wing [[Likud]]. There are also some left-wing Religious Zionists, such as Rabbi [[Michael Melchior]], whose views were represented by the [[Meimad]] party (which ran together with the [[Labor (Israel)|Israeli Labor party]]). Many Israeli [[Israeli settlements|settlers]] in the [[West Bank]] are Religious Zionists, along with most of the settlers forcibly expelled from the [[Gaza Strip]] in August and September 2005.\n\n== Military service ==\n{{unreferencedsect|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:IDF soldier put on tefillin.jpg|thumb|Second-Lieutenant [[From the Wilderness and Lebanon|Asael Lubotzky]], an [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] field commander during [[Second Lebanon War]], prays with [[Tefilin]]]]\nAll adult Jewish males in Israel are obligated to serve in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]]. Certain segments of Orthodoxy defer their service in order to engage in full-time Torah study. Religious Zionist belief advocates that both are critical to Jewish survival and prosperity.\n\nFor this reason, many Religious Zionist men take part in the [[Hesder]] program, which allows military service to be combined with [[yeshiva]] studies. Some others attend a pre-army [[Mechina]] educational program, delaying their service by one year. 88% of Hesder students belong to combat units, compared to a national average of below 30%. \n\nWhile some Religious Zionist women serve in the army, most choose national service, known as [[Sherut Leumi]], instead (working at hospitals, schools, and day-care centers).\nIn November 2010, the IDF held a special conference which was attended by the heads of Religious Zionism in order to encourage female Religious Zionists to join the IDF. The IDF undertook that all modesty and kosher issues will be handled in order to make female Religious Zionists comfortable.\n\n== Notable figures ==\n* [[Yehuda Amital]]\n* [[Eli Sadan]] \n* [[Shlomo Aviner]]\n* [[Naftali Bennett]]\n* [[Yosef Burg]]\n* [[She'ar Yashuv Cohen]]\n* [[Haim Druckman]]\n* [[Effi Eitam]]\n* [[Mordechai Eliyahu]]\n* [[Moshe Feiglin]]\n* [[Shlomo Goren]]\n* [[Yitzhak HaLevi Herzog]]\n* [[Meir Kahane]]\n* [[Binyamin Ze'ev Kahane]]\n* [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]\n* [[Avraham Yitzchak Kook]]\n* [[Zvi Yehuda Kook]]\n* [[Dov Lior]]\n* [[Rafi Peretz]]\n* [[Zevulun Orlev]]\n* [[Shlomo Riskin]]\n* [[Avraham Shapira]]\n* [[Shaul Yisraeli]]\n* [[Oury Amos Cherki]]\n* [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n* [[Baruch Marzel]]\n* [[Michael Ben-Ari]]\n* [[Baruch Goldstein]]\n* [[Yisrael Ariel]]\n* [[Yehuda Glick]]\n* [[Aharon Lichtenstein]]\n* [[Yaakov Ariel]]\n* [[Jonathan Sacks]]\n* [[Hanan Porat]]\n* [[Zvi Thau]]\n* [[Yaaqov Medan]]\n* [[Haim Sabato]]\n* [[Nahum Rabinovitch]]\n* [[Robert Aumann]]\n* [[Uri Orbach]]\n* [[Meir Bar-Ilan]]\n* [[Shimon Gershon Rosenberg]]\n* [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Chardal]]\n* [[Haredim and Zionism]]\n* [[Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Religion in Israel]]\n* [[Atchalta De'Geulah]]\n* [[Arutz Sheva]]\n* [[Hesder]]\n* [[Machon Meir]]\n* [[Mamlachti dati]]\n* [[Torato Omanuto]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''The Zionist Idea and Its Variations'' by [[Shlomo Avineri]], ''Am Oved'' publishing, chapter 17: \"Rabbi Kook \u2013 the dialection in salvation\"\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcepar|Zionism an Affirmation of Judaism}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.rza.org/ Religious Zionists of America]\n* [http://therav.net/gallery/ReligiousZionists8.5x14V14.0.pdf Poster of Historic Religious Zionist Leaders]\n* [http://www.biu.ac.il/Spokesman/Tolerance/michman.htm A Historical Look at Religious Zionism] by Prof. Dan Michman\n* [http://www.shapell.org/manuscript.aspx?ben-gurion-peace Original Letters and Manuscripts: Zionism, Ben-Gurion on God's Promises] Shapell Manuscript Foundation\n* [http://www.kipa.co.il/ \"Kipa \u2013 House of Religious Zionism\" (Hebrew)]\n* [http://www.mafdal.org.il/?sid=27 Official National Religious Party website (in English)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041216072651/http://www.mizrachi.org/ideas/view.asp?id=122 Religious Zionism And Modern Orthodoxy], Rav Yosef Blau\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050421213010/http://www.hagshama.org.il/en/resources/view.asp?id=1428 Religious Zionism, Compromise or Ideal?], hagshama.org.il\n* [http://www.afyba.org/ The American Friends of YBA \u2013 Supporters of religious Zionist educational movement in Israel]\n\n\n{{Religion in Israel}}\n{{Religious Zionism}}\n{{Zionism}}\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jews and Judaism}}\n{{Relpolnav}}\n\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism| ]]\n[[Category:Types of Zionism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ideology that combines Zionism and Orthodox Judaism}}\n[[File:Kippot.jpg|thumb|Crocheted [[kippot]]]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 7273 \u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e6\u05d9quot;\u05d1 \u05e2\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05ea\u05d9\u05d9\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionist pioneers found Kibbutz [[Ein HaNatziv]], 1946]]\n\n'''Religious Zionism''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05b4\u05d9\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05e0\u05d5\u05bc\u05ea \u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9\u05ea}}, [[Romanization of Hebrew|translit.]] ''Tziyonut Datit'', or {{Hebrew|\u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9 \u05dc\u05b0\u05d0\u05bb\u05de\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9}} ''Dati Leumi'' \"National Religious\", or {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4 \u05e1\u05b0\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d2\u05b8\u05d4}} ''Kippah seruga'', literally, \"knitted skullcap\") is an ideology that combines [[Zionism]] and [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\nBefore the establishment of [[Israel|the State of Israel]], Religious Zionists were mainly observant Jews who supported Zionist efforts to build a [[Jewish state]] in the [[Land of Israel]].\n\nAfter the [[Six-Day War]], and the capture of the [[West Bank]], a territory referred to in Jewish terms as [[Judea and Samaria]], right-wing components of the Religious Zionist movement integrated nationalist revindication{{explain|This term is not defined here, nor under the Ideology heading, and has no page or definition at the encyclopedia|date=July 2018}}, and evolved into [[Neo-Zionism]]. Their ideology revolves around three pillars: the Land of Israel, the People of Israel, and the Torah of Israel.<ref>[[Adriana Kemp]], ''Israelis in Conflict: Hegemonies, Identities, and Challenges'', Sussex Academic Press, 2004, pp.314\u2013315.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Abraham Isaac Kook 1924.jpg|thumb|[[Abraham Isaac Kook]], 1924]]\n\nIn 1862, German Orthodox [[Rabbi]] [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]] published his tractate ''Derishat Zion'', positing that the salvation of the Jews, promised by the [[Nevi'im|Prophets]], can come about only by self-help.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=56&letter=K Zvi Hirsch Kalischer] (Jewish Encyclopedia)</ref> Rabbi [[Moshe Shmuel Glasner]] was another prominent rabbi who supported Zionism. The main ideologue of modern Religious Zionism was Rabbi [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], who justified Zionism according to [[Halakha|Jewish law]], and urged young religious Jews to support efforts to settle the land, and the secular [[Labour Zionist]]s to give more consideration to Judaism. Kook saw Zionism as a part of a divine scheme which would result in the resettlement of the Jewish people in its homeland. This would bring salvation (\"Geula\") to Jews, and then to the entire world. After world harmony is achieved by the refoundation of the Jewish homeland, the [[Messiah]] will come. Although this has not yet happened, Kook emphasized that it would take time, and that the ultimate redemption happens in stages, often not apparent while happening. In 1924, when Kook became the [[Ashkenazi]] [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], he tried to reconcile Zionism with [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\n== Ideology ==\n[[File:Jerusalem Day.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionists celebrating [[Jerusalem Day]]]]\nReligious Zionists believe that \"[[Eretz Israel|Eretz Yisrael]]\" (the Land of Israel) was promised to the ancient [[Israelites]] by [[God in Judaism|God]].  Furthermore, modern Jews have the obligation to possess and defend the land in ways that comport with the [[Torah]]'s high standards of justice.<ref>Novak, David.  [https://mosaicmagazine.com/response/politics-current-affairs/2020/01/what-unites-people-of-faith-across-religions-and-divides-them-from-others/ \"What Unites People of Faith across Religions, and Divides Them from Others.\"] ''Mosaic''.  23 January 2020.  23 January 2020.</ref> To generations of [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora Jews]], [[Jerusalem]] has been a symbol of the [[Holy Land]] and of their return to it, as promised by God in numerous [[Bible|Biblical prophecies]]. Despite this, many Jews did not embrace Zionism before the 1930s, and certain religious groups opposed it then, as some groups still do now, on the grounds that an attempt to re-establish Jewish rule in Israel by [[human agency]] was blasphemous. Hastening salvation and the coming of the Messiah was considered religiously forbidden, and Zionism was seen as a sign of disbelief in God's power, and therefore, a rebellion against God. Rabbi Kook developed a [[theology|theological]] answer to that claim, which gave Zionism a religious legitimation: \"Zionism was not merely a political movement by secular Jews. It was actually a tool of [[God]] to promote His divine scheme, and to initiate the return of the Jews to their homeland \u2013 the land He promised to [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[Jacob]]. God wants the [[children of Israel]] to return to their home in order to establish a Jewish sovereign state in which Jews could live according to the laws of [[Torah]] and [[Halakha]], and commit the [[Mitzvah|Mitzvot]] of Eretz Israel (these are religious commandments which can be performed only in the [[Land of Israel]]). Moreover, to cultivate the Land of Israel was a Mitzvah by itself, and it should be carried out. Therefore, settling [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is an obligation of the religious Jews, and helping Zionism is actually following God's will.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Torat Eretz Yisrael|first=David|last=Samson|author2=Tzvi Fishman |publisher=Torat Eretz Yisrael Publications|location=Jerusalem |year=1991}}</ref>\n\nReligious Jews also disapproved of the Zionists because many were secular Jews or [[atheist]]s, taking their cue from [[Marxism]]. [[Labour Zionism|Socialist Zionism]] envisaged the movement as a tool for building an advanced [[socialist]] society in the land of Israel, while solving the problem of [[antisemitism]]. The early [[kibbutz]] was a communal settlement that focused on national goals, unencumbered by religion and precepts of Jewish law such as [[kashrut]]. Socialist Zionists were one of the results of a long process of modernization within the Jewish communities of Europe, known as the [[Haskalah]], or Jewish Enlightenment. Rabbi Kook's answer was as follows:\n\n:''Secular Zionists may think they do it for political, national, or socialist reasons, but in fact \u2013 the actual reason for them coming to resettle in [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is a religious Jewish spark (\"Nitzotz\") in their [[soul]], planted by God. Without their knowledge, they are contributing to the divine scheme and actually committing a great [[Mitzvah]].''\n\n:''The role of religious Zionists is to help them to establish a Jewish state and turn the religious spark in them into a great light. They should show them that the real source of Zionism and the longed-for Zion is [[Judaism]] and teach them [[Torah]] with love and kindness. In the end, they will understand that the laws of [[Torah]] are the key to true [[harmony]] and a [[socialist]] state (not in the [[Marxist]] [[Socialist mode of production|meaning]]) that will be a light for the [[goyim|nations]] and bring salvation to the world.''\n\n[[Shlomo Avineri]] explained the last part of Kook's answer: \"... and the end of those pioneers, who scout into the blindness of secularism and atheism, but the treasured light inside them leads them into the path of salvation \u2013 their end is that from doing Mitzva without purpose, they will do Mitzva with a purpose.\" (page 222, <sup>[[Religious Zionist Movement#References|1]]</sup>)\n\n== Organizations ==\n[[File:Bnei akiva logo.jpg|thumb|100px|left|[[Bnei Akiva]] youth movement, combining Torah and work]]\n\nThe first rabbis to support Zionism were [[Judah Alkalai|Yehuda Shlomo Alkalai]] and [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]. They argued that the change in the status of [[Western Europe]]'s Jews following [[Jewish emancipation|emancipation]] was the first step toward redemption (\u05d2\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4), and that, therefore, one must hasten the messianic salvation by a natural salvation \u2013 whose main pillars are the [[Kibbutz Galuyot]] (\"Gathering of the Exiles\"), the return to Eretz Israel, agricultural work (\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05ea \u05d0\u05d3\u05de\u05d4), and the revival of the everyday use of the [[Hebrew language]].\n\nThe [[Mizrachi (Religious Zionism)|Mizrachi]] organization was established in 1902 in [[Vilna]] at a world conference of Religious Zionists. It operates a [[Zionist youth movement|youth movement]], [[Bnei Akiva]], which was founded in 1929. Mizrachi believes that the [[Torah]] should be at the centre of [[Zionism]], a sentiment expressed in the Mizrachi Zionist slogan ''Am Yisrael B'Eretz Yisrael al pi Torat Yisrael'' (\"The people of Israel in the land of Israel according to the Torah of Israel\"). It also sees Jewish nationalism as a tool for achieving religious objectives. Mizrachi was the first official Religious Zionist party. It also built a network of religious schools that exist to this day.\n\nIn 1937-1948, the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]] established three settlement blocs of three kibbutzim each. The first was in the [[Beit Shean]] Valley, the second was in the [[Hebron]] mountains south of [[Bethlehem]] (known as [[Gush Etzion]]), and the third was in the western [[Negev]]. Kibbutz [[Yavne]] was founded in the center of the country as the core of a fourth bloc that came into being after the establishment of the state.<ref>\"Settlement clustering on a socio-cultural basis: The bloc settlement policy of the Religious Kibbutz Movement in Palestine,\" Yossi Katz, ''Journal of Rural Studies'', vol. 11, no. 2, pp. 161\u2013171, 1995</ref>\n\n== Political parties ==\nThe [[Labor Movement]] wing of Religious Zionism, founded in 1921 under the Zionist slogan \"Torah va'Avodah\" (Torah and Labor), was called [[Hapoel HaMizrachi]]. It represented religiously traditional [[Labour Zionism|Labour Zionists]], both in Europe and in the Land of Israel, where it represented religious Jews in the [[Histadrut]]. In 1956, Mizrachi, Hapoel HaMizrachi, and other religious Zionists formed the [[National Religious Party]] to advance the rights of religious Zionist Jews in Israel. Other parties and groups affiliated with religious Zionism are [[Gush Emunim]], [[Tkuma (political party)|Tkuma]], and [[Meimad]]. [[Kahanism]], a radical branch of religious Zionism, was founded by Rabbi [[Meir Kahane]], whose party, [[Kach and Kahane Chai|Kach]], was eventually banned for [[racism]]. Today, [[Otzma Yehudit]] is the leading wing of this school of thought.\n\n== Educational institutions ==\n:''See: [[Yeshiva #Israel]]; [[:Category:Religious Zionist yeshivot]]; [[List of Midrashot]].''\n[[File:Mercaz HaRav01.JPG|thumb|[[Mercaz Harav]], Jerusalem]]\nThe flagship religious institution of the Religious Zionist movement is the [[yeshiva]] founded by Rabbi Abraham Isaac Kook in 1924, called in his honor \"[[Mercaz haRav]]\" (lit., the Rabbi's center). \nOther Religious Zionist yeshivot include [[Ateret Cohanim]], [[Beit El yeshiva]] and Yeshivat [[Or Etzion]], founded by Rav [[Haim Druckman]], a foremost disciple of Rabbi [[Tzvi Yehuda Kook]].\n\nThere are also approximately 90 ''[[Hesder]]'' yeshivot, allowing students to continue [[Torah study]] during their National Service (see [[#Military_service|below]]).\nThe first was [[Yeshivat Kerem B'Yavneh]], established in 1954; the largest is the [[Hesder Yeshiva of Sderot]] with over 800 students.\nOthers well known include [[Machon Meir|Yeshivat Machon Meir]], [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], [[Yeshivat HaKotel]], [[Yeshivat Birkat Moshe]] in [[Maale Adumim]], [[Yeshiva Har Bracha|Yeshivat Har Bracha]] and Yeshivat Har Hamor.  \n\nThese institutions usually offer a [[kollel]] for ''[[Semikha]]'', or Rabbinic ordination. Students generally prepare for the ''Semikha'' test of the [[Chief Rabbinate of Israel]]; often for that of the [[posek]] R. [[Zalman Nechemia Goldberg]].\nTraining as a [[Dayan (rabbinic judge)]] in this community is usually through [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d0\u05dc|''Machon Ariel'']] (''[[Machon Harry Fischel]]''), also founded by Rav Kook, or [[:he:\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5_\u05d7\u05de\u05d3\u05d4_(\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05dc) |''Kollel Eretz Hemda'']].\n\nWomen study in institutions known as ''Midrashot'' (sing. [[Midrasha]]) - examples are [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv Women's Seminary]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]]. Some also offer degree studies (and may then be known as a ''machon'').\n[[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] trains women as [[Yoetzet Halacha|Yoatzot Halacha]]; see also [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] and [[Matan Women's Institute for Torah Studies|Matan]], which similarly offer Talmud focused learning to women.\n\nHigh school students study at [[Education_in_Israel#Educational_tracks|''Mamlachti dati'']] schools, often associated with ''[[Bnei Akiva]]''. The first of these was at [[Kfar Haroeh]] established by [[Moshe-Zvi Neria]]. A girls' high school is referred to as an ''[[Ulpana]]''.\nFor degree studies, many attend [[Bar Ilan University]], which allows students to combine Yeshiva studies with university study; \n[[Jerusalem College of Technology]] similarly (which also offers a Haredi track).\nThere are also [[List_of_Israeli_universities_and_colleges#Colleges|several colleges of education]] associated with Hesder and the ''Midrashot'', such as [[Herzog College]] and the [[Lifshitz College of Education]]. These often allow specializations in [[Tanach]] and ''Machshava'' ([[Jewish thought]]).\n\nSome institutions are aligned with the ''[[Hardal]]'' (\u1e24aredi Le'umi) community, with an ideology that is slightly more \"statist\".\nThe leading Yeshiva here is [[Har Hamor]]; [[Hardal#Schools|several high schools]] also operate.\n\n== Dress ==\nReligious Zionists are often called ''Kippot sruggot'', referring to the knitted or crocheted [[kippot|skullcaps]] (Hebrew ''kippa'', pl. ''kippot'') worn by many of the men. (However, there are also men who wear other types of headcoverings, such as ''kippot'' in black velvet.) Their dress, otherwise, is largely the same as secular Israelis\n\nIn the ''Hardal'' community, the dress is slightly more formal, with an emphasis on appearing neat;  \nthe Kippot, also knitted, are significantly larger, and it is common for [[tzitzit]] to be worn visibly, as is the [[Haredi]] practice. \n\nAt prayer, members of the community often use the [[Koren Siddur]] or ''[[Rinat Yisrael]]''.\n\n== Politics ==\nMost Religious Zionists embrace [[right-wing]] politics, especially the religious right-wing [[Jewish Home]] party, but also support the mainstream right-wing [[Likud]]. There are also some left-wing Religious Zionists, such as Rabbi [[Michael Melchior]], whose views were represented by the [[Meimad]] party (which ran together with the [[Labor (Israel)|Israeli Labor party]]). Many Israeli [[Israeli settlements|settlers]] in the [[West Bank]] are Religious Zionists, along with most of the settlers forcibly expelled from the [[Gaza Strip]] in August and September 2005.\n\n== Military service ==\n{{unreferencedsect|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:IDF soldier put on tefillin.jpg|thumb|Second-Lieutenant [[From the Wilderness and Lebanon|Asael Lubotzky]], an [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] field commander during [[Second Lebanon War]], prays with [[Tefilin]]]]\nAll adult Jewish males in Israel are obligated to serve in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]]. Certain segments of Orthodoxy defer their service in order to engage in full-time Torah study. Religious Zionist belief advocates that both are critical to Jewish survival and prosperity.\n\nFor this reason, many Religious Zionist men take part in the [[Hesder]] program, which allows military service to be combined with [[yeshiva]] studies. Some others attend a pre-army [[Mechina]] educational program, delaying their service by one year. 88% of Hesder students belong to combat units, compared to a national average of below 30%. \n\nWhile some Religious Zionist women serve in the army, most choose national service, known as [[Sherut Leumi]], instead (working at hospitals, schools, and day-care centers).\nIn November 2010, the IDF held a special conference which was attended by the heads of Religious Zionism in order to encourage female Religious Zionists to join the IDF. The IDF undertook that all modesty and kosher issues will be handled in order to make female Religious Zionists comfortable.\n\n== Notable figures ==\n* [[Yehuda Amital]]\n* [[Eli Sadan]] \n* [[Shlomo Aviner]]\n* [[Naftali Bennett]]\n* [[Yosef Burg]]\n* [[She'ar Yashuv Cohen]]\n* [[Haim Druckman]]\n* [[Effi Eitam]]\n* [[Mordechai Eliyahu]]\n* [[Moshe Feiglin]]\n* [[Shlomo Goren]]\n* [[Yitzhak HaLevi Herzog]]\n* [[Meir Kahane]]\n* [[Binyamin Ze'ev Kahane]]\n* [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]\n* [[Avraham Yitzchak Kook]]\n* [[Zvi Yehuda Kook]]\n* [[Dov Lior]]\n* [[Rafi Peretz]]\n* [[Zevulun Orlev]]\n* [[Shlomo Riskin]]\n* [[Avraham Shapira]]\n* [[Shaul Yisraeli]]\n* [[Oury Amos Cherki]]\n* [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n* [[Baruch Marzel]]\n* [[Michael Ben-Ari]]\n* [[Baruch Goldstein]]\n* [[Yisrael Ariel]]\n* [[Yehuda Glick]]\n* [[Aharon Lichtenstein]]\n* [[Yaakov Ariel]]\n* [[Jonathan Sacks]]\n* [[Hanan Porat]]\n* [[Zvi Thau]]\n* [[Yaaqov Medan]]\n* [[Haim Sabato]]\n* [[Nahum Rabinovitch]]\n* [[Robert Aumann]]\n* [[Uri Orbach]]\n* [[Meir Bar-Ilan]]\n* [[Shimon Gershon Rosenberg]]\n* [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Chardal]]\n* [[Haredim and Zionism]]\n* [[Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Religion in Israel]]\n* [[Atchalta De'Geulah]]\n* [[Arutz Sheva]]\n* [[Hesder]]\n* [[Machon Meir]]\n* [[Mamlachti dati]]\n* [[Torato Omanuto]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''The Zionist Idea and Its Variations'' by [[Shlomo Avineri]], ''Am Oved'' publishing, chapter 17: \"Rabbi Kook \u2013 the dialection in salvation\"\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcepar|Zionism an Affirmation of Judaism}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.rza.org/ Religious Zionists of America]\n* [http://therav.net/gallery/ReligiousZionists8.5x14V14.0.pdf Poster of Historic Religious Zionist Leaders]\n* [http://www.biu.ac.il/Spokesman/Tolerance/michman.htm A Historical Look at Religious Zionism] by Prof. Dan Michman\n* [http://www.shapell.org/manuscript.aspx?ben-gurion-peace Original Letters and Manuscripts: Zionism, Ben-Gurion on God's Promises] Shapell Manuscript Foundation\n* [http://www.kipa.co.il/ \"Kipa \u2013 House of Religious Zionism\" (Hebrew)]\n* [http://www.mafdal.org.il/?sid=27 Official National Religious Party website (in English)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041216072651/http://www.mizrachi.org/ideas/view.asp?id=122 Religious Zionism And Modern Orthodoxy], Rav Yosef Blau\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050421213010/http://www.hagshama.org.il/en/resources/view.asp?id=1428 Religious Zionism, Compromise or Ideal?], hagshama.org.il\n* [http://www.afyba.org/ The American Friends of YBA \u2013 Supporters of religious Zionist educational movement in Israel]\n\n\n{{Religion in Israel}}\n{{Religious Zionism}}\n{{Zionism}}\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jews and Judaism}}\n{{Relpolnav}}\n\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism| ]]\n[[Category:Types of Zionism]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDress", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religious_Zionism"}
